summary: I specialize in automating and improving the efficiency of business systems and processes.  I learn my client's business and go over the ideas they have for areas to improve. These improvements can be made within the existing software and systems a business uses, or in some cases, creating new tools from the ground up.  I analyze and architect the solutions, which could be anything from a web-based portal to a mobile formatted web-app.  The solution is then designed and developed by me and my on-site team, all located in Orlando, FL. \n\nIf you have a need or interest in Streamlining Your Business Systems, please feel free to contact me.  For more information on what we do, check out our website: www.precisioninfinity.com\n\n@Recruiters: Feel free to connect to me on linked in, however, I'm not actively seeking new employment and do not wish to be passively recruited at this time.  If you do have a client that is not direct hire and can be billed through my company, please feel free to contact me.\n\nThe Technical Details about us: We use agile development practices with ASP.Net and/or SharePoint as the target platforms for our solutions. Our DevOps team is also versatile in maintaining and supporting Windows Server production environments, and Microsoft Azure Cloud Services.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2017.5 ~ now', u'description': u'I was part of American Society of Animal Science's complete website redesign. This project was implemented in Telerik (Progress)'s Sitefinity CMS. I experimented with using more of the web's latest frontend and backend technologies  by utilizing grunt and Sitefinity Feather. Sitefinity Feather allowed us to have a cleaner backend implementation with our custom widgets (using the MVC pattern) that also provided the additional benefit of improved performance. The frontend assets were provided as static HTML/CSS/JavaScript, for which I used grunt to compile the Sass (that I converted from CSS) and then minify (as well as the JavaScript). This projected turned out to be an enjoyable learning experience with a very maintainable result.', u'title': u'American Society of Animal Science'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2008.1 ~ 2008.1', u'description': u'BookMarshal\u2122 is a system created by Greg Smalter, now owned by Red Stapler Software. This system is used by book stores such as Yesterday's Muse Bookstore in Webster NY to store the thousands of items of inventory. Through this system book stores are able to export their inventory to be sold on many popular book-selling websites, including Amazon. This system also facilitates customer retention and marketing by storing customer and business profiles and associating information with them, such as books they're looking for and what has been sold to them in the past. Books can be associated with pictures of the actual item, which is also exported and on used on 3rd party eCommerce sites.', u'title': u'BookMarshal\u2122'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.1 ~ 2016.6', u'description': u'', u'title': u'EnduraCode Scheduling Engine'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.7 ~ now', u'description': u'I am the primary developer of the New York State eMOLST application for Excellus BlueCross Blueshield through Bross Group. Prominent contributions include developing features for the front end (ASP.NET, Sass, JavaScript, Backbone.js) and backend (Enterprise Web Library, ASP.NET). Through the development of this application I have advanced my skills of writing high-performance, maintainable, reliable software used by thousands of users in hospitals and health care facilities across the state.', u'title': u'New York State eMOLST'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.11 ~ 2013.11', u'description': u'I was one of the backend developers for this project on behalf of Fusion Productions. Specifically, I worked on the Gerber Bump, Gerber Grow, as well as other miscellaneous widgets. This application made heavy use of Sitefinity, ASP.NET MVC and Entity Framework. I implemented the input handling for the widgets, saved the data to persistent storage, and provided the front-end team with the data they required to draw the data.', u'title': u'My Gerber'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.11 ~ 2014.11', u'description': u'I was the lead developer for the redesign of the American Meat Science Association website at http://meatscience.org. This site was developed in Sitefinity and features custom widgets that are backed by custom content types, making it easier for content managers to provide structured data that is plugged into the design. I implemented the design of this site with Sass (Syntactically Awesome Style Sheets) which provided amazing support for tweaking the design later. Being the primary implementer of the design on this project greatly enhanced my skills for stylesheet maintainability and lead me to some discoveries that turned into blog posts: http://samrueby.com/2014/11/14/using-css-to-prevent-the-user-from-scrolling .', u'title': u'American Meat Science Association'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.4 ~ 2014.4', u'description': u'I had the privilege to contribute to the complete website redesign for Sigma Xi Scientific Research Society, with Fusion Productions. For this project (which is powered by Telerik\u2019s Sitefinity), I contributed in the following ways:\n\u2022\tImplemented designs, translating mockups to HTML and CSS.\n\u2022\tFully implemented several server-side controls which are used on the home page and throughout the entire website.\n\u2022\tImplemented client-side behaviors, such as dynamically loading of items and paginated blocks of information (which are dynamically set on the backend).\n\u2022\tImplemented custom backend interfaces in a manner that made it as easy as possible for the client to modify.\n\n', u'title': u'Sigma Xi Website Redesign'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.5 ~ 2012.5', u'description': u'I am primary developer of the Rochester RHIO Provider Portal through Bross Group. Written in Enterprise Web Library (ASP.NET) and backed by SQL Server, developing this application has taught lessons in maintainability and reliability. Thousands of users use this application daily to access information and perform tasks.', u'title': u'Rochester RHIO'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.5 ~ 2015.7', u'description': u'I was the lead developer for Project Management Institute's PMO Symposium 2015 website. With designs supplied by PMI, I implemented this responsive site using Sass, integrated into Telerik's Sitefinity CMS. This site features custom widgets that pull from structured data created using custom  Sitefinity modules, providing content managers with guided fields for adding content that fits the structure of the page while avoiding the need for scrupulous markup-editing. Working on this project fortified my Sass (Syntactically Awesome Style Sheets) skills that allow me to create projects with meaningful, maintainable styles.', u'title': u'PMI PMO Symposium 2015'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.4 ~ 2016.4', u'description': u'I implemented the Rochester RHIO's two public websites: http://grrhio.org and https://providerportal.grrhio.org. Both of these sites are implemented using ASP.NET MVC on IIS, utilizing RESTful web service calls to a Web API backend Content Management System. (Yes that's a lot of buzzwords, all completely accurate). I did not design these websites. Both website templates were provided to me by a designer with example content and I cut them up into MVC Views with content injected from our CMS, allowing the RHIO the power to easily modify their website's content with minimal risk of design degradation. This project was a fun experiment utilizing .NET async, Facebook's React.js, and for extra performance using bundling, minification and client/server caching.\n\n', u'title': u'Rochester RHIO Public Websites'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2012.8 ~ 2012.8', u'description': u'While taking the CECS 545 course at the University of Louisville, this is the very first project that the professor assigned and completed in one and a half week. Since, this project can be program in any programming languages, but I've decided to solve this problem in web forms.\n\nTraveling Salesperson Problem (TSP) was developed using ASP.net 4.0 framework in C#, HTML/CSS, JavaScript, and JQuery. The main purposes of this web application is to use Brute Force algorithm to to find the minimum cost solution to a Traveling Salesperson Problem.\n\nWhat is TSP? (See http://www.tsp.gatech.edu for more info)\n\nThe Brute Force algorithm is basically generating all possible tours and calculates the distances of each tour. Once figured out the distance of all possible tours and the shortest tour will be the best tour route.\n\nThere are four basic steps to solve the Travelling Salesperson Problem. Step 1 is to compute the total number of tours. Step 2 is to compute all the possible tours based on the number of cities. Step 3 is to compute the distance for each tour and finally step 4 is to get the best tour which is the shortest distance from all possible tours.\n\nCheck out the web app here:\nhttp://www.phibui.com/home/works/projects/TSP/Default.aspx', u'title': u'Traveling Salesperson Problem (TSP)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.8 ~ 2013.8', u'description': u'Implemented genetic algorithm to solve Quadratic Assignment Problem, and tried to improve it with Wisdom of Crowds approach. It was programmed in C# and XNA .NET 4.0 Framework. projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2012.8 ~ 2012.8', u'description': u'While taking the CECS 545 course at the University of Louisville, this is the very first project that the professor assigned and completed in one and a half week. Since, this project can be program in any programming languages, but I've decided to solve this problem in web forms.\n\nTraveling Salesperson Problem (TSP) was developed using ASP.net 4.0 framework in C#, HTML/CSS, JavaScript, and JQuery. The main purposes of this web application is to use Brute Force algorithm to to find the minimum cost solution to a Traveling Salesperson Problem.\n\nWhat is TSP? (See http://www.tsp.gatech.edu for more info)\n\nThe Brute Force algorithm is basically generating all possible tours and calculates the distances of each tour. Once figured out the distance of all possible tours and the shortest tour will be the best tour route.\n\nThere are four basic steps to solve the Travelling Salesperson Problem. Step 1 is to compute the total number of tours. Step 2 is to compute all the possible tours based on the number of cities. Step 3 is to compute the distance for each tour and finally step 4 is to get the best tour which is the shortest distance from all possible tours.\n\nCheck out the web app here:\nhttp://www.phibui.com/home/works/projects/TSP/Default.aspx', u'title': u'Traveling Salesperson Problem (TSP)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.8 ~ 2013.8', u'description': u'Implemented genetic algorithm to solve Quadratic Assignment Problem, and tried to improve it with Wisdom of Crowds approach. It was programmed in C# and XNA .NET 4.0 Framework. projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2012.1 ~ 2012.3', u'description': u'Fragment screening is a powerful tool for ligand discovery that is often complementary to traditional high-throughput screening. In a summary fragment screening is a process of throwing various compounds at an enzyme and recording the compounds that stick to the enzyme (recording the hits). \r\n\r\nSince the compounds being thrown at the enzyme are very small a sensitive method is needed to detect the hits. One of the most common fragment screening methods employs NMR (Nuclear Magnetic Resonance). This method is very effective but the downfall is that it can be slow. One way to go around it is with the process of pooling (poolsize 4-24). The bigger the poolsize the faster the NMR will run, however the bigger the poolsize the more time one has to spend deconvoluting the sample made from all the compounds based on the poolsize. \r\n\r\nThe whole process of fragment screening can approximately take up to 10 days or more. Process includes pooling of the data, making a sample tracking sheet, making run files for the Mitsubishi Electric RV-2SDB Robot, analyzing the data, identifying compounds for hit pools, deconvoluting the ones that have a hit, tracking individual samples and making new run files based on the individual samples. \r\n\r\nThe reason it takes so long is because there is a lot of manual labor involved. GLUE is an integration and automation of fragment screening. One push of a button can save hours and even days of work. It allows one to add pooled destinations to a master SDF file, add filenames to pre-pooled SDF file, create an output file that can be used as instrument input for peak detection, create run files for the automated sample handling, track the analysis of screening data and update the master SDF file, create an output file for follow-up of individual hits that can be used as instrument input for peak detection, and finally create run files for follow-up with automated sample handling.', u'title': u'GLUE (Integration and Automation of Fragment Screening)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.10 ~ 2011.12', u'description': u'Never before has the fate of so many lives been so influenced by one cryptographic machine, as in the Second World War. Enigma showed the importance of cryptography to military and civil intelligence. \r\n\r\nOur objective was to design the process of Enigma machine with assembly language for x86 processors. The bonus objective was to implement the program making it fancier once everything has been tested and was working properly. \r\n\r\nMy approach towards the project was to break down the process and understand the very basics of it. Then after modularizing the project prioritize it by deciding where to start and where to end. Lastly testing each component before moving along to make sure it was working perfectly. \r\n\r\nAfter breaking everything down I have realized that I have seven main components to work on: Three rotors along with the reflector, plug board, input panel and output panel. After that I started taking notes on separate components and making sure to notice any special cases, exceptions or errors that would need to be handled individually. One of the special cases I found had to do with the rotors, which after researching I have found was called the double-step. During that double-step there were special characters which moved the rotors with one single step and therefore would make the whole process more complicated. The special characters were \u201cV\u201d and \u201cE\u201d. Anytime the third rotor was on \u201cV\u201d the next time when it was rotated it would move the second rotor with a single step. Similarly when the second rotor was \u201cE\u201d the next time it was moved it would move the first rotor with a single step.\r\n\r\nMy partner came up with a great idea on integrating Caesar Cipher into the entire project which became our bonus objective. \r\n\r\nAfter exhausting hours in front of the computer screen, researching information and rewriting codes we were finally ready for our presentation. Everything went great and our program worked perfectly with no errors.\r\n', u'title': u'Translating Enigma Cipher Machine into Assembly Language'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.2 ~ 2012.5', u'description': u'This project was mainly focused on automating the process of dispensing and dilution of DMSO liquid samples. During the process one needed to perform multiple steps manually including 2D barcode scanning, capping/decapping of the plates, making sure there were no errors during the process, manually generating a Tecan worklist, repeating the same process for each plate individually. Altogether the process took approximately 2 hours.\r\n\r\nProject Aliquoter was an integration of the whole process described above into an Overlord workflow. There were 5 main steps in the project. First step was to get the required inputs which were the Mosaic control file and selection for defrosting the source plates. Second step was for validating the source plates and making sure every 1D rack barcode matched with the one in Mosaic control file. Third step had a conditional step so if defrosting was selected then workflow would validate the destination plates and defrost the source plates simultaneously otherwise it would only validate the destination plates. Fourth step was a decision algorithm which had to look at the current rack types and choose an appropriate solution or approach. Fifth step was the chosen approach itself \u2013 there were three ways of approaching the problem. \r\n\r\nThe reason there were multiple approaches is because of the fact that different plates had different requirements meaning some of them needed capping and some didn\u2019t. The current decapper (FluidX) that we had could only handle one rack at a time and therefore necessary measures needed to be taken \u2013 which is why we came up with different types of approaches/solutions.\r\n\r\nError checking was also automated and made easier for the user to detect anything before it got too late. After automating the process instead of taking 2 hours to finish up it only took 30 minutes. User only had to be there for 2 or 3 minutes just to set up the process. After the user started the process he or she could just walk away.', u'title': u'Project Aliquoter'}]

summary: Who am I?  I'm a programmer, an application developer, a geek.  I've found that when a person tries to put what they do into a nice box in tech, that is when they become irrelevant.  Tech is always changing and therefore there is something always new to play with and learn.  That is what I love.  So what do I use?  Everything I can, but always what is best for the end product or the user.  I use macOS, Linux and Windows.  I code in Java, C#, SQL, Swift, and a little Python.  I've used all sorts of technologies and frameworks.  I may not be a master of any one technology, but I can learn anything and therefore do anything.  I've found that no matter what the problem, it can be broken down into simple easy to understand components.  Once you've done that, you can make a complex, robust solution.  That is what I do.

summary: I am a IT specialist and developer in the Boston area.  Technology has been my passion since I was a a child, learning my first programming language (basic) well before my age turned into double digits.  Looking back, I've seen the industry change hundreds of times over and I am proud to say I am part of the life-cycle.\n\nI love both hardware and software and due to my extensive history, I can architect anything from a custom computer to a data center or a simple tool to an enterprise level application.  I strive to continuously learn, adapt, and teach.  I have had many great mentors and I consider myself to be one as well.  Tools are one of the basic ideas that differentiate intelligent life from that is considered basic, and that is exactly what I do; I create.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2014.4 ~ now', u'description': u'Financial services client in Plano, Texas wished to revamp their loan scenario application, which provided potential borrowers pricing information for a new loan or refinance.  The prior system was written as a desktop application with an access database and was difficult to install and maintain.  Each Loan Officer kept a copy of their database on their machine and there was no centralized database to pull reports. As the company began to grown troubleshooting and maintenance became incredibly taxing on the IT staff.  Program changes required a recompile and reinstall on each LO\u2019s computer.  Database changes were discouraged since each LO maintained a copy on their local machine.  This severely limited IT\u2019s ability to respond to new feature requests.\n\nDigiclarity assisted in the design, development, and implementation of Loan Scenario vNext and we transformed this system into a modern web application based on the .net platform.  Using WebAPI coupled with client side jQuery we were able to replicate the complex desktop functions onto a centralized web server for all employees.  Speed was critical in designing this application as the LO\u2019s were accustomed to using a desktop application, so page refreshes were out of the question.  We designed a solution with heavy emphasis on client side calculations to provide a fast and consistent experience.\n', u'title': u'Loan Origination Web App'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.7 ~ 2013.8', u'description': u'Revamp of ASP.NET webforms project to include additional enhancements and functionality. Significant amount of VB.NET code re-factoring and new development with C#.  Added DevExpress reporting component to deploy reports to all employees.  Also utilized jQuery for client side functions along with Bootstrap for CSS. \n\nSkills Used:\nASP.NET, VB.NET, C#, DevExpress Reporting, Entity Framework, T-SQL Development, Relational Data Modeling, jQuery, Bootstrap CSS', u'title': u'ASP.NET WebForms Revamp for City Government'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.2 ~ 2014.2', u'description': u'Tasked with improving performance of several SQL Server 2000 databases with limited hardware resources. Leveraged SQL indexes, query best practices, and database maintenance to significantly improve performance for Hilton\u2019s customers without an immediate hardware investment.\n\nCreated performance baseline for existing SQL Server architecture utilizing Performance Monitor, SQL Profiler, and Execution Plan analysis.\n\nIdentified poorly performing queries via high duration and CPU usage counters. Evaluated queries in depth and made recommendations to improve performance by modifying indexes and enabling \u2018sargable\u2019 query conditions.\n\nSkills Used:\nDBA, SQL Tuning, SQL Indexes, SQL Trace Profiling, Performance Monitoring, T-SQL Development, Stored Procedure Review', u'title': u'Hilton Worldwide - SQL Performance Analysis'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.9 ~ 2013.9', u'description': u'Client seeking solution to assinging document to a specific document type in a parent child relationship.  Certain types need to be excluded based upon which Laserfiche template is selected.  Developed Laserfiche settings database to store the properties and business rules with a XAML front end.  Client is able to assign specific document group types to a specific template as well as adding new types and documents.\n\nSkills Used:\nSQL Relational Data Modeling, Laserfiche, Laserfiche Dynamic Templates, XAML, C#', u'title': u'Laserfiche App For Custom Template and Field Management'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.5 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'Tasked with upgrading an entire suite of legacy VB6 applications to modern .NET technology.  Utilized C# with WPF and MVVM frameworks to create new applications with expanded functionality.  Also utilized ASP.NET for web application development along with jQuery for SPA functions. Client experienced a reduction of time spent with end users for application deployment tasks, improvement with the user experience of installing applications, and reduction in overall application maintenance. \n\nSkills & Technology Used:\nVB6, C#, WPF, MVVM, IoC, .net, DevExpress, ASP.NET, jQuery, Bootstrap CSS', u'title': u'VB6 Application Conversion to C# WPF MVVM & ASP.NET'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.8 ~ 2013.8', u'description': u'Developed custom PowerShell scripts to populate Active Directory user properties from PeopleSoft databases. Utilized System Center Orchestrator to schedule the tasks and log events during the process. This resulted in a centralized repository of verified employee information.\n\nDeveloped PowerShell script to retrieve updates from System Center and deploy them on their scheduled date. This reduced complexity when scheduling the update run books in SCORCH.\n\nSkills Used:\nHyper-V 2012, PowerShell Scripting, System Center Configuration Manager, System Center Orchestrator, Runbooks, T-SQL Programming', u'title': u'NTTA - PowerShell Scripting & SCCM'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.11 ~ 2013.2', u'description': u'Implemented Laserfiche content management system for mortgage servicing client. The new system allowed employees to search for borrower documentation across all client locations. Reduced time and cost associated with processing borrower files which provided a faster close for their clients.\n\nCreated Laserfiche Workflows to route specific borrower document types across the organization. This provided a structured framework for placing documents into the content management system.\n\nEstablished tight system integration to support content management system. Integrated with as400, SQL Server, and LDAP. Built custom LDAP authentication modules in C#. This reduced the amount data entry and provided consistency across all applications.\n\nSkills Used:\nLaserfiche, Laserfiche Workflow, SQL Server 2008 R2, C#, vb.net, T-SQL Programming, SQL Indexes', u'title': u'Laserfiche Paper to Digital Loan Documentation Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.12 ~ 2013.12', u'description': u'Developed pricing tool to reduce the amount of time needed for staff to develop cost analysis projections when creating client bids. Utilized geospatial data coupled with pricing information to provide client the ability to obtain pricing information across the country.\n\nSkills Used:\nC#, MVVM, WPF, Entity Framework, SQL Server 2008 R2, Fact & Dimensional Modeling, SQL Index tuning, Haversine Distance Formula, Geospatial Data', u'title': u'Vendor Pricing App'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.7 ~ 2013.7', u'description': u'Deployed SharePoint 2013 along with SQL Server 2012 and Windows Server 2012.  Designed PowerPivot reports and implemented online with Excel Services.  ', u'title': u'SharePoint 2013 Deployment with Microsoft BI'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.8 ~ 2014.8', u'description': u'\uf0a7\tCity of Rowlett needed a solution to track employee enrollment in their annual Health and Wellness program. summary: Iris Classon is an appreciated speaker, writer, blogger, Microsoft C# MVP and member of MEET (Microsoft Extended Experts Team) with a tremendous passion for programming. Iris is hostess on the Get Up and Code! podcast, and on her spare time she does pro-bono work as a dietitian and is very engaged in the developer community. She also enjoys extreme sports such as barefoot running, mountain biking, weightlifting and scuba diving- and of course traveling.

', u'title': u'Fulcrum Consulting L.L.C Official Website'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.6 ~ 2015.6', u'description': u'Crop management applications extensions and services for the agriculture industry.a software provides powerful tools for managing agronomic crop production data.', u'title': u'AgStudio\u2122 Services'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.7 ~ 2015.8', u'description': u'Utilized Amazon cloud services AWS S3 and SQS to implement a fully featured background processing to support Pioneer Encirca Services.', u'title': u'Pioneer S3 & SQS Processing'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.1 ~ now', u'description': u'The ESB is implemented in software that operates between the business applications, and enables communication among them. Ideally, the ESB should be able to replace all direct contact with the applications on the bus, so that all communication takes place via the ESB. To achieve this objective, the ESB must encapsulate the functionality offered by its component applications in a meaningful way. This typically occurs through the use of an enterprise message model. The message model defines a standard set of messages that the ESB transmits and receives. When the ESB receives a message, it routes the message to the appropriate application. Often, because that application evolved without the same message model, the ESB has to transform the message into a format that the application can interpret. A software adapter fulfills the task of effecting these transformations, analogously to a physical adapter.', u'title': u'Enterprise Service Bus'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.3 ~ 2015.3', u'description': u'Provided support and bug fixes to the automation WCF services in addition to analyzing the database interactions with the service through the Entity framework platform.', u'title': u'Automation Services'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.6 ~ 2015.6', u'description': u'Rule engine software is commonly provided as a component of a business rule management system which, among other functions, provides the ability to: register, define, classify, and manage all the rules, verify consistency of rules definitions (\u201dGold-level customers are eligible for free shipping when order quantity > 10\u201d and \u201cmaximum order quantity for Silver-level customers = 15\u201d ), define the relationships between different rules, and relate some of these rules to IT applications that are affected or need to enforce one or more of the rules.', u'title': u'Dynamic Business Rules Engine Core'}]

Includes a stack reconstruction script, an extension for tracing various leaks, and others.', u'title': u'WinDbg Extensions'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2009 ~ 2009', u'description': u'Managed helper APIs for User Account Control (Vista+), including launching a process as administrator, querying for whether UAC is enabled, obtaining the linked administrator token, and other features.', u'title': u'User Account Control Helpers'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2009 ~ 2009', u'description': u'A WinDbg extension for executing WCT (Wait Chain Traversal) on a live system for a single thread, a single process, or all processes. This tool aids in deadlock detection on live systems.', u'title': u'Wait Chain Traversal WinDbg Extension'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2008 ~ 2008', u'description': u'A CLR host for managed applications that uses non-paged memory for the garbage-collected heap. This can improve performance on systems that have aggressive working set trimming or other (less important) applications competing for physical memory.', u'title': u'Non-Paged CLR Host'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011 ~ 2011', u'description': u'An application for browsing stacks of arbitrary .NET processes, with support for CLR 2.0 and CLR 4.0.', u'title': u'CLR Stack Explorer'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.7 ~ now', u'description': u'(For a more detailed description, visit the project README and Wiki.)\n\nThis project provides a command-line environment a-la WinDbg for executing SOS commands without having SOS available. It is based on the ClrMD library that is essentially a managed replacement for SOS.\n\nYou should use this project when you don't have SOS available, or when you want a quick alternative to firing up WinDbg and locating SOS. One such situation is when debugging dumps from Windows Phone devices; Microsoft does not make the Windows Phone CoreCLR SOS publicly available at present. What's more, some msos commands already offer more information than their SOS counterparts. Especially cool is the !hq command, which compiles an arbitrary dynamic query over heap objects and classes.', u'title': u'msos -- Command-Line Debugging and Analysis Environment for .NET Applications'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2015.6 ~ 2015.6', u'description': u'This work was associated with a UnitZ framework and requires to move it from Unity Networking to the Photon Cloud framework. The were a lot of problems because the Unity Networking realization was based on a HUGE bunch of the RPC calls. It is not too bad for LAN (actually it is still a bad architecture), but not work well when client and server in \u0435\u0440\u0443 different subnets of even world parts. \nBesides that I came up with a technology that allows to decrease network packets to zero and use OnPhotonSerializeView method at the same time :)', u'title': u'PhotonCloud integrating'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.3 ~ 2015.3', u'description': u'ShooterAI framework has its own IK solution, but it did not work properly with third-party human model and it required to replace already integrated IK logics with FinalIK which has more settings right out of box. For example it has targets that allow fix up wrong bone rotation.', u'title': u'ShooterAI and FinalIK integration'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.4 ~ 2015.4', u'description': u'The work was associated with UnitZ framework. It requires to optimize this framework for Mobile device. After optimization FPS rises from 8 to 45 in CIty (the most complex map location) on Samsung Galaxy S3. Threre were these main steps:\n* New mobile shader (simple enough)\n* Modification of the spawners activity\n* Change Day/Night Light algorithm\n* Optimization for shadow casting / receiving \n* Changing of car object far-light behavior\nand more', u'title': u'Mobile Game Optimization'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.11 ~ now', u'description': u'Multi-player car racing simulator based on Unity3D and Photon Server. Live test-drive: \nCity http://mehanos.ru/game?mtid=1\nHarbour http://mehanos.ru/game?mtid=25\nWinter Lake http://mehanos.ru/game?mtid=17\nEstoril http://mehanos.ru/game?mtid=2\nIsland http://mehanos.ru/game?mtid=15\nand much more http://mehanos.ru', u'title': u'Mehanos'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.2 ~ 2015.2', u'description': u'As a VoIP solution it allows gamers to speak to each other in a game.\nTo solve this task I used DFVoice (https://www.assetstore.unity3d.com/en/#!/content/19344) and Photon Chat system (https://www.assetstore.unity3d.com/en/#!/content/1786), as far as I know I was the first who used Photon Chat to transmit VoIP information :) This system was tested successfully on Android, WebPlayer, PC.', u'title': u'VoIP solution for Unity3D'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.8 ~ 2013.8', u'description': u'Small presentation with screen-shots and videos for Android tower defense game \nhttp://cv.mehanos.ru/rb/', u'title': u'RedButton - Tower Defense (Android)'}]

', u'title': u'A Debugger for the GLSuite6 Rule Engine'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.10 ~ 2013.10', u'description': u'Create a client-side button container that holds buttons. summary: I am the Manager of Redheeler Software LLC.   I am currently working on upgrading a Website for a client. The Website does testing.  Work is in C#, ASP.NET, JavaScript and TSQL. The previous project for a different client involved building a plugin for their product in C# that can communicate with mainframes.  Previously I built 3d workstation software in partnership with Nimble Development Inc. here in Bend. This is a native C++ project for Windows.  I am worked with Polygonica Solid Modeling API which is a 3d mesh API and integrating it in a viewer that uses Hoops by SoftTech 3D.   A second project is to integrate an off the shelf multi-platform job  scheduling system with zOS under contract with the scheduler's manufacturer.\n\nRedheeler Software also develops software products, which are currently in progress.\n\nI am an expert level programmer with lots of experience in C, C++, Java, C#, VB.NET, TSQL, JavaScript, and assembly. I have a background in mathematics and science including mathematical statistics. I use an object oriented approach to design that emphasizes information hiding. I put software engineering best practices into place when I am in a leadership role. As a manager I experience very little turnover among the people that I hire. I have a lot of online retailing experience and understand retail business processes.  I own Redheeler Software LLC a software development and consulting company.

summary: I am a huge people-person and spent several years in Software Engineering, Web Development, Branding and Product Management, but a few years ago a serendipitous event inspired me to get into Cyber Security, and I love it! There is nothing greater than finding Vulnerabilities and Malware for smart companies and individuals to do awesome things, and it's a fantastic process that I feel lucky to integrate my IT skills with cyber security.\n\nWhen I'm not working, I usually research about different countries and about their lifestyle, cuisines, tourist attractions and their native language. summary: Over 16 years of developing web applications. Using the latest web trends and innovative technologies to deliver high quality, robust websites for many worldwide companies. This is accomplished by using the Software Development Cycle (SDLC). From conception to release, deliverables are methodically planned, documented, developed and tested to meet the project’s needs and requirements.\n\nOver 10 years of using Agile methodologies like SCRUM, Pairing and Extreme Programming. The teams and projects have demanded anywhere from 2 to 4 week sprints. Used stories and tasks to manage the life cycle of a sprint. Also, incorporated automated builds and testing for an integrated build solution that would release builds to each environment (Dev, Staging and Production). Technologies used are MSBuild, Cruise Control, Visual Studio, Windows Scripting Host, iSQL, oSQL and Jenkins.\n\nOver 16 years of utilizing the language JavaScript, for both front-end and server-side code. Can create front-end components to easily access and maintain. Combined with JQuery, JSON, HTML, DHTML, XML, XSLT, XPATH and AJAX, my front-end code offers easy-to-use APIs and tight security.\n\nOver 3 years of using JavaScript libraries like Dojo, jQuery, Backbone.js and Angular.js to deliver customizable widgets for business applications. My experience has been able to offer innovative solutions by combining the .Net framework with Web Services, SOAP, RESTful APIs and AJAX calls to deliver scalable solutions for high traffic web applications.\n\nOver 16 years of Single Page Web Application experience. Before the buzzwords “ajax”, “responsive”, and “web 2.0” were coined, my code delivered solutions that would update web page and database content dynamically without page reloads.

summary: E.J. Ajax & Sons provides innovative metal-forming solutions for customers in architecture, appliance manufacturing, kinetic engineering, transportation and a range of other industries. Our mission is to delivery every part on time and to print.\nOur value-added approach to metal stamping and fabrication creates long-lasting relationships with our customers and vendors. \n\nWe are a globally competitive company, exporting more than a third of our total production to China, Saudi Arabia, Mexico and Western Europe.\n\nOur quality and productivity are enabled by a highly trained and diverse team. We invest 5.5 percent of payroll each year in on-going training. A print and a quick phone call are usually all we need to provide a quote.\n\nCapabilities:\n\nStamping\nShort production runs, rapid prototyping, and precision stampings from any type of metal or alloy are our specialties. Our extensive library of tools helps reduce start-up costs. \n\nProgressive Stamping \nWe provide progressive metal stamping services for cost-effective production of complex components in multiple stages. Our multi-station presses range from 30 tons to 200 tons.\n\nDeep Draw Stamping\nWe have earned a reputation for producing deep drawn components from steel, aluminum, brass and copper with tight tolerances in industries such as commercial construction and home appliance. \n\nSheet Metal Forming \nWe are one of North America’s premium suppliers of precision sheet metal casings to the HVAC and heat exchanger industry for the past 50 years. Our turret presses, lasers, and press brakes can fabricate critical sheet metal parts, such as header and end plates with precision extrusions. \n\nPress Brake Forming \nOur multi axis CNC press brakes allow us to provide complex compound angle forms. \n\nTurret Press Punching\nWe manufacture parts with tight tolerances to required dimensions, eliminating secondary operations, which translates into cost and time savings for our customers.\n\nSpecialties: Surface critical stainless, carbon and red metal stampings,  Progressive in-die assembly and tapping, supply chain management.

Ajax Hotel is a 4 star hotel located  near the center of Limassol and the sea front. It is also near to the most prestigious shopping street in Limassol, the Archaeological museum, the Old city and the Medieval Castle. Ajax Hotel also, has direct access to the charming villages, the two airports and the wineries. The Ajax Hotel is well-known for its high quality accommodation and personal service. It recently had a renovation in order to upgrade its service and facilities to full quality standards.\n\nThe Ajax Hotel has 176 guestrooms that are featured with many amenities such as air-condition, direct dial phones, television with satellite channels, mini bars, coffee and tea making facilities, Free internet access, fully equipped bathrooms with hair dryers, bathtubs and bathroom accessories. All guestrooms have their own private balconies for overlooking the pool or the hotel garden. In addition, the hotel has an indoor heated swimming pool, an outdoor swimming pool along with a Jacuzzi, a health club, a fitness center and sauna. It also features massages, beauty services and body & face treatments. Dining at the Ajax Hotel is a fantastic experience as guests have two amazing restaurant choices that both of them offer local and International cuisine. Firstly, there is the Priamos Restaurant with its gastronomic cuisine. Then, there is the Ekavi Restaurant where guests can dine all day as breakfast, lunch and dinner is served. Guests also have the choice of the indoor and outdoor bars of Ajax Hotel. The Ulysses Bar and the Poseidon Snack and Pool Bar are available for enjoying drinks and snacks. The hotel also provides facilities for conferences such as modern equipment, projectors, and professional technical support.

summary: From my blog:\nDave is a software architect and developer specializing in Microsoft .Net and related technologies. Having worked  with Fortune 100, 500 and 1000 companies, architecting and building award winning applications  in the fields of healthcare, insurance, finance, education, medicine,  and government, Dave brings over 20 years experience to the field. He has been a Microsoft Certified Professional since 1999.\n\nOne of the applications he designed increased sales for the Personal Lines Division of a major insurer by 500% in its first year and also reduced insurance application errors by 500%. The application paid for itself in 3 months, winning Dave and his team, the “Best of Blues” award. Having been a business owner for many years, Dave understands the “bottom line”, and brings his unique approach of “Just Enough Technology” to every customer, no matter how large or small the company.\n\nTechnology is Dave’s passion, and teaching it his glory. Since 1999, Dave has taught dozens of seminars on a wide range of technical subjects. He was the primary speaker at Developer Guild seminars held at the Latanze Center at Loyola University in Baltimore, MD.  At the Association of IT Professionals 50th anniversary conference, Dave had the honor of being the featured .Net speaker.\n\nSpecialties: Web Application Architecture and Development

summary: I work for Umbraco, a wonderful open source CMS built on ASP.NET.  I've been on the Umbraco core development team since 2009 and I am fortunate enough to be working on this great product full time since 2011. For the 5 years previous to starting at Umbraco HQ, I worked as the Technical Director for The FARM Digital in Sydney, Australia. \n\nI have a passion for development, it's one of my favorite things to do. I've been developing software since I was a teenager when the Internet was in it's infancy and have been specializing in web development since I completed college in 2001. I've been working in the .NET OSS community for a long time now and have several of my own popular OSS projects in active development, these are all hosted on my GitHub account.\n\nApart from developing I love to surf, travel, relax and generally just like to hang out with good friends.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2011.10 ~ 2012.2', u'description': u'You should place Kinect devices on the locations you want to secure and keep it connected to a high end PC capable enough to do a video encoding and up streaming. The Kinect devices will be run by a WPF application running on the PC which will look for any human intrusion. While there is no human intrusion, it will remain in \u201cPatrol Mode\u201d where it will upload pictures of its view on regular intervals to Windows Azure. These pictures can be monitored at any point of time through the application running on Windows Phone and Windows 8. Whenever there is an human intrusion detected the Kinect changes itself to \u201cIntrusion Mode\u201d; it then alerts Windows Azure and also starts streaming the video to the Smooth Streaming Server hosted on Windows Azure. The Azure notifies all the devices subscribed (Windows Phone / Windows 8 ) using a toast and will allow those application to view the live streaming. From your Windows Phone / Windows 8 app you can also control the Kinect device.', u'title': u'Home Security System Using Kinect, Azure, Windows Phone and Windows 8'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.8 ~ 2013.8', u'description': u'The Kinect Status Notifier, will pops up a notification in system tray whenever this changes in sensor status.', u'title': u'Kinect Status Notifer'}]

summary: Development Consultant, Solution Development Lead, Technical Advisor, Pre Sales SME with more than 10 years of experience in the IT industry with expertise in Development, Engineering, Consulting and Services Delivery on Microsoft technologies.  Associated with Microsoft over 7 years and held different roles in Delivery, Development, Presales.\n\nAs Development Lead, managed several complex projects and delivered solutions to enterprise customers across USA, LATAM and EMEA with high customer satisfaction. In the present role, he is Incubating delivery model for Emerging Capabilities, as well as working on different connected scenarios with HoloLens, Azure and Mobility. \n\nHe is a former Microsoft MVP (Most Valuable Professional), Code Project MVP, Insider, Mentor, Speaker of various Microsoft Events including Tech Ready, Tech Ed India, Azure Camp, Web Camps etc. and an avid blogger. summary: Scott Addie is an avid blogger, a Telerik Developer Network author, and a technical evangelist of the modern web. Scott has reached masses of developers through blog posts, articles, and speaking engagements at user groups, code camps, and conferences across the globe. With a strong emphasis on JavaScript and the Microsoft web technology stack, Scott holds numerous industry-recognized Microsoft development certifications and has been named a Microsoft MVP twice in the award category of Visual Studio and Development Technologies. His thought leadership in the .NET community has also earned him a seat in the Telerik Developer Experts program. As a firm believer in giving back to the community, Scott is a frequent open source contributor to high-profile GitHub projects in the Microsoft developer ecosystem. In his day job as a blue badge, Scott produces ASP.NET Core content for docs.microsoft.com.

summary: I consider myself as experienced software developer and architect on Microsoft .NET and SharePoint platforms. I grew up with computers and programming and during my school years programming got my passion. I love to work on challenging projects, face complexities and solve complex business and technical problems trying to find best balance between business needs and technologies. As playing with technology is my main hobby then over years I have worked on different tools and platforms and seen many technologies coming, going and staying.  I am also active in technical communities as speaker and blogger. My community activities are also recognized by Microsoft through MVP title I'm holding since 2008.\n\nCurrently I'm running my project company that targets ASP.NET and SharePoint projects. I work together with carefully selected professionals. We have well functioning international team and currently we are covering western and northern markets in Europe. Core members of our teams are carefully selected professionals who are open minded and able to learn and innovate.\n\nContact me if you are looking for strong software development partner: me@gunnarpeipman.com\n\nMy skills:\n- Development on .NET, ASP.NET, ASP.NET MVC, SharePoint and Windows Azure\n- Strong on technical design and architecture\n- Building web based system, web services and middleware services\n- Languages: C#, VB.NET, JavaScript, PHP, T-SQL, ASP\n- Software projects planning and management\n- Strong working discipline, good in communication, strong experiences with remote projects\n- Working on field 15+ years in challenging and complex projects\n\nMost important achievements:\n- Microsoft ASP.NET/IIS MVP since 2008\n- DZone MVB

summary: As an early adopter of OOP techniques, I started out developing client-server applications using cutting edge technology. I also had a vocation as a teacher, and have been teaching and coaching since the start of my career. During my many years of experience in development of back office tools, end user applications and solutions - mainly with Microsoft development tools - I have evolved with the latest technology, and I am now working in the .NET environment.\nOver the years, I've developed a pragmatic and eclectic style of analysis and programming, picking the right techniques for the right circumstances, while keeping an open mind for new insights.\nThrough my contacts with hundreds of professionals, as a teacher and as a programmer, I have obtained quite some insight in the mindset of a typical professional programmer, analyst, or manager, and in the workings of many IT-departments.\n\nSpecialties: WinForms, Visual Studio.Net 2005, VB.Net, C#, SQLServer 2005 and TRANSACT SQL, ORACLE 10g and PL/SQL, Visual SourceSafe, Team Foundation Server, Crystal Reports

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2017.1 ~ 2017.3', u'description': u'Creating another conversion application, based on the framework of the earlier developed Subcontractor Exchange project. \n\nThis project will convert all incoming transport order file/message types to a Fritom standard format and store this in the main Fritom repository. It also has the capability to convert the Fritom standard format to several message formats which will be read by a TMS.', u'title': u'Fritom - Transport Order Convertor'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2016.6', u'description': u'The security agents of I-Sec are scheduled for their shifts using an application called OPA. This application has been created several years ago and is in need of some upgrades. \nMy task in this project was to act as the spokesmen and team lead for the improvements of the application and making sure the correct features are being implemented.\nWe've also made sure the deployments are professionalized using continuous integration and continuous deployments.\nKeywords are: .NET 4.5, C#, SQL Server, performance, team lead, managing, analysis, Teamcity, Octopus Deploy, Git, off-shored team', u'title': u'I-Sec - OPA'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.7 ~ 2016.9', u'description': u'The current Lasaulec webshop is in need of an update. This new version of the website is being used in Belgium for a couple of months. Belgium is a relative new market for Lasaulec, therefore it's an ideal location to launch this new website. During this time the Lasaulec Webshop team is fixing the bugs, creating functionality which was overlooked or postponed. Once this backlog is cleared, the website will also be placed in the production environment for the Netherlands.\nThe new Webshop consists of multiple micro-services, most of them deployed on (several) Amazon virtual machines.\nKeywords are: .NET 4.6, C#, Amazon, AWS, Elasticsearch, Cassandra, jQuery, Teamcity, Octopus Deploy, Git, micro services, ASP.NET MVC, ASP.NET Web API, NUnit', u'title': u'Lasaulec - Webshop'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.1 ~ 2016.6', u'description': u'The company was in need of a new application which enables the managers and supervisors to check the location of security agents, what their status is, communicate with each other and provide an easy to use interface to manage the personnel. An earlier attempt to create such a piece of software has failed as it doesn't meet the business requirements. \nAll of the information has to be presented in a real time fashion and is dependent on several external systems. The front end and back end also has to be composable per airport as the application will be deployed all over the world and we want to minimize the development effort necessary per local deployment.\n\nMy task in this project was to determine what the functional- and technical requirements, assemble the development team (off shored), design the solution- & software-architecture and guide the team throughout the iterations. \nKeywords are: .NET Core 1.0, C#, Azure, Azure Service Fabric, micro services, architecture, design, AngularJS, Cordova, iOS, Bootstrap, Teamcity, Octopus Deploy, Git, off-shored team, team lead, integration', u'title': u'I-Sec - SARA'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.10 ~ 2016.10', u'description': u'Investigating the reason behind the slow performance of the current, internal, TMS Online application. After having created the reports, creating a plan on how to improve this on the short term and creating a plan to upgrade this a modern web application.\nWhile working on this project coaching and training the other team members to learn how to set up a project and work with the latest development techniques which are useful and available for this project.\n\nKeywords: ASP.NET WebForms, MS SQL Server, Autofac, WCF, Entity Framework, Web API, jQuery, AngularJS, Typescript, architecture, software design', u'title': u'Fritom - TMS Online'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.9 ~ 2016.3', u'description': u'We have created a device to be used on an airport which is able to do security checks for high risk flights. This device will make the security checks more efficient so passengers can get through it faster without sacrificing the security.\nThe application on the device is able to do several important bio-metric scans and with this information it determines if a passenger is a potential risk for the specific flight. All of this is presented in a user friendly manner with a nice kiosk standing at the airport connected to a touch screen monitor for the passenger & an iPad for the security agents to check on the progress of the scan.\nAll of the information is shown real time to the passenger and security agent.\n\nKeywords are: .NET 4.5, C#, Reactive Extensions, RavenDB, XSockets, AngularJS, Bootstrap, NUnit, Teamcity, Octopus Deploy, Git, team lead, off-shored team', u'title': u'I-Sec - B-APS'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.11 ~ 2017.3', u'description': u'The main goal of this project is to receive and send messages from several subcontractors and send them to other subcontractors. These subcontractors all have different formats for the same type of file, so we had to create a mapping application. \nThis application picks up the received message files, converts them to a standardized Fritom XML format, stores it in the database. When a message is succesfully processed within the Fritom ecosystem, the message will be converted to a different format, depending on the receiving subcontractor.\nAll of this has to be implemented in the current Fritom ecosystem, which consists of Windows Server machines and SQL Server. Preferably no other technologies should be introduced due to maintenance and knowledge of the current DevOps team.\nKeywords are: .NET 4.6, Autofac, MEF, SQL Server, Entity Framework, AutoMapper, testing, software design, coaching, education, design patterns, message queue', u'title': u'Fritom - SubcontractorExchange'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.10 ~ 2016.10', u'description': u'Fri300 - Upgrade Bing Maps\nThis fleet tracking application is used throughout the company for gaining insight of the trucks and trailers. It was using an old version of Bing Maps (6.3) which is being turned off any time soon.\nThis project involved upgrading the Bing Maps component to the latest version (8) and making sure this component can easily be switched by some other component in the future.\nKeywords: .NET 3.5, Bing Maps, TypeScript, Autofac, Dependency Injection, unit-testing', u'title': u'Fritom - Fri300 Maps upgrade'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.3 ~ now', u'description': u'Being part of the SnelStart web development team.\nThis team is responsible for creating, maintaining and improving the web application of the SnelStart accounting software.\n\nKeywords: Azure, SQL, Entity Framework, Unity, Angular, TypeScript, C#', u'title': u'SnelStart - Web application'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.9 ~ 2015.9', u'description': u'For this project we had to migrate the existing on-premise software to a cloud platform in order to give the international customers a better product experience. We have chosen to use the Microsoft Azure cloud platform due to the existing knowledge of the development team and all the features provided by the platform. \nIn order to deploy the existing software in multiple regions and continents, there had to be made quite a lot of changes. My job on this project was to analyze the current software solution, gathering requirements from stakeholders, create and design a new cloud architecture for the existing software and acting as the lead developer on the project.\nThe biggest in this project was making sure all the customers' data was stored in a location nearby, for low latency. In order to satisfy this requirement we started using the Microsoft Elastic Scale libraries (since version 0.7) with SQL Azure databases. This way we were able to create different shards with customer data in several parts of the world, therefore having the data nearby the customers' location at all times. Using these libraries also made sure the current development team can maintain the software with ease.\nApart from the changes in the software design, some changes in the deployment methods were necessary also. First I made sure a continuous integration build was triggered on each commit and we started creating integration- and unit-tests. Next goal was setting up a continuous deployment solution. For this, we started using Octopus Deploy. I've created several projects in this product to make sure our complete Azure solution (as described in the architecture designs) could be deployed at every time of the day without any downtime and manual intervention.\nKeywords: Azure, .NET 4.5, MVC, SQL, Elastic Scale, sharding, Autofac, TDD, architecture, design, documentation, Octopus Deploy, Teamcity, PowerShell', u'title': u'Cross Point - Migration to the cloud'}]
summary: Jan has been developing software for well over a decade. In the past couple of years he has helped out multiple customers with several projects in a role of a solution architect/developer. His main focus is developing highly performant and scalable solutions using the great services provided by the Microsoft Azure platform.\n\nHe's always trying to keep up with the latest and greatest services Azure has to offer which enables him to use them in real-life projects whenever necessary. \nWhenever Jan finds something interesting to write about, he shares his findings on either his personal blog (https://jan-v.nl) or the 4DotNet blog (https://blogs.4dotnet.nl).

He helps conscious professionals achieve greater levels of performance and success by teaching them how to integrate the intelligence of their minds with the intuitive intelligence of their hearts. The way he does this is by teaching a powerful system of heart-mind-body integration called ‘Heart Intelligence’ that, when fully embodied, gives you access to greater levels of performance, creativity, and higher order thinking.\n\nGabriel’s gift is in working with men and women who have forgotten how courageous and powerful they are, or who need to tap deeper into their inner source of heart-based power than ever before, for the challenges they are facing next. projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2008.10 ~ now', u'description': u'Zeitgeist is an activity logging framework for user activities and events (file usage, browser history, conversations, etc). Its goal is to enable applications to enhance their user interface through contextual information, as well as enabling new desktop paradigms (by analyzing usage patterns, etc).\n\nZeitgeist has been successfully deployed in Ubuntu and powers the document search feature in Unity. It is thus being used on millions of end-user systems.\n\nThe main engine code is written in Vala, and client libraries for C, Vala and Python are available. Several data-sources (plugins for applications to send information to the engine) are also provided. projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2006.10 ~ 2006.10', u'description': u'This team is made up of those who have achieved membership of the Ubuntu Iranian Team.', u'title': u'Ubuntu Iranian LoCo Team'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015 ~ now', u'description': u'Role: Lead Frontend Developer\nTechnologies: Polymer, JavaScript, HTML5, D3\n\nData Analyser was an advanced automated data analysis system designed to monitor and analyze the behavior of networks to detect and catch computer viruses, worms, trojans, adware, spyware, and other network security related threats in a fully automated mode. \nSince I had a good understanding of how computer networks work and already have studied machine learning algorithms and was hands-on on statistical analysis tools like R and Matlab, I have been chosen as the head and leader of the GUI team because of my strong background in GUI development. \nI was responsible for designing and developing SPA (Single Page Application) front-end for modeling and visualizing the given data which were fed from several sources and different technologies such as Elasticsearch, InfluxDb, Gephi, etc. \nI implemented many charts using D3.js and Sigma.js libraries. Besides, the Data Analyser was also responsible for configuring and visualizing the result of a Correlation and NBA (Network Behavior Analysis) engine cores too. \nWe created an interactive interface to provide a comprehensive analyzing tool to detect threats and attacks, visualize them and send alarms to network administrators via SMS and email. summary: I'm a long time Open Source user and contributor currently mostly involved in the Edubuntu project, Ubuntu itself and LTSP.\n\nI'm the current maintainer of LTSP in Ubuntu, one of the main contributors to Edubuntu and an upstream developer of LTSP as well as project leader of LTSP-Cluster.\n\nMy interests range from increasing the use of open source technologies in education to increasing security of computer systems using containers (LXC in particular).\n\nI consider myself an hybrid between system administrator and developer. Having extensive experience in networking (BGP, IPSEC, IPV6, recently working with Vyatta) but also a good knowledge of scripting languages (Python being my preference) and decent knowledge of C and C++.\n\nI enjoy working with the Open Source community, helping create a community around a new or an existing project and help it grow to a point where the community can manage the project on its own.\n\nSpecialties: Ubuntu, Open Source, community liaison, thin clients, computer networking, ltsp

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2014.8 ~ 2014.12', u'description': u'This was a one semester senior project that focused primarily on Programming knowledge and skills, along with some hardware implementation.  There was also an IoT component.  Keywords: Python, REST, Open Source,  MIT AppInventor 2, Hardware, Raspberry Pi GPIO, Internet of Things, WebIOPi, Linux ****\n\nIn this project, the team starting in the typical fashion of learning how to use the Raspberry Pi GPIO to affect the outside world.  Then, they constructed the robotic vehicle and made the appropriate hardware connections with the Pi.  The remainder of the semester focused on the team implementing various 'application layer vehicular control practices' to control the vehicle in diverse ways.  They are listed below.  \n\n\u2022  Keyboard control program in Python that ran via command line\n\u2022  Wii Remote Control Code where Wii Remote connected directly to Bluetooth adapter on the Pi\n\u2022  Installing WebIOPi - The Raspberry Pi Internet of Things Framework on the Pi and using it in the following fashions \n**Creating AppInventor Android App that acted as a REST client that used the WebIOPi GPIO REST endpoint functionality to control the vehicle via the App\n**Using a second Raspberry Pi to communicate with the Wii Remote.  The Wii code on the 'new' Pi sent REST requests to the original Pi connected to the vehicle running the WebIOPI REST server in order to control it.  This solution significantly increased the transmission range of the Wii Remote to control the vehicle.    \n\n', u'title': u'Raspberry Pi Enabled PiTank Robot: Emphasizing a Variety of Control Applications'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.1 ~ 2015.5', u'description': u'This was a one semester senior project that focused primarily on IT knowledge and skills.  Keywords: Python, REST Client, Python MatPlotLib Library, Open Source, JSON, Data Visualization, Data Analysis, Python Request Library, Ubuntu Linux ****\n\nThis team discovered that on the NCAA website, JSON is also returned when viewing box scores for college athletics via a web browser.  As a result, this project involved the team creating a Python command line REST Client that was especially tailored to query, analyze, and view statistics from MEAC Conference basketball games.  The application allowed the user to select teams or games played on a particular date.  As a result, their code concatenated the appropriate URL and executed the REST request.  Then, their code presented a menu to the user that asked what statistics they wanted to view in a table or plot, based on the JSON returned from the request.  Excellent work was done by this team.     ', u'title': u'HBCU Sports Report: A REST Client that Plots and Analyzes Collegiate Sports Data'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.1 ~ 2015.5', u'description': u'This was a one semester senior project that focused primarily on IT knowledge and skills.  Keywords: Python, Python Bottle Web Framework, MongoDB, Ubuntu Linux ****\n\nDuring this project, the team learned the concepts and advantages of MongoDB.  Then, they created a database with a few collections to play with.  Finally, they created a website to interact with the data using the Python Bottle web framework. \n', u'title': u'Getting to Know and Using MongoDB'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.1 ~ 2015.5', u'description': u'This was a one semester senior project that focused primarily on IT knowledge and skills.  Keywords: Python, MySQL, PDF Reports, Python ReportLab Library, Python MatPlotLib Library, Open Source, Ubuntu Linux ****\n\nThe team created a simple database with users and financial transactions.  During this project, the team was charged with developing a Pythonic PDF report generation tool that could query this MySQL database to retrieve data from individual or sets of users and create PDF's.  That is, the goal was to create a professional and standardized PDF report using the Python ReportLab library that detailed and summarized user activity in tables.  Also, the team was to use the Python MatplotLib library to add bar and line graphs to the PDF's that corresponded to the tables and other quantities derived from the data.  ', u'title': u'From Database to PDF:  Programmatically creating PDF's for Users or Clients'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.1 ~ 2014.12', u'description': u'This was a two semester senior project that focused primarily on IT knowledge and skills.  Keywords: Python, Javascript, REST, Open Source, MySQL, PostgreSQL, Django, Ubuntu Linux, PHP, Slim PHP, JSON, Python Request Library, Javascript xmlhttprequest ****\n\nDuring the first semester, the team started with a pre-existing game written in Python using the PyGame library.  Server side, the goal was to create a MySQL database and PHP REST API that allowed the storage of game play statistics and users.  Finally, the appropriate http requests and menus were added to the game to use the server side functionality.  \n\nDuring the second semester, a similar scope was accomplished using an open source Tetris game written in Javascript.  This time the server side component was implemented using a PostgreSQL database and Python Django web application framework.   ', u'title': u'Adding Back-end and Remote Data Support via REST API to Open Source Video Games'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.8 ~ 2015.12', u'description': u'This was a one semester campus outreach project that focused primarily on IT knowledge and skills.  Keywords: Python, R, Data Visualization, Data Analysis, Linux, Web Development ****\n\nIn this project, the team received data from the undergraduate admissions office at A&T that pertained to applicant information for the 2013, 2014, and 2015 school years.  The purpose was to visualize the locations of in-state applicants to A&T.  The team used Python to manipulate the data into more usable forms.  Then googleVis, an R interface to the Google Charts API, was used to create various geographically focused plots of the data.  Finally, a website was built to house all of the plots and provide informative information about the project.  ', u'title': u'North Carolina A&T Admissions Data Visualization Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.8 ~ 2015.12', u'description': u'This was a one semester senior project that focused primarily on IT knowledge and skills.  Internet of Things was also a focus.  Keywords: Linux on z, Raspberry Pi, Internet of Things, Mobile Application Development, Phone Gap, jQuery Mobile, php, MySQL, z/VM ****\n\nDuring this semester, the entire class focus was to work on projects that related directly or indirectly to a Linux instance running on an IBM system z Mainframe.  Four project areas were covered.  Please see the slides under my Adjunct Instructor, Computer Systems Technology job for descriptions and more information and architectures regarding each project area. ****\n\n1. Server side database and REST API running on Debian Linux on IBM System Z + z/VM to serve the other project areas\n2. Internet of Things sensor vehicle based on Raspberry Pi - posted data to REST API and DB\n3. Mobile Application REST Client (PhoneGap) which consumes JSON formatted data from z Linux Instance\n4. Internet of Things health sensor application based on Raspberry Pi and Arduino - posted data to REST API and DB', u'title': u'Overall Senior Project for Fall 2015 - Linux on System z Focus'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.1 ~ 2015.5', u'description': u'This was a one semester senior project that focused primarily on Programming knowledge and skills, along with some hardware implementation. Keywords: Python, Hardware, Raspberry Pi GPIO, Linux, DTMF Decoder ****\n\nIn this project, the team first learned the basics of Raspberry Pi GPIO programming and built a simple tank style robot controlled by a Raspberry Pi.  Then, a unique aspect was added to the vehicle that would allow it to be controlled anywhere that cellular phone service is available.  That is, they used a DTMF decoder that connects to the audio output of any mobile device.  This decoder had 4 output pins that changed status based on what tones it received on its audio input, which we connected to the mobile device.  By connecting the output of the decoder to the Raspberry Pi GPIO and adjusting the code, we build a system that would allow a user to control the vehicle after placing a call to the mobile device attached to the decoder and vehicle.  Very cool and extendable project.    ', u'title': u'Raspberry Pi Enabled PiTank Robot: Emphasizing Phone Call Control with DTMF Decoding'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.8 ~ 2014.12', u'description': u'This was a one semester senior project that focused primarily on IT knowledge and skills.  Keywords: Ubuntu Linux, DB2, PHP, Slim PHP, Python, REST, REST Client, JSON, Python Requests Library ****\n\nIn this project, students learned about REST API's and their purpose in Enterprise Computing.  The students then installed DB2 Express-C on an Ubuntu Linux VM and created a database with a very simple schema and limited data.  Then by using the Slim PHP micro framework, the students built a RESTful interface to service mock 3rd party applications that could use the database in question for basic CRUD operations.  The team concluded by building a Python test REST client to verify the API and database.  ', u'title': u'Implementing a DB2 Database on Ubuntu, along with Slim PHP REST API Layer'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.1 ~ 2014.8', u'description': u'This was a two semester senior project that focused primarily on IT and Hardware skills.  Keywords: Python, Smart Home, Data Visualization, Open Source, MySQL, Sensors, IR Control, Cloud, Internet of Things, Raspberry Pi, Linux ****\n\nIn this project, a prototype Raspberry Pi based Smart home solution was created with the following features.\n\n\u2022  The team built software that could sense the temperature and upload it to a remote web and database server\n\u2022  The system could sense movement in a room and upload occupancy information to a remote web and database server\n\u2022  Implemented a software based temperature control system via an Infrared transmitter that was programmed to turn on a fan when the temperature was sensed to be above a certain level  \n\u2022  Allowed users to control and receive information about the system via text message\n\u2022  Via a website running on the remote Linux virtual machine housing the sensed information,  system included a cloud component that allowed system control and visualization of the stored data  \n \n', u'title': u'Raspberry Pi Smart Home Applications'}]

summary: Samantha (Sam) DeBianchi founded DeBianchi Real Estate in July 2011, knowing that her unique background in hospitality and passion for real estate could help her provide the market with an innovative real estate buying and selling experience second to none. Sam has represented a number of athletes, entrepreneurs, investors and locals and provides all of her clients with the best-in-class service.\n\nHer drive for excellence coupled with her innate creativity and “over-the-top, out-of-the-box thinking” led her to fill a void missing in the industry and obtain positions writing and speaking nationally and internationally about the housing market on FOX News, FOX Business, CNBC, CNBC World and Bloomberg. Her expert advice and opinions have been featured on major media outlets including Forbes, Bloomberg, Huffington Post, FOX News, FOX Business, CNN Money, AOL, and Yahoo as well as in various publications, radio shows and television networks across the globe. Sam is also the First Lady of Million Dollar Listing Miami on Bravo TV.\n\nAs the Millennial Millionaire of money saving business site, The Penny Hoarder, Sam helps people turn their side hustle into full time gigs with her business advice and motivation. \n\nToday, Sam is one of the nation’s most sought out business and motivational keynote speakers. Her dynamic personality and high-valued informative content is engaging all audiences across the globe.\n\nAs an avid reader and researcher, Sam is educated on the latest market news and trends, and truly has a “sixth sense” for her client’s real estate needs. She prides herself on employing a no-nonsense, straight-forward approach and is constantly aiming to raise the bar of the real estate industry.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2013.12 ~ 2014.1', u'description': u'Redesigned the Shorewall project website; updated to modern CSS/XHTML and greatly enhanced usability, while retaining all site content and publishing procedures intact.\nLive site: http://www.shorewall.org', u'title': u'Shorewall Project Website Redesign'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.9 ~ now', u'description': u'As part of teaching CEG 3120 (Introduction to the Design of Information Technology Systems) at Wright State University, I have developed a concept for a class project which the students work on over the course of each semester.  This project gives students the opportunity to learn and apply advanced Java concepts in an environment where teamwork is required.  Each semester a new group of students continues the project where the previous semester's students left off.  This project mirrors the environment a typical programmer might find in a hybrid open source/commercial development project (with some important adjustments because of the academic constraints on the project).  We even have some external participants.  Feel free to follow the project or to join in the fun.', u'title': u'JFiles - a file browser (CEG 3120 class project @ WSU)'}]
