projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2014.8 ~ now', u'description': u'A mostly simple, yet powerful C++ data integration toolset for nodakwaeri (nk) or other software(s) which would make use of it.\n\nLicensed under Apache v2.0, nodamysql features the MySQL C++ Connector from Oracle - which is licensed according to the terms provided under the FOSS License Exception when used with nodakwaeri (nk) or other Free and Open Source Software sporting acceptable license types.\n\nnodamysql (nk-mysql) is designed to use Prepared Statements - and to allow implicit asynchronous usage - in order to help keep your application secure and efficient.\n\nWhen Oracle finishes the Memcached entry point for mysql-server and mysql-cluster, nodamysql will provide access to both conventional sequel as well as noSQL - both with the efficiency of noSQL. This will help enable a user experience tailored both to developer and designer.\n\nThis project is in a state of on-going development and is also available via npm, which you can view from the publications section of this profile.', u'title': u'nodamysql (nk-mysql)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.10 ~ 2013.9', u'description': u'JoomConnect is the oldest and first integration of its kind; boasting the ability to capture leads from your sign-up form and landing pages directly into ConnectWise, sync clients both ways, generate ConnectWise Opportunities, Service Tickets, Activities, Add or Remove Users to or from Marketing Groups and Tracks, attach Marketing Campaigns, assign a Sales Rep and provide one-click access to the ConnectWise Client Portal from a single click on your website.  \n\nCheck out http://www.joomconnect.com for more information.', u'title': u'JoomConnect'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.8 ~ now', u'description': u'nk-mvc is the 'Hello World!' example of - and project template for - a nodakwaeri (nk) MVC Application.\n\nnk-mvc was developed conceptually as the base for nk-xrm. The project is in a state of on-going development.', u'title': u'nk-mvc'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.11 ~ now', u'description': u'MMOD Panel is an upgrade to the Topbar in Gnome3, creating a customizable panel and providing options for fine-tuning your Desktop Experience.\n\nSupported Gnome-shell versions:\n\n3.10\n3.12\n3.12.2\n3.14\n\nFeatures:\n\n- Set comfort levels to provide theme support and fine-tune the overall look and feel of the panel.\n- Set the location/position of the panel (bottom by default).\n- Add a button to the panel in place of the activities link, using an icon of your preference.\n- Auto-hide the panel when not active/in-focus (makes use of pressure/gesture for showing the panel).\n- Display and manage your favorites/running apps directly on the panel.\n- Move the date menu to the aggregate/tray area.\n- Access and manage your extension preferences directly from the aggregate menu.\n- Customize behavior of the overview and panel(hot-corners/animations/effects) to suit your preferences.\n- More to come soon!\n\n\nThe project is available on extensions.gnome.org, the direct link available from the publications section of this profile.', u'title': u'MMOD-Panel'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.8 ~ now', u'description': u'The Massively Modified, Massively Modern Solution for Node.js which enables the collection and customization of desired components via a native extension system in order to create an original (X)Cross-Relational Management System. Users can create a CMS, a CRM, or any other application they can imagine by browsing available plug-ins or creating their own.\n\nThis project is in a state of on-going development and is also available via npm, which you can view from the publications section of this profile.', u'title': u'nk-xrm'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.2 ~ 2016.2', u'description': u'Kwaeri-GP - the Kwaeri Game Platform - is a browser based WebGL client built using Babylon.js.\n\nIt uses minimal HTML markup to implement a very basic sample UI over a 3D open world, with a model built using MakeHuman and Blender. Complete with WASD movement, several animations, and gravity - it demonstrates the use of WebGL and common game mechanics in modern browsers.', u'title': u'Kwaeri-GP'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.8 ~ 2014.8', u'description': u'A simple, yet powerful, and fully-featured cross-platform application framework for Node.js\n\nnk is simple to use, featuring tools for easing common processes without losing efficiency. This is accomplished by fully writing out if/else statements and avoiding conditionals and ternary operators as a form of 'shorthand' for the latter. This is especially important in interpreted languages such as JavaScript when used with technologies such as Node.js\n\nAnother focus for preserving efficiency, is in using events as little as possible. Node.js already utilizes events to provide the API that it offers - and by using events for every little facility within a framework; we add 2-3 invocations at least for any event - as many times as the event occurs. A solid OOP approach with the necessary time invested is far superior to falling back onto events for the sake of easing core development. There exists countless development, efficiency, and other issues which could arise from using events too often - and so lightly.\n\nAside from those basic tools, nk also provides a full MVC framework, along with the tools required to write a fully featured web application:\n\n\nFactories:\n\n- Server\n- Session\n- Router\n- SCJL (Cryptography)\n- Controller\n- Model\n- Renderer\n- HTML\n\n\nIn order to supplement the facilities provided by nk directly, applications (such as nk-mvc or nk-xrm)  make use of nodamysql (nk-mysql) as a database provider, as well as Bootstrap(which includes Normalize) and jQuery via CDN as the technologies of choice for the client-side user experience.\n\n\nThe results are an unbelievably efficient, and feature rich, application framework.\n\n\nThis project is in a state of on-going development and is also available via npm, which you can view from the publications section of this profile', u'title': u'nodakwaeri (nk)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.2 ~ now', u'description': u'MMod GP, or Massively Modified Gaming Platform, is a C++ game platform (engine) which supports DirectX 9, 10, 11, and OpenGL.  The project will start as a fully featured MMORPG style game for Windows, later expanding to Linux and Mobile devices, offering unique experiences between the different types of devices to deliver a rich gaming experience everywhere you go.\n\nMMod GP is currently in development.  The server and client software are in a live development stage.  The current software/features which exist/are supported:\n\n\n- Crazy Eddie's GUI Library (CEGUI)\n- LUA Scripting Module (via CEGUI)\n- GUI Theming System (via CEGUI)\n- DirectX 10 Support\n- Custom model format (Includes tool for Maya conversion to custom format)\n- Live Chat\n- Server/Client communication via WinSock\n- 3rd person camera\n- WASD movement\n- Collision detection', u'title': u'MMod GP'}]

summary: After 10 years in the safety and components e-commerce business, my career has taken a turn.  Over those 10 years I have had a close working relationship with Kee Safety and now they have offered me the opportunity to work at the center of their organization to improve digital marketing across the entire group.\n\nThere's a lot more to me than a few sentences can express, but since you're here I'll tell you a bit about myself.\n\nI’m on the passionate side. I like helping people and building things.  My friends and I took a seed idea and grew an e-commerce business from zero to over $8M. This business has taken me all over the world (UK, German, Netherlands, France, China).  I’ve met a lot of interesting people as we expand our global e-commerce presence.\n\nI'm a family man with seven male children (yes you read that correctly).  I try hard to be in touch with my local community and help people see that there is someone greater than themselves at the center of the universe. On top of all this, I tend to be a hacker and a geek.\n\nI have the kind of skills mix that tends to lead to success in our current economy.  I can present, I can relate to people, I can code, I can market, I can lead and I can play the guitar.  I'm not sure the last one counts for much, but now you know a little more about me.\n\nSo, what brings you here?  Feel free to reach out to me and start a conversation.\n\nHere's what the Democrat and Chronicle had to report about our business: http://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/money/business/2015/10/03/catching-up-chris-pollock-simplified-safety/73091150/

summary: As a young man, I solved an array of hardware and software problems in the computer repair industry.  I spent sixteen to eighteen hours each day studying how computers work. I devoted most of this time to computer viruses. Many people found my expertise useful: I found myself fixing more and more friend’s and family’s computers. I enjoyed this work. However, I worked for free, and I realized I could not spend so much time repairing computers without compensation. So I started my own computer repair and maintenance company, Stepmans PC.\n\nOne day, I received a call from one of my satisfied customers.\n\n“Alex! We want to create a website, and we want you to do it.”\n\n“I am really sorry,” I replied. “I’m not a programmer, or web developer, and I’m not qualified.”\n\n“But you are the best at solving computer problems!” \n\n“Computers, yes,” I said.“But not programming.”\n\nIt was hard to resist my customer’s persistence, but I experienced a moral dilemma—a dilemma that, in the past, had made me pause before I agreed to do any work: I did not want to get paid for a job that would not satisfy my customer.\n\nI said: “I will create a website for myself, and if you like the website, I will create something similar for your company.” The customer agreed, and I did create a website, a site I maintain to this day: www.masterkitchendesign.com\n\nNot long after, the customer asked: “Why is our website not found on Google?”\n\nLike most web developers, I had no idea. However, I was intrigued: How does one make a website appear on Google's first page? I offered a compromise. I assumed the price for search engine optimization was equal to the price of virus removal, so I refunded the cost for my customer to hire his own specialist. We soon learned that the cost for an optimization specialist could be ten times more than virus removal. So I had no choice: I had to learn search engine optimization.\n\nToday, I am practicing SEO specialist, fluent in all aspects of computer hardware and design.

To offer this system for sale to other orthodontists, I set up an easy-to-use e-commerce solution based on WordPress and WooCommerce.\n\nNow, rather than spending time on the phone taking orders, his fulfillment specialist can concentrate on simply shipping out orders, as all payments are handled electronically.  Inventory is also a snap to manage, as it adjusts itself when products are sold, so there's no need to answer customer calls about whether or not a product is in stock.\n\nI manage this site on my Linux server, providing timely updates, security patches, and software maintenance. When any problems arise, I provide troubleshooting and quick solutions to ensure minimal, if any, downtime.', u'title': u'Ortho SuperTAD'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.4 ~ 2014.4', u'description': u'I designed and developed the website for Shreddies USA. This is the first US distributor of Shreddies flatulence-filtering underwear. I designed the website with Pixelmator and developed the site for WooCommerce and WordPress with the bones of the Genesis framework from StudioPress. I have built a robust shipping platform that largely automates the process of receiving and shipping orders, so the business can focus on marketing and reaching new customers.', u'title': u'Shreddies USA - Flatulence Filtering Underwear'}]

What do noise and music reveal about human and nonhuman communities and the state of the environment? What are soundscape, Biomusic, situation music, circumstance music, environmental music, soundwalk, animal music and plant music?\n\nWhat aspects of sound, society and environment should be treasured, reclaimed and protected from the adverse impacts of human civilisation, environmental degradation and acoustic disturbance?\n\nWhat can individuals learn and do about noise and music in their society and environment to promote holistic thinking and sustainable ways of life? summary: CEO, Software Engineer, Educator \n\nFounder and CEO of We Can Code IT, Crain's Cleveland 2014 Woman of Note, and software engineer & architect with 20 years of professional experience, I am humbled to have the opportunity to give back to the community and shepherd new, diverse, programmers into tech careers. \n\nMy interest in bringing coding to everyone began nearly as soon as I started my role as a software engineer.  I've worked in IOT, Artificial Intelligence, Augmented Reality and enterprise development. Throughout my career, I've always found it satisfying to share my love of computer science and engineering subjects with kids, teens, & adults. We Can Code IT was born out of this love and my passion for equity. \n\nAs the CEO of We Can Code IT, I bring this mission to life. \n\nAt We Can Code IT our goal is to teach people how to code, especially those who don't typically feel invited to the field. Our coding boot camps flip the demographics of a traditional computer science classroom on its head. 80% of our students are women and people of color. My job is to help those in need find a new life, a new career, a new home in the tech community.

summary: Geoff Myers has been involved in and excited about business, marketing, design, and technology since 2004, when he founded SimDex LLC at the age of 14 in his hometown of Saint Paul, Minnesota. Although SimDex originally started as an IT consulting and support company, it evolved into a web design and development agency by 2008, and eventually matured into a full-service digital marketing consulting firm by 2016, specializing in custom WordPress web application development. For more than 12 years, Geoff has been designing and coding for the web while also growing his – and his clients' – businesses through the application of strategic marketing technologies and the development of custom-built, user-focused web applications.\n\nGeoff originally started out building static websites with Dreamweaver in HTML and CSS, but shifted to using the Joomla! content management system (CMS) by 2008, when version 1.5 was released. In 2010, he fell in love with – and became addicted to – WordPress and its community. Since then, Geoff has designed, developed, marketed, managed, and maintained over 60 WordPress-powered websites for a wide variety of clients in terms of industry, size, type, and location. Lately, Geoff has focused on building highly personalized web applications and integrations for WordPress using PHP and MySQL, the building blocks of WordPress itself.\n\nGeoff Myers\nPresident + CEO | SimDex LLC\ngeoff@simdex.org | www.simdex.org\n651.447.6247 | 414.455.6675

Dynamic demand is handled by an induction loop sensor in a standard intersection, to model the voltage input of an induction loop a 10k\u03a9 rheostat, when demand is detected the remaining travel time on the active street is reduced by 30%. summary: Currently I am a Project Engineer with Total Electric Construction on East Side Access: where my time is evenly split between material selection and  compliance; system drafting shop drawing review, design coordination, engineering resource management, and value added engineering. \n\nI have had the pleasure of interning with Welsbach Electric: Moynihan Station, and the New York Power Authority: Polletti Power Project working on project engineering, commissioning, I&C and testing as well as bulk power and design. \n\nAt City College’s Grove School of Engineering, I earned a BE in electrical engineering. My senior design project was performing a prototype performance testing on a (Mk 2) 25kVA electrostatically shielded toroidal dry type transformer per IEEE C57.12.91-2011. To complete this project a startup (HIGHest Transformers) was formed and market penetration research, developing manufacturing best practices were pursued. The Mk2 unit failed although the root cause analysis revealed the source of the issue: voltage regulation and excess current draw during no load heat rise testing. This has since been corrected in the successful Mk3 Prototype\n\nAt LaGuardia Community College I earned an AAS Electrical Engineering Technology. I served as a VP of the Engineering Club; arranging meetings with potential employers, professional organizations, project demonstrations and peer mentoring. I worked as a research assistant for Dr. Jaafar's work on Single Molecule Magnet decoherence. \n\nI have completed a 5 year NJATC apprenticeship with IBEW local 177 and served 5 more years as a Journeyman Inside Wireman working on factories, shipyards, railroads, data centers, powerhouses and substations. Instrumentation and controls, electrical machinery, automation, SCADA, fire alarms, base power, and communication systems were emphasized during coursework and OJT.\n

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2015.11 ~ 2015.12', u'description': u'\u2022 Designed a CDO by determining the fair annual credit spreads of the three tranches. \n\u2022 Used Copula to simulate the default times of each bond.\n\u2022 Implemented Monte-Carlo simulation, got the credit spreads of each tranche. Found the loss and excess of the CDO, explained them in different scenarios.', u'title': u'Collateralized Debt Obligation (CDO) Design, R'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.9 ~ 2016.12', u'description': u'\u2022 Collected economic indicators (e.g. CPI and SPX) from Bloomberg. Applied Correlation based Feature Selection to search the most relevant attributes.\n\u2022 Adjusted the parameters in the clustering approach and Local Outlier Factor approach to detect outliers. Removed those outliers, and predicted the GDP by Linear Regression.\n\u2022 Compared with the prediction without anomaly detection, the R-squared increased from 0.7 to 0.77. Turned out that the outliers came in post-financial crisis.', u'title': u'GDP Prediction with Anomaly Detection, Python and Weka'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.8 ~ 2017.5', u'description': u'\u2022 Constructed a pricing model, which contained bond, stock, and collateral, to replicate the payoff of the American option with considering the funding spread and the counterparty credit risk,\n\u2022 Explored how funding spread and counterparty credit risk would affect the American option price based on no-arbitrage analysis,\n\u2022 Implemented numeric experiments to illustrate relationships between the XVA and parameters (e.g. funding spread, bond's rate of return, collateralization rate, the number of periods).', u'title': u'Arbitrage-Free Pricing of XVA for American Options in Discrete Time'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.1 ~ 2017.5', u'description': u'\u000F\u000F\u2022  Preprocessed the dataset with feature extraction and balanced the dataset.\n\u000F\u000F\u2022  Implemented classical decision tree and the Gradient Boost Tree to the training set as the benchmodel. Compared it with other machine learning methods (e.g. K-nearest neighbors, Naive Bayes, Neural Network) with the evaluation based on the validation set.\n\u000F\u000F\u2022  Combined multiple methods by Meta-learning. Concluded that the Gradient Boost Tree came with the best result, which increased the accuracy by 7% when compared with the zero-R.', u'title': u'House Interest Level Prediction with Decision Tree, Matlab'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.4 ~ 2016.4', u'description': u'\u2022 Constructed portfolio with stocks, covered calls and protective puts. \n\u2022 Based on the Finite Difference Method, got the function of pricing options. Implemented them into Matlab, and made the choices of covered call or protective put.\n\u2022 Formed the portfolio in Interactive Brokers, evaluated the strategy based on the payoff.', u'title': u'Portfolio Hedging and Risk Management, Matlab'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2015.12', u'description': u'\u2022 Standardized the returns of three stocks based on the daily predicted volatilities from GARCH model.\n\u2022 Fit a three-dim distribution to the relative return series, standard normal or student t distribution, depending on the QQplot and the MLE. Simulated the future stock returns with GARCH model.\n\u2022 Evaluated the risk of all feasible combinations of the three stocks with the Value at Risk and the Expected Shortfall. Backtested the result with the analysis using the real data.', u'title': u'Portfolio Risk Analysis, R'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.9 ~ 2016.12', u'description': u'\u2022  Picked 20 stocks on the market. Collected their historical stock prices from Bloomberg, and calculated the covariance matrix by the stocks' return.\n\u2022  Computed stocks' weight on the tangency portfolio based on the MPT. Formed the portfolio on Interactive Brokers with an initial value of $1,000,000, and rebalanced it every week in two months.\n\u2022  Implemented performance analysis, including Alpha, Beta, Sharpe ratio, and Leverage ratio. \n\u2022  Improved the calculation of the covariance matrix by Factor Model and the French and Fama Model.', u'title': u'Portfolio Optimization by Modern Portfolio Theory(MPT), Matlab'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2016.3 ~ 2016.3', u'description': u'', u'title': u'Predicting loads in the knee joint using software \u2018Opensim\u2019.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.11 ~ 2015.11', u'description': u'\u2022 Evaluated the position and orientation of the end-effector, for the given joint parameters using Reverse Kinematic Analysis.\n\u2022 Computed all the solution sets using the code generated on MATLAB, based upon available spherical equations and direction cosines for the given polygon configuration.\n\u2022 Verified the results of the reverse analysis with the forward analysis methodology.', u'title': u'Forward and Reverse Kinematic Analysis of GE P60 and Cincinnati Milacron T3-776 manipulator on MATLAB.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.4 ~ 2010.4', u'description': u'Aim of the project was to align the normal vector with falling sun rays. Thereafter, it was required to manually adjust the vertical axis of the system, using planks.  ', u'title': u'Design and development of solar tracker.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.8 ~ 2016.8', u'description': u'Finite Element Analysis of Beams using Abaqus:\n\u2022 Analysed the stress generated in structures subjected to various types of forces such as compression, extension, bending and torsion.\n\u2022 Analysis of data to verify load bearing capacity of the structure. \n\u2022 Optimization of dimension for a stressed bar in MATLAB using input file data.\n\u2022 Calculated the stresses and tip deflection for a cantilevered beam using CST, Linear and quadratic rectangular elements. ', u'title': u'Velocity and Acceleration analysis of Cincinnati Milacron T3-776 manipulator using MATLAB.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.8 ~ 2016.8', u'description': u'\u2022 Using available journals and papers available online from forums such as science direct were studied for different types of hydroforming techniques, their area of application and modern developments.\n\u2022 Cumulative study was presented as a part of Production Engineering coursework.', u'title': u'Project to study trends and modern developments in the field of Hydroforming.'}]

u'Keyword Identification based on BP neural network with Matlab'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.12 ~ 2015.12', u'description': u' Applied GARCH, MA-based time-varying volatility estimation methods. Analyzed the affection of big event in stock market by utilizing serval methods includes: regression, abnormal return, event window and standard deviation of deviation.\n\n', u'title': u'Time Series Analysis and Event Study with R'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.5 ~ 2017.6', u'description': u'A client is looking for growth of business of credit card. They want to dig out more customers with good performance in the past. We created a Data-Mart for a various types of further predictive models.\n\uf09f\tAccording to the data mapping, selected and extracted samples from a list of raw dataset, eliminated duplicates, created a one-subject-per-row dataset in PROC step and DATA step. \n\uf09f\tWith given requirement, established a segmentation for the behavior of customer with PROC FORMAT based on their credit score. Applied this segmentation on all selected samples.\n\uf09f\tFor all numeric variables, performed data quality check with PROC MEANS and PROC FREQ, focusing on minimum, maximum, and missing values. Did correction for errors and marked missing value.\n\uf09f\tWith PROC UNIVARIATE, checked extreme values for the dataset and did correction to the errors.\n\uf09f\tFor all character variables, checked data quality with PROC FREQ. Found invalid and missing values. Corrected invalid values and assigned supposed value to the missing ones.\n\uf09f\tCreated a format to separate valid data from invalid data with PROC FORMAT. Applied this format to the whole dataset.\n\uf09f\tChecked formats for certain character variables. Manipulated irregular character value with SUBSTR function and concatenation operator to correct them.\n\uf09f\tIntroduced a variable as a last-update indicator in order to trace the time of insertion or updating for every samples. MAX function was used to determine which value of the indicator should be used among those from different raw datasets.\n\uf09f\tDefined a variable to calculate aggregate number of default with SUM statement and IF statement.\n\uf09f\tCreated a Macro with keyword parameters of data cleansing process for future use, including PROC UNIVRIATE, PROC PRINT and DATA step.\n\uf09f\tAs instructed, split the dataset into 3 equal percentage with MACRO\nStatistical Methods: Segmentation, Cluster Analysis, Discriminant Analysis.', u'title': u'Customer Segmentation and Marketing Campaign Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.6 ~ 2017.7', u'description': u'Responsibilities:\n\uf09f\tImported raw data into a new dataset with DATA step, defined several new variables to calculate roll-rate (RR) of different time periods with LAG function. Performed different calculation of RR for first appearance of every account and rest with First. Automatic variable and IF statement.\n\uf09f\tPerformed 3-month moving average analysis of RRs. For first appearance of every account, assigned missing value to all RRs. For rest of the records, utilized SUM, LAG and N function to achieve moving average calculation. Discrimination of first appearance and rest of the records was implemented by First. Automatic variable and IF statement as well.\n\uf09f\tBased on calculated moving average of RRs, converted original multiple-row-per-account dataset into a one-row-per-account dataset. Only last record of every account was kept with last. Automatic variable and IF statement.\n\uf09f\tSelected, extracted and combined variables with PROC SQL. Eliminated duplicates with distinct option.\n\uf09f\tKept the last month\u2019s status of every account as an indicator to track whether a customer has charged off with IF statement. Converted this character variable to numeric indicator 0 and 1 for further analysis.\n\uf09f\tFor charge-off customers, calculated the time period from the beginning of study to the time that they charged-off with INTCK function. For non-charge-off customers, assigned a constant for this variable.\n\uf09f\tIn order to find out the potential relation between default behavior and the time period, performed logistic regression with PROC LOGISTIC and figured out the regression equation.\n\uf09f\tBased on logistic regression analysis, forecasted a list of customers with different delinquency history to see the probability that they would default in the future. \nStatistical Methods: Roll-Rate Calculation, Moving Average Analysis, Logistic Regression, Survival Analysis.', u'title': u'Risk Management Project and Basel II Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.1 ~ 2015.3', u'description': u'\u2022\tDeveloped regression/nonparametric models by model diagnosis, data simulation and \n        transformation\n\u2022\tSelected the best fit model using the Stepwise method & AIC/BIC                               \n\u2022\tOptimized the model variables by PCA with minimum complexity\n\u2022\tApplied the GARCH models to estimate time-varying volatilities             \n', u'title': u'Equity Price/Volatility Forecasting with R '}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.12 ~ 2015.1', u'description': u'\u2022\tWorked in a team to develop an integral annual report for a large catering company\n\u2022\tPerformed in-depth analysis on the company\u2019s liquidity, profitability and efficiency using Excel\n\u2022\tUsed multiple methods (e.g. NPV, IRR, Payback Period and Discounted Payback Period) to evaluate \n        a project\n', u'title': u'Financial & Investment Analysis'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2016.6 ~ 2016.9', u'description': u'\u2022 Developed an OFDM Transmitter and Receiver for WLAN 802.11a/g standards for Rayleigh Multipath channel in the presence of AWGN.\n\u2022 Performed BER (Bit-Error-Rate) vs SNR (Signal-to-Noise Ratio) analysis for QPSK, 8-PSK, 16 - QAM modulation schemes in IEEE 802.11a/g standards over AWGN and Rayleigh Multipath channels.\n\u2022Analyzed the spectral efficiency of SISO and 2x2 MIMO channel diversity with developed Rayleigh Multipath profiles for a target BER (Bit-Error-Rate) of 10^-3 using Adaptive Modulation.', u'title': u'Physical Layer Simulation of OFDM for WLAN 802.11a/g standards and LTE systems'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.9 ~ 2016.9', u'description': u'\u2022 Measured and calculated the path loss at various distances in the Line of Sight and Non-Line of Sight path from the Access Point to the receiver.\n\u2022 The Received Signal strength was measured using inSSIDer software and path loss was modelled using MATLAB and estimated the path loss components using the model.\nPerformed BER vs SNR analysis for various modulation schemes such as QPSK, 8-PSK, 16 - QAM over AWGN and Multipath channels and implemented OFDM modulation and demodulation in MATLAB.\nSimulated the performance of Adaptive Modulation for channel diversity in LTE-OFDM Systems in MATLAB by analysing the spectral efficiency', u'title': u'Fading Simulator for Digital Communication Systems'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.8 ~ now', u'description': u'Professor : Dr Mathew Heins \n- Equivalent circuit modelling using components from modelithics \n- Design and validate a Low noise amplifier at frequency 2 GHz\n- Designed Bias network ,input & output matching networks\n- Measurement of non - linear characteristics ', u'title': u'Active Microwave Lab '}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.9 ~ 2016.9', u'description': u'\u2022 Projects were designed as part of the course RF design and measurements where every design was tested in the lab for its performance and characteristics and compared with the simulated results. Thanks to Professor Lehmann for the course plan.\n\nTools used : AWR Microwave Office, AWR AXIEM\nHardware : Vector Network Analyser (VNA) , Signal Generator, Power Meter, Spectrum Analyser, Soldering Station.\n\nThe following designs were performed :\n\n\u2022Scalar Measurement\n\u2022Vector Measurement (scattering Parameters)\n\u2022 Open Circuit Stub Resonators: \nDesigned, simulated, tested single and parallel open-circuit stub resonators. While decoding the motion vector and reference frame is used to generate the next frame.\nTasks involved:\n1) Writing the code to generate motion vector between the given frames using the 2D Logarithmic search algorithm. \n2) Writing the code to regenerate the target frame from the motion vector and the reference frame.\n', u'title': u'MATLAB implementation of 2D Logarithmic Search Algorithm'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.2 ~ 2016.4', u'description': u'The goal of the project was to speedup the process of clustering using GPU. summary: I graduated with M.S in computer engineering at New York University. I love building things from basic elements since I was in my childhood. I am quite good at physic and Mathematics. But when I was exposed to programming when I was young, I was attracted to it because it gave me the freedom. I saw that I could build a career for my future. When I was in my undergraduate program. I earned outstanding student award and finish whole 4-year courses in 3 years. After that I joined a start-up company, I improved the core algorithm by 20% and then I helped to launch the first product of company on a listed company funding platform. And it funded over 1000% as the original goal. When in my graduate program, my focus is mainly about big data analysis and algorithm design. I built a recommender system using Hadoop big data process platform and tested it on AWS. And through designing TopK system in high QPS and other real worlds projects, I got to know core issue about system design in real scenarios. Like how to scale and tradeoff according to different scenarios. I love programming and solving problem and l am looking for a full-time opportunity now.

The toolboxes have built in commands for the specific tasks that they are expected to perform. They take the necessary input of the particular operation from the user, process the input with the pre-defined commands and provide the expected output that the user may arrive at, if the task is carried out empirically. Unfortunately, no such toolbox exists for chemical engineering equipment. The rationale behind undertaking this venture is to create a tool box that would ease the task of chemical engineers for designing major equipment needed in process industries. \nThis project includes MATLAB codes written for the designing of various heat exchangers such as the double-pipe heat exchanger, shell and tube heat exchanger etc. It then moves on to include programs for mass transfer equipment such as the sieve trays, baffled vessels etc.  \nVarious input data is asked from the user before giving relevant output. By developing films of diatoms we can use their shells to our advantage to further improve the efficiency of solar cells. summary: Systems/Advanced Concepts + Technologies Engineer at Northrop Grumman\n\n---\n\nMechanical Engineering PhD Graduate from Northwestern University\nProjects include research in energy, sustainability, mechanical/RF sensors, medical sensors, 3D printing and commercial product research and development.  I manage projects concerning the additive manufacturing of stent medical implants, the design of a new manufacturing system for medical implants, kinetic energy harvesting designs for powering medical implants and bio-sensing contact lenses for medical applications.\n\nI also serve as our lab's director for an internship program which hosts roughly 5 undergraduate students per summer, which involves interviewing, hiring, training, and mentoring.\n\nA brief summary of my projects (for those who expanded this summary tab!)\n\nHere at Northwestern I am developing new stent medical implants that can be 3D printed using custom designed 3D printers we have built in our lab.  These stents are important because the material they are made out of allows them to absorb into the body over time, eliminating the need for invasive post-operative surgeries.\n\nIn addition to developing the stent medical product, another focus has been reducing the manufacturing time and improving the quality of the stent.  In this way I have designed a new 3D printer that will reduce manufacturing time of each stent down from 10 hours per stent on our existing printer to about 10-15 minutes each.\n\nAdditional work has involved the design of a mechanical energy harvesting device small enough to fit into a pacemaker.  The goal of this device is to replace a portion of the pacemaker battery and allow the pacemaker to be charged by the mechanical energy supplied by the beating heart indefinitely.

4:00pm\nLocation: 90-3122\nAttachment: \napplication/pdf iconpv-micro-grid-hdu_by_prof_jianmin_zhang_from_hdu.pdf\n', u'title': u'Summer Intern, June-July. 2012, Micro Grid Lab, Hangzhou Dianzi University, Hangzhou'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2007.10 ~ now', u'description': u'     Urbanization has become a worldwide trend with rapid growth of electricity consumption in metropolis\u2019s area. Presently, PV (Photovoltaic) on roof has been utilized in this regarding. However, a seriously neglected potential power resource is the potential power resource behind the tall buildings in form of pumping storage hydropower. In fact, all city high-rise buildings have a water loop system and both of roof and bottom of buildings are equipped with water tanks together with pumping system for drinking, sanitation, swim pool, fire control, water drain, etc. \n     By using buildings\u2019 30 to 200 meters water height or hydro power can be used by pumping storage as a method to shift the peak and redeem the off-peak of grid. If we combine the roof\u2019s photovoltaic power generation and building pumped storage to form a micro-grid, it is possible to meet the balance of electric power in the day time and energy load of the building with a certain conditions of the sun; even in the non-sunny days, relying on the pumped-storage power in the daytime using the energy of grid, we can provide peak power load of the buildings; in rainfall season, with the using of roof rainwater storage, we can also have a great of electrical power. Thus, taking full advantage of the potential energy resources of the city buildings and the combination of building photovoltaic and large power grids serious peak-off-peak difference, etc.\n     Due to a short period of under graduate dissertation study, we have only done the research trying to built model and simulation to discuss its preliminary technical feasibility.\n     Such research work can be seen from a seminar in Lawrance Berkery National Lab. in Aug.2012, see Project URL.', u'title': u'A Feasibility and Simulation Study of High-rise Building in City with PV and Mini-hydro Pumping\uff1aMight be a Big Solution for Future City Smart & Micro Grid'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.8 ~ 2014.12', u'description': u'Advisor: Prof. Daniel Tylavsky \nFunded by: Salt River Project, Tempe, AZ \n\n\u2022\tCreated computer programs to estimate two-layer soil parameters and analyzed the ground grid safety \n\u2022\tFormulated a nonlinear optimization model by using genetic algorithm and pattern search for the substation ground grid security design and economic analysis. \n\u2022\tDeveloped by Matlab program and Matlab Graphical User Interfaces\n', u'title': u'Optimal Substation Ground Grid Design Based on Genetic Algorithm and Pattern Search: Software development and application ( Funded by: Salt River Project, Tempe, AZ)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.6 ~ 2012.10', u'description': u'\u2022\tDeveloped a PV plant power output forecasting model using radiation and PV panel manufacturing characteristic data for utility to verify the energy metering data and prevent the stealing of electricity illegally or abnormal of metering\n\u2022\tProvided a comprehensive parameter calibration method to decrease the numbers of measurements and topologic connection data of PV plant\n\u2022\tProvided a parameter sensitive analysis method to put forward the accuracy requirement of measurement and PV panel characteristic data\n', u'title': u'Photovoltaic plant metering monitoring model and parameter analysis'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.8 ~ 2013.11', u'description': u'\u2022\tDeveloped Matlab and C codes for AC power flow analysis\n\u2022\tUsed LDU decomposition for matrix inversion and Tinny method for optimal ordering\n\u2022\tSolved the AC power flow problem using Newton-Raphson method\n\u2022\tTested the computer program using the IEEE 118-bus system and comparing the results with commercial software packages\n', u'title': u'AC power flow analysis using sparsity-programming techniques'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.8 ~ 2014.8', u'description': u'A popular explicit analytic Borowy 2C PV module model is proposed for power generation prediction. The maximum power point and the open-circuit point which are calculated in this model cannot be equal to the data given by manufacturers under standard test condition (STC). The derivation of this model has never been mentioned in any literatures. The parameter forms of 2C model in this paper are more simplified, and the model is decomposed into a STC sub-model and an incremental sub-model. The STC model is derived successfully from an ideal single-diode circuit model. Relative error estimations are developed to do the conformity error measurements. The analysis results showed that though the biases at those critical points are very small, the conformity will depend on both of the two ratio values I m/I sc and V m/V oc, which can be used to verify whether 2C model is applicable for the PV module produced by a particular manufacturer.', u'title': u'Derivation and conformity measurement of a popular explicit analytic Borowy 2C PV module model'}]

summary: I currently work as an Analyst at Arcesium LLC which recently spun out of the D. E. Shaw group. Arcesium provides software and services that support asset managers’ post-trade activities. The platform is the result of a five-year, comprehensive re-engineering effort by the D. E. Shaw group, and is capable of supporting the most complicated post-trade needs, as well as the broadest coverage of asset classes.\n\nPreviously I worked for Genpact Analytics's financial services analytics group for close to one and a half year. As part of Genpact's Smart Decision Services I worked on multiple projects such as ALM reporting for various banks and forward rates generation.\n\nI have done MBA in financial engineering and B-Tech in computer science and engineering (CSE).\n\nGood understanding of global macro, asset-backed securities, convertible bonds hedging, catastrophe bonds & portfolio optimization.\n\nIn terms of tool experience, I have used C,Linux,PHP, Excel, SQL and VBA, MATLAB and have hands on experience with various data science tools such as Python, Stata, Tableau.\n\nPart of what I bring to the table includes analytical aptitude, strong technical and research skills.\nSpecialities :\n• Financial modelling & mathematical finance\n• Automation & optimization\n• Programming & algorithms design\n• Simulation techniques\n\nGithub: https://github.com/go4vivek\nPapers: http://ifmr.academia.edu/vivek.

summary: Ali Mohammad Alqudah was born in Irbid, Jordan. He received the BSc degree in Biomedical Systems Engineering from Department of Biomedical Systems and Informatics Engineering, Hijjawi Faculty for Engineering Technology,  Yarmouk University (YU), Irbid, Jordan, in 2015. He is currently pursuing the MSc degree in the Electrical and Computer Engineering (Industrial Automation) at Hijjawi Faculty for Engineering Technology, Yarmouk University (YU), Irbid, Jordan.\n\nHis current research interests include  Medical imaging Systems, Biomedical Signal Processing, Medical Image Processing, Artifical Neural Network and Fuzzy Logic and Expert systems.\n\nThrough his research, Ali aimed to integrate different technologies with biomedical engineering to improve health care.\n\nAli is working as Arduino, C#.Net, ASP.Net, ADO.Net and Matlab freelance developer. His experience in many programming languages gives him the motivation to diverse his interests in utilizing many platforms and technology engines.

summary: I am currently working at Caterpillar as a Catalyst Performance Engineer in the Large Power System Division. \nI graduated with Masters in Mechanical Engineering from Michigan Technological University in April 2017. The focus area towards my graduate degree was IC Engine modeling, calibration, hardware in the loop (HIL) simulation, validation and Hybrid Electric Vehicles. \nI have listed my areas of interest and technical skills below. I would love to discuss any direct hire opportunity that matches with my skill set. I can be contacted either by phone on (906)231-2238 or by email at jharsulk@mtu.edu.\n\nSpecialties: Engine combustion and performance development, 1-D Engine Cycle Simulation, HIL simulation and validation, Data Acquisition and Calibration Science, Hybrid Electric Vehicle Modeling\n\n Technical Skills:\n - 1-D Engine performance simulation (GT-Power, MATLAB)\n - After-treatment Simulation and Analysis (MATLAB, Simulink)\n - HIL Real Time Simulation/ Modeling/ Calibration (MotoTune/ MotoHawk)\n - Hybrid Electric Vehicle (HEV) Modeling (MATLAB, Simulink)\n - Post-processing of experimental results (MS Excel, MATLAB)\n - CAN protocol (MATLAB/ MotoHawk/ CanKing)\n - Combustion modeling (Spark Ignited, Compression Ignited engines)\n - Chemical Reaction Kinetics development (ANSYS Chemkin)\n - Thermo-Fluid process Modeling (EES, MATLAB)\n - Engine cycle Simulation (MATLAB, EngineSim)\n - Signal Processing (MATLAB)\n - Transducer/Sensor Instrumentation, Calibration and Data Acquisition (Experience in ACAP and NI LabVIEW data acquisition)

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2017.3 ~ 2017.5', u'description': u'Part 1 Milsoft WindMil Circuit Building Exercise\nThe first part was to build up a distribution circuit model from scratch using the Milsoft WindMil commercial distribution analysis program. The team was given a distribution circuit data set and a circuit feeder model was developed and tested.\n\nPart 2 Feeder Upgrade Analysis and Recommendations\nThe second part of the project was to perform planning analysis on this circuit. The project team assumed the role of a distribution planning group and determined the circuit upgrades needed to meet planning criteria at the lowest cost.\n\nPart 3 PV Integration Analysis and Recommendations\nThe third part of the project was to investigate high-penetration PV system integration on this same circuit using OpenDSS. ', u'title': u'ECE 551-Smart Electric Power Distribution Systems Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.11 ~ 2016.11', u'description': u'Carried out in-depth review of a technical paper presenting a dynamic model of a grid connected variable speed wind turbine. Modelled the simulation and dynamic performance of gearless variable speed wind turbine to the variations in the wind using PSCAD/EMTDC and MATLAB.', u'title': u'PSCAD/EMTDC-Based Modeling and Analysis of a Gearless Variable Speed Wind Turbine'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.11 ~ 2016.11', u'description': u'Performed Contingency Screening on a IEEE-85 bus system using two methods. The first method was using a Power Flow algorithm and the second method was based on Nodal Analysis method. The results of Voltage Violations and Branch Overloads were then verified for a simulation of a Line Outage in the MATLAB.', u'title': u'Contingency Screening on a IEEE-85 Bus System'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.11 ~ 2012.11', u'description': u'Minor Project 1 submitted in 5th Semester completed under the guidance of Shri J. N. Rai for partial fulfillment of Degree of B.Tech in Electrica Engineering.\n\nElectrical Energy has become a fundamental requirement for the existence and development of the modern society. With the ever increasing demand in electricity more efficient plants are required. Combined cycle plants are the most fuel-efficient plants capable of providing efficiency exceeding 58% compared to steam and gas power plants alone whose efficiencies are limited to 35-42% and around 30% respectively. Modern combined cycle plants are operated in combined cycle gas turbine (CCGT) configuration in which the exhaust of the gas turbine is utilized to produce the steam to carry out the steam turbine process. Combined Cycle Gas Turbines, because of their quick startup time provide high operational flexibility for adjusting the load output faster and load predictability therefore modeling of gas turbines, which produces about two-third of the total power output of the CCGT, becomes important. Several models of gas turbines have been proposed but none of them is able to fully explain the behavior of a gas turbine. The following report presents an initial and preliminary effort in modeling of single shaft combined cycle gas turbine using MATLAB/Simulink describing various controlling units in the operation of CCGT. Various studies have been carried out using this Simulink model so as to describe the behavior of various parameters by varying gas turbine conditions and also the variation in the efficiency of CCGT overall process is studied when the gas turbine efficiency is varied. Furthermore, the effect of the temperature control using practical data has been studied by plotting various graphs and examining them.', u'title': u'Performance Analysis of CCGT Power Plant Using MATLAB/Simulink Based Simulation.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.5 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'Minor Project 1 done for the 6th Semester under the guidance of Shri J. N. Rai and also with the expertise industrial guidance from the officials of Pragati Power Plant (PPCL).\n\nA worldwide trend in the development of power systems is to build interconnections with the goal to achieve economic benefits. Such large interconnected systems can cover many countries or even wide continental areas. Interconnections of power systems may offer significant technical, economic and environmental advantages, such as pooling of large power generation stations, sharing of spinning reserve and use of most economic energy resources taking into account also ecological constraints: nuclear power stations at special locations, hydro energy from remote areas, and solar energy from desert areas and connection of large off-shore wind farms. On the other hand, as power transfer grow, the power system becomes increasingly more complex to operate and the system can become less secure for riding through the major outages. It may lead to large power flows with inadequate control, excessive reactive power in various parts of the system, large dynamic swings between different parts of the system and bottlenecks, and thus the full potential of transmission interconnections cannot be utilized. The following report continues the study of previous report by analyzing the power flow control and stability (both steady state and transient state) of a synchronous generator driven by a shaft of the combined cycle configuration (single shaft) which was studied in the previous report using MATLAB simulation. The report also contains a case study describing the operation of a combined cycle power plant of GTPS-IPGCL (Gas turbine power station) and the parameters which are measured and controlled for the proper operation of the generator and various technological advancements for control operation.', u'title': u'Performance Analysis of CCGT-Generator Using MATLAB/Simulink Based Simulation And A Case Study Based on Real-Time Data from Pragati Power Corporation Limited.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.1 ~ 2017.5', u'description': u'\u27a2\tDetermined relay settings for SEL 387A and 351S relays, CT size and breaker size on a distribution network based on short circuit analysis.\n\u27a2\tIntegrated device co-ordination scheme in relay settings using time dial and pickup values generated from S& C Coordinaide tool.\n\nProtection Schemes Implemented : Differential, Over Current, Under-frequency, Under-voltage and CT and breaker selection\n\nTools Used : S&C Coordinaide, AcSELerator Quickset for configuring SEL 387A and 351S Relays, Relays tested using RTDS at FREEDM Systems Center', u'title': u'Protection Scheme Designing For a Distribution Substation'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.11 ~ 2013.11', u'description': u'Major Project 1 (7th Semester) carried out under the guidance of Shri J. N. Rai for partial fulfillment for the award of Degree of Bachelor of Technology in Electrical Engineering.\n\nFossil fuels such as coal, oil, and gas have been the primary means of energy generation for many centuries. But, however there is a new interest in renewable sources such as those derived from wind power, hydro-power etc. These are more universally available and they can potentially help with global warming by reducing the carbon footprint. Then, there is a third kind of energy source based on photovoltaic conversion of sunlight into electricity by certain widely available semiconductors, which is arguably the cleanest, most ubiquitous, and potentially the most reliable alternative. The following report presented the analyses of the characteristics of solar panel through detailed analysis of the characteristics by using MATLAB simulation and plotting various graphs for the same. A CCGT-Generator model along with Solar panel\u2019s is modeled to understand the load flow by both sources of energy. The report also presents the features of construction of a Solar Power Plant which is under construction by IPGCL (Indraprastha Power Generation Corporation Limited).', u'title': u'Performance Analysis of CCGT with PV Solar Panel using MATLAB/Simulink Based Simulation'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.11 ~ 2016.11', u'description': u'Implemented a communication setup such that the data concentrator, SEL RTAC 3530, acts on a multi-protocol scheme and is connected to a SCADA Master simulated using Distributed Test Manager via DNP3 Protocol. Field Device 1 (SEL-651R) is connected to the RTAC using DNP3 Protocol and Field Device 2 (SEL 451) is connected using IEC 61850 MMS protocol.', u'title': u'Implementation of Multi-Protocol Scheme Using SEL RTAC 3530 Connected to DTM As Master'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.5 ~ 2014.5', u'description': u'Major Project 2 done for the 8th Semester under the guidance of Shri J. N. Rai and also with the expertise industrial guidance from the officials of BSES for hardware realisation.\n\nThe aim of this project was to determine the distance (in kilometres) of underground cable faults from base station. Underground cable systems are found in many urban areas. When a fault occurs, at that time the repairing process in relation to that particular cable is a dicey issue due to not knowing the exact location of the cable fault. The proposed system helped to find the exact location of the fault.\nThe project applied Ohms law that is when a low Direct Current voltage is applied at the feeder end through a series resistor (Cable lines), then the current would vary as a function of the location of fault in the cable. The project was assembled with a set of resistors representing the equivalent circuit of a 3-phase cable and fault creation is made by a set of limit switches at known distances to cross check the accuracy.', u'title': u'Development Of Alternate Method For The Detection Of Underground Fault In Industry'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.3 ~ 2017.5', u'description': u'\u27a2 A prototype system was designed with a goal to determine the minimum system requirements. The design assumed that a standby generator would be used to provide the supplemental power when needed.\n\n\u27a2 A web search was done to determine the actual components that were available that would best meet the design. \n\n\u27a2 A detailed economic assessment of the project was done. The study had both the energy output estimate and the total cost estimate of the system, as well as LCOE.', u'title': u'Design of an Off-grid PV system for a cabin in Ashville NC'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2013.1 ~ 2014.5', u'description': u'Worked on biomedical embedded system which acquires ECG electrocardiogram signal as well as body vibration signals from the human body using Lab VIEW interfacing with Arduino Mega 3600, ADXL 365 \nAccelerometer, AD 620 Instrumentation Amplifier, GSM300 Module. \n', u'title': u'Senior Design Level Project'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.9 ~ 2015.9', u'description': u'Through combinations of renewables and storage technologies, power system planners can better predict and plan the power flow between generation and demand.  This article identifies the impact of renewable generation with and without energy storage in relation to consumer demand. This paper will examine the generation of key commercial renewable technologies such as wind and solar which provide reliability concerns to the local network due to variability and uncertainty in generation.  Additionally, the generation of solar and wind will be examined in relation to typical load demands.  Lastly, this paper will examine the technology and potential impact of energy storage technologies for system stability and controllability of variable renewable generation.', u'title': u'Combining Renewable Energy Integration and Energy Storage for Power System Planning'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.3 ~ 2015.3', u'description': u'Validating Test and Training data.\nTrained the data  with 70%  and the testing is done on the remaining 30% of the dataset with different kernel function. \nPrediction of data for both test and train of the different classifier. \nBuilding of fisher LDA for classification of two classes for test and train data.\nBuilding SVM using different kernel function and changing the box constrain .\nFinding the confusion matrix in terms of TP ,TN, FP & FN for both train and test data. Comparison is done between the different classifier.\nPlotting the ROC curve to find AUC,EER & decidability.\n', u'title': u'Using Support Vector Machine(SVM),Pricipal Component Analysis(PCA) and Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)classification for breast cancer detection'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2015.10', u'description': u'With the change in climate and depletion of fossil fuel sources, the United States is looking to increase renewable generation to 30 percent by 2025 through the use of federal and state incentives. Additionally, the U.S. has seen an explosion of wind generation over the past two decades with an average annual increase of 13 GWh from 2001 to 2014.  With the rapid introduction of renewable generation, traditional wholesale electricity markets and regional transmission owners are integrating new designs to compensate for the increase in variable and uncertain power generation sources. ', u'title': u'Power Distribution Management'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2015.10', u'description': u'\nIt uses fisher LDA to maximize between class scatter and minimize within class. \nPCA is applied to reduce dimension. Getting (n-c) principal components.\nPca projection using covariance  matrix. Finding the mean of the pca components of train .\nAt first I took an empty array for within and between class matrix\nTaking the number of instances of train as 6 and test as 4\nFinding between class matrix: (m1\u2212m2)*(m1 \u2212m2)T\nFinding within class matrix: (xt \u2212m1)*(xt \u2212m1)T\nApplying fisher lda by multiplying inverse of within scatter by between scatter.\nUsing cascade of PCA and LDA by multiplying weight of Wpca and Wlda. Implement it on imposter and genuine. \n\n', u'title': u'Face recognition using Eigen and Fisher Faces  methods'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.2 ~ 2015.2', u'description': u' ECG signal is enormous in size, compression algo- rithms  must be used to make the whole tele-cardiology faster and  efficient.  A faster  solution  is of crucial  importance  for diagnoses and treatment of cardiovascular  diseases. To make body sensor network energy efficient, we performed ECG analysis and data mining on the compressed ECG signal using Correlation based feature extraction and k-nearest neighbors and Radial bases function as a classification technique. \n', u'title': u'Distinguishing Between Ventricular Tachycardia and Ventricular Fibrillation From Compressed ECG Signal in wireless Body Sensor Networks.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.9 ~ 2013.9', u'description': u' 1.Manufacturing Industry:Overview(Present day need of manufacturing), Fabrication, 7 tank pre treatment process ,Powder coating paint and Wiring\n2. Details about MCC panel (Motor Control Centre):  KWH Meter,BUS BAR Concept, Holding Circuitd. Switch Fuse Unit, Overload Relay and Power Contactor\n3. PLC :  PLC based dual starter and comparison with normal wired starter\n', u'title': u'Project on Industrial Training'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.3 ~ 2015.3', u'description': u'T. Pumped Hydro \u2013 pumped hydro utilizes an induction machine as a pump during low demand periods to pump water to a reservoir and operates as a generator during high demand periods.\n2. Gravity storage \u2013 similar to pumped hydro but instead of pumping water to reservoir, gravity storage uses water to pump a piston. During high demand periods, the machine reverses and, using the piston\u2019s weight, the water reverses direction to generate power.\n3. Batteries \u2013 utilize chemical reactions (salt bridge, lead, lithium, hydrogen) to store electrons which can then provide electrons during discharge. \n4. Super-capacitors \u2013 use energization between metals (magnetization) to store electrons which can then be discharged.\n\nv. Fly-wheels \u2013 utilizes moment of inertia to store energy via an object in motion.', u'title': u'Energy Storage Technologies'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.8 ~ 2015.8', u'description': u'The general concept for renewable generation is through the conversion of natural energy sources such as sunlight, geothermal heat, water, and wind energy to electricity.  The benefit of these technologies is that, in general, these renewable sources tied to the main electric grid can support the power demand by local load and avoid long distance transmission. This ultimately reduces the loading, and thus any overloading or conjection, of transmission lines during the peak loads. However, there are certain limitations on power generations from these renewable sources due to their variability and reliability in generation. For instance, solar power is generated from sunlight and is contingent upon cloud coverage and irradiation angle throughout the day. Similarly, wind generation is dependent upon the wind velocity being at an appropriate speed in order to produce non-distorted generation.', u'title': u'Renewable Power Generation'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.11 ~ 2014.11', u'description': u'Using MATLAB , finding out the ramp error, settling time, percentage overshoot,  gain crossover frequency, and phase margin. \n1. Cascade Lag\n2. Rate Feedback\n3. Cascade PI\n4. Cascade PID\nComparison of compensated and uncompensated system. ', u'title': u'The design procedure  to improve the performance of the plant using ROOT locus and BODE plots.'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2015.8 ~ 2015.8', u'description': u'Worked on project Vehicle Access CAN based Network; Got trained in understanding about CAN ISO/OSI model; Worked on the significant problems and proposed solutions for drivers during traffic; Learned about In-vehicle network simulation software i.e CAN communication in Simulink and main stages to build the transmitting and receiving CAN model; Worked on CAN electronic circuit, CAN transceiver MCP2510 with Microcontroller-PIC18F458; Worked on (CANSPI protocol) in developing C- Code In Vehicle Network for data exchange between 2 PIC\u2019s;\nTested and analyzed signal in lab', u'title': u'Vehicle Access CAN based Network'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.10 ~ 2014.10', u'description': u'1. Studied the effects of Multipath in a Two-Ray Model on Bit Error Rate (BER).\n2. Path loss is calculated by Okumura-Hata model, friis formula and another formula which includes the effect of multipath due to a perfectly conducting ground. \n3. BER dependency is observed by varying the physical parameters in Analytical model and empirical model and by comparing the two results calculation of BER in Okamura- Hata model is easy when compared to Analytical model because of the reflections that caused complexities. \n4. Finally, the results were verified with MATLAB.\n', u'title': u'Studied project that investigates the effects of the ground reflections on the bit-error-rate in a mobile wireless communication system.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.5 ~ 2015.5', u'description': u'1.\tThe objective of this project is to provide an understanding to the dSPACE software, the dSPACE DS1104 controller board, and their use in development and implementation of a simple temperature control system by using temperature sensors.\n2.\tLearned great understanding of Control Desk Environment\n3.\tLearned Interfacing dSPACE Software to the Experiment using Simulink\n', u'title': u'dSPACE software, the dSPACE DS1104 controller board, and their use in development and implementation of a temperature control system'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.6 ~ 2016.6', u'description': u'1.\tModelled motor, motor controller, Battery, PI controller with road speed and road torque as commanded input\n2.\tSimulated and plotted Road speed/torque/Power, Motor Voltage/Current/Power, Battery Voltage/Current/Power, Battery Voltage Error, Controller gain using Matlab and Simulink.\n3.\tHad a clear understanding of motoring which consumes battery and regeneration that charges the battery\n', u'title': u'Battery Electric Vehicle simulation using Matlab/Simulink'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.3 ~ 2015.3', u'description': u'The project cover a broad range of EMI topics beginning with electromagnetic theory. Basic fundamentals of point charges, Maxwell\u2019s equations, and finally transverse electromagnetic waves are examined. Sources of EMI are discussed such as conducted EMI, transients, ground loops, common and differential mode currents, coupling, and cross-talk. Major contributors to radiated EMI will be identified, and design solutions are proposed to reduce the magnitude of the radiated fields. These proposed solutions are primarily focus on PCB layout design, but will also include shielding, coupling paths, and ground loops. A flowchart is also presented in order to identify EMI problems and reduce emissions. For the major problems which contribute to radiated EMI, specific circuits are designed which intentionally exacerbate the amount of emissions. This is done to classify which circuits contribute the largest amount of EMI emissions from any product which is to be sold on the market. Using the circuits designed to exacerbate radiated EMI, comparisons are made to a good design to identify the increase in radiated EMI. By identifying which circuit issues contribute the most to the amount of radiated EMI, design considerations can be implemented which will yield the highest reduction in emissions for almost any product. Finally, a case study is performed on a prototype circuit board in order to prepare for success during EMI testing.', u'title': u'Switching Power Supply Design:  EMI Reduction techniques.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.11 ~ 2015.11', u'description': u'According to the understanding and investigation of the research paper, geometrical configuration of the gold and silver nanoparticles was optimized to obtain an enhanced Fano resonance which comes with various potential applications. Secondly, important fact observed was the enhanced intensity of Fano resonance that is detectable by any standard spectroscopic technique when the radius of the gold nanoparticle is close to three times the radius of silver nanoparticle with a shorter distance separation between them. The aspect ratio of radius of Au:Ag nanoparticles which is close to 3:1 gave us simulation results where we obtained prominent intensity of Fano resonance. Finally, we arrived at a conclusion with the help of simulation using MATLAB and DDSCAT that resulted enhanced Fano resonance is induced only by the longitudinal component of the dimer Surface Plasmonic Resonance (SFR). The surrounding medium in which the experiment is performed is water with a refractive index nm= 1.33. ', u'title': u'Enhanced Fano Resonance in Asymmetrical Au:Ag Heterodimers'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2015.10', u'description': u'Focus is pointed on the related technology, the inherent system complexity and aspects of customer acceptance', u'title': u'The Role of Driver Assistance Systems in Traffic Scenario'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.4 ~ 2016.4', u'description': u'Designed a controller to simulate the unit step response of the original system with the linear-state-variable feedback constants using MATLAB', u'title': u'PWM-Switch Modeling of DC-DC Converters (Power Electronics)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.8 ~ 2014.8', u'description': u'1. Impedance matching method and frii\u2019s formula were used to calculate the variation of Bit error     Rate.\n2. The path gain in the link closure relationship is done for both near and far field cases by considering two dipole antennas in a parallel-in-echelon arrangement.\n3. Wireless communication modulation schemes used in the project are Frequency shift keying and quadrature phased shift keying. \n4. Finally all the results are simulated with MATLAB and verified with FEKO. \n', u'title': u'Studied RF Propagation Path Gain and variation of Bit Error Rate with respect to near and far field by varying the distance of two dipole antennas in Wireless data transmission.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.4 ~ 2015.4', u'description': u'In this project we focused on the economical consideration of standalone hybrid systems having PV and Biomass for electrical production in remote areas of India. Also in this project a simulation approach has been carried out for designing stand alone grid for remote areas. The average solar radiation and quantity of biomass required data are to  predict the general performance of the generating system. The batteries can also be used in this system to store the extra energy which can further be used for backup. Also the extra power is used to supply to the grid. Here the simulation is carried out using HOMER software. The results and analysis can used to improve the development of the proposed model.', u'title': u'Design of a Photovoltaic-Biogas Hybrid Power Generation System for Remote Areas in India Using Homer Software'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2010.8 ~ 2010.12', u'description': u'\u2022 Designed, built and tested a 15V to 5V buck converter using Texas Instruments TPS40200 buck controller.\n\u2022 DC/DC converter met all the specifications of efficiency, voltage ripple, regulation, transient response, over-current protection and phase margin.\n\u2022 Learnt the design trade-offs between specifications.\n', u'title': u'Design, Build and Testing of Buck Converter using PSpice and Eagle'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'\u2022\tAnalyzed real-life EEG data to differentiate healthy people from people suffering with Alzheimer\u2019s disease.\n\u2022\tUtilized wavelet transforms to remove noise from the EEG data.\n\u2022\tExtracted features such as activity level in different cerebral lobes while subject is at rest to separate the two classes.\n', u'title': u'Data Analysis and Feature Extraction for Identifying Alzheimer\u2019s Disease using MATLAB'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'\u2022\tDeveloped an optical setup to scatter white light and project the entire spectrum on the DMD Discovery board.\n\u2022\tThe reflected spectrum from the DMD was focused onto a small point by using multiple optical lenses.\n\u2022\tPrototype for optical filter was developed by implementing images created in MATLAB.\n', u'title': u'Implementation of Programmable Optical Spectral Filter using DMD and Discovery1100 board'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'\u2022 Programmed the DSK6713 board using C to filter an audio signal into different bands of frequency. \n\u2022 DIP switch input was used to select the bands and the signal strength of each band was displayed on LEDs. \n', u'title': u'Implementation of 3-band Audio Equalizer in C'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'\u2022\tUtilized four classifiers - LDA, QDA, KNN and CART, in a wrapper based approach (SFFS) for feature selection in a Microarray dataset. Experimental data evaluated targeted drugs\u2019 effects on cancer cells.\n\u2022\tMicroarray data consisted of 57 samples and 465 features for two different cell lines. The selected features were used to predict the classes of 5 unlabeled drugs.\n\u2022\tResubstitution error, Leave-one-out error and Bootstrap errors were estimated for all of the classifiers. The results were verified against a random dataset having the same distribution as the original data.\n', u'title': u'Implemented and Evaluated Feature Selection Algorithm in Microarray Data using MATLAB'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'\u2022\tTested 40 chips on VLCT and bench to verify functionality and electrical characteristics of NAND gate (SN7400).\n\u2022\tPerformed statistical analysis to verify repeatability, reproducibility and process stability. \n', u'title': u'Integrated Circuit Testing on VLCT (Automatic Test Equipment) using Pascal'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'\u2022\tDeveloped an algorithm to put pieces of a puzzle together from a photo containing all the pieces spread randomly.    \n\u2022\tUtilized local thresholding technique to reduce noise and image properties like correlation and mean to identify correct location.\n', u'title': u'Development and Implementation of Puzzle Solving Algorithm using MATLAB'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'\u2022\tAnalyzed real-life ECG data to differentiate healthy people from people suffering with arrhythmia. \n\u2022\tDeveloped a code to count heart beats, time interval, and detect arrhythmia like Bradycardias and Tachycardias.\n', u'title': u'Data Analysis and Algorithm Development for Detecting Arrhythmia using MATLAB'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'\u2022\tDeveloped a variant of Relief algorithm for feature selection. Implemented the algorithm on Microarray datasets of Ovarian cancer having 54 samples and 1536 features, and Colon Cancer having 36 samples and 7457 features.\n\u2022\tTested and compared the algorithm results with original Relief and another variant using a Na\xefve-Bayes classifier.\n', u'title': u'Algorithm Development for Feature Selection in High-dimensional Data using MATLAB'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'\u2022\tModeled a battery containing 1000mAH state-of-charge and a fully charged voltage of 4V and fully discharged voltage of 3V.\n\u2022\tDesigned a battery charger using a current controlled buck to charge the battery with a constant current of \u2018C\u2019 rate (1 A). The battery discharges with a constant output voltage of 4V through a voltage controlled boost. \n', u'title': u'Design of Battery Charging and Discharging circuit using PSpice'}]
