projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2015.9 ~ 2015.12', u'description': u'Robotics Course Project (2015)\nAdvisor \u2013 Prof. Dennis Hong (Department of Mechanical and Aerospace Engineering, University of California Los Angeles)\n\n\u25cfThe goal of the project was to map and analyse the coordinate frames of the open source Darwin OP and to perform a particular physical task.\n\u25cfWorked with WeBots (Simulator) and MATLAB to simulate the motion of Darwin prior to the actual run.\n\n', u'title': u'Analysis and Control of Darwin OP'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.7 ~ 2015.5', u'description': u'Undergraduate Thesis (2015)\nAdvisor \u2013 Prof. Hemanth Kumar (Department of Mechanical Engineering, National Institute of Technology Karnataka)\n\nThe project involves using Bouc-Wen and Modified Bouc-Wen models to characterize the hysteric behavior of MR fluid dampers. The Bouc-Wen model parameters are optimally calculated from the experimental hysteric behavior obtained by dynamic tests performed on the fabricated damper for different input currents by minimizing the mean square error between analytical and experimental results. This is done by solving the multi-objective optimization problem through the combination of Non-dominated Sorting Genetic Algorithm \u2013 II (NSGA II) and Pareto optimal scheme. The Bouc-Wen and Modified Bouc-Wen models are modeled in MATLAB Simulink and used in the optimization technique to find the optimal parameter values by comparing it with the given experimental values.  \n\n\u25cf Modelling and analysis of Semi-Active Suspension systems using ADAMS-MATLAB Co-simulation Environment \n\u25cf Implemented PID, Skyhook and Ground Hook control for the system and compared the responses of the suspension model for each strategy.\n\u25cf Generated parametric Bouc Wen and Modified Bouc Wen models of the MR Fluid, solving for a Multi Objective Optimisation Problem. Implemented parametric models using MATLAB Simulink Environment.', u'title': u'Analytical Modelling of Magnetorheological Fluids (Undergraduate Thesis)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.3 ~ 2016.6', u'description': u'High Temperature Mechanical Design Project (2016)\nAdvisor \u2013 Dr. Nasr Ghoniem (Department of Mechanical and Aerospace Engineering, University of California Los Angeles)\n\n\u25cfModelled and simulated the mechanical and thermal effects on an automobile disc brake during braking using COMSOL. \n\u25cfOptimized vane profiles for maximum cooling using Solidworks design study and co-simulation using COMSOL\n', u'title': u'Multiphysics Analysis of Automobile Disc Brakes (COMSOL/SOLIDWORKS)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.1 ~ 2016.3', u'description': u'Compliant Mechanisms Project (2016)\nAdvisor \u2013 Prof. Jonathan Hopkins (Department of Mechanical and Aerospace Engineering, University of California Los Angeles)\n\n\u25cfDesigned a Flexure based Micro Mirror System - driven at resonant frequencies using Solidworks for precision applications. \n\u25cfPerformed FEA and frequency optimisation using ANSYS and designed for MEMS fabrication capabilities. \n', u'title': u'Flexure Based Micro Mirror Design'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.6 ~ 2014.6', u'description': u'Summer Internship  (2014) - Tampere University of Technology, Finland\nDepartment of  Mechanical Engineering and Industrial Design\nAdvisor \u2013 Dr. Riku Heikilla \n\nThe project involved the development of the environmental control unit (air flow, temperature, clean room and humidity) and control logic for the TUT Microfactory concept. New modules were designed and manufactured to fit the current design, Electronics were incorporated and controlled with the help of an Arduino micro controller.', u'title': u'Micro Factory Environmental Control'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.1 ~ 2017.3', u'description': u'Designed and developed a novel 3D printed GoPro Mount.\n\n\u25cf Developed and optimized 3D models using SOLIDWORKS and fabricated 3D printed prototypes.\n\u25cf Evaluated designs at every stage of iteration against applied stresses and fatigue analysis using ANSYS.\n\u25cf Developed rendering for consumer studies using Keyshot.\n\u25cf Conducted market survey and consumer testing of early prototypes. \n', u'title': u'3D Printed GoPro Mount'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.4 ~ 2015.4', u'description': u'INTEL IOT Hackaton Bangalore | India\n\nWireless camera interface providing translation to user through Google translate along with text reading and definition', u'title': u'iRis - Project for Intel IoT Roadshow 2015'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.9 ~ 2015.12', u'description': u'Nano Fabrication Course Project (2015)\nAdvisor \u2013 Prof. Yong Chen (Department of Mechanical and Aerospace Engineering, University of California Los Angeles)\n\nThe goal of the nano project is to design nano materials and nano fabrication technology to improve the efficiency and reduce the costs of the solar cells. Proposed models for a new innovative solar cell with capabilities of achieving higher efficiency theoretically as compared to the current cells. The parts of the standard solar cells modified includes the Electron Transport medium, the anti reflective layer,  and overall fabrication techniques to keep production cost low', u'title': u'Nanotechnology for High-efficient Low-Cost Solar Cells'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.1 ~ 2015.1', u'description': u'MIT Media Lab Design Innovation Project (2015)\nAdvisor \u2013 Mr. Rajesh Nair (MIT Media Lab)\n\nDesigned and developed initial prototypes of a cheap , affordable and completely mechanical prosthetic arm for double amputees.Working with various school for the disabled in Gujarat , the project was completed as a part of the MIT Media Lab Design Innovation Workshop.  ', u'title': u'ForLIMB (MIT Design Innovation 2015)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.5 ~ 2015.5', u'description': u'Summer Internship (2015) - Tata Center for Technology and Design, India\nIndian Institute of Technology, Bombay \n\nThe project aims to build a Digital Microscopic system that can scan the entire cell slide at the source point.The digital image can then be transferred digitally to an urban setting where further analysis can take place. Digitally transferring the cell slide to a cyto technician replaces the physical transfer of the slide across the health centers and higher level hospitals.\n\n\u25cfDesigned and implemented the prototype of an affordable, portable and robust Digital Microscopic Device for scanning cancerous cells at source point.\n\u25cfDeveloped lens arrangements and worked with image processing to manipulate and stitch together the captured images.\n\n\n', u'title': u'Project Drishti'}]

summary: Mechanical Engineer pursuing my masters at UCLA specializing in Mechanical Design and Robotics. I have worked in areas ranging from rapid prototyping, mechanical design, robotics, analysis, electronics and control systems. I enjoy working in an interdisciplinary environment and the lab is my favorite place. I build, test and refine till I get it right. I believe that simple and efficient designs are always the hardest to create and strive towards developing affordable, robust and user-centric devices.\n\nI use CREO and SOLIDWORKS for mechanical design including surfacing, ANSYS and COMSOL for design analysis and PTC Windchill for managing CAD  data. On the programming side, I work with MATLAB and LabVIEW. Working in the consumer robotic industry I also have experience with in home user testing of prototypes. \n\nApart from my work I love building and flying drones, designing web pages, tinkering with Photoshop and I enjoy taking part in hackathons and talking about the latest gadgets! \n\nPlease feel free to look at all my work on my website:  http://hkkrishnan.com/  .

facilitate proper removal of heat from the source.\n\u25cf  Analyzed the temperatures at specific regions to attain useful thermal map.\n\u25cf  Achieved the design objective of maintaining the temperatures below 65C.\n', u'title': u'Thermal management of high power devices using ANSYS Icepak'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.8 ~ 2016.8', u'description': u'\u25cf A laser is shown through a polymer asymmetric in x-y plane.\n\u25cf Generated an explicit FEM code to map the wave i.e the density variation as a function of position.\n\u25cf Utilized principle of virtual work to obtain the projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2016.5 ~ 2016.5', u'description': u'Finite element Analysis for studying heat transfer in a chimney made up of concrete and brick was conducted in Matlab and Abaqus-CAE. The results for temperature distribution and heat flux were compared. The FE analysis was performed using following Element types and results for each element type were compared:\na) 4 \u2013 Node Quadrilateral Element (Element type \u2013 DC2D4 in Abaqus-CAE).\nb) 8 \u2013 Node Quadrilateral Element (Element type \u2013 DC2D8 in Abaqus-CAE).\nc) 6 \u2013 Node Triangular Element (Element type \u2013 DC2D6 in Abaqus-CAE).\n\nMesh convergence study was performed before using each element type in order to determine the optimum mesh size or element size required for meshing and getting accurate result.', u'title': u'Finite Element Analysis of Heat transfer in a composite wall using ABAQUS solver and validating with Matlab code'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.2 ~ now', u'description': u'-    Analysis for the time dependent response of FRP\u2019s using ABAQUS and Python under thermal conduction.\n-    Effects of thermal stresses/stress concentrations at the interfaces on the thermo-mechanical deformations were studied.\n', u'title': u'Thermal Stress Analysis of fiber-reinforced polymeric composites'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.5 ~ 2016.5', u'description': u'Most commercial heavy duty truck trailers are equipped with either a two sensor,\none modulator (2S1M) or four sensor, two modulator (4S2M) anti-lock braking system (ABS).\nIn the case of trailers equipped with the 2S1M system, it has been observed that placement of the\nsensor, whether on the rear or front axle, has great effect on the skid wear rate of the trailer tires.\nA preliminary study, performed by Merrill , has shown a significant increase in wear rates in\ncases with the sensor placement being on the front axle. It is the intention of this paper to further\nexplore the effect of the sensor placement through the acquisition of more field data. From the\ncollected information it has been determined that placement of the 2S1M system on the front\naxle leads to a significant increase in rear axle tire wear. It is the recommendation of this study\nthat anti-lock braking system sensors, if only two are to be used, be mounted to the rear axle.\nThis will greatly reduce overall skid wear of the trailer tires ensuring a cost efficient as well as\nsafe trailer environment.', u'title': u'Effect of Anti-Lock Braking System Placement on Skid Wear in Heavy duty Truck Tires'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.10 ~ 2016.10', u'description': u'The task was to develop a time-domain simulation to solve the differential equation of motion using the Euler integration approach and then use that time-domain solution to identify the magnitude of the vibration response', u'title': u'Numerical integration using MATLAB to solve the Single Degree of Freedom Forced Vibration equation of motion and extract frequency response function'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.2 ~ now', u'description': u'-Simulation of Ball to Plate impact analysis is carried out using element deletion criteria\n-The ball is modelled as a linear material(rigid body) and for the plate, simple bi-linear plasticity definition is used.\n-An element deletion criteria is used which allows the ball to rupture the plate and pass through it\n-The ball is given a velocity of 40 km/s and the edges of the plate are constrained in all degrees of freedom.\n-Model is analyzed for stresses  developed in the plate\n', u'title': u'High velocity Impact Analysis of 4340 steel plate coated with  Polyurea.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.2 ~ now', u'description': u'1)  Simulation of Forming(Manufacturing process) a channel in a metal sheet using contact pairs is performed in ABAQUS/standard.\n\n2)The Objective was to determine the forces acting on the punch during the forming process and determine how well the channel is formed wit the assumed blank holder force settings and coefficient of friction.\n3)Blank is modeled as a 2d plane strain model (assuming the metal sheet is sufficiently long), high strength steel which undergoes considerable work hardening as it deforms plastically\n\n4The blank is modeled as a deformable body  and the Punch, Blank holder, and Die are modeled as rigid surfaces, the definition of contact pairs is used rather than general contact.\n\n5)Surface to surface contact is defined between die -blank and holder with some coefficient of friction\n\n6) As significant nonlinearity is introduced(because of frictionless sliding, changing contact conditions and inelastic material behavior) the maximum number of increments are kept higher.\n\n7) Model meshes with reduced integration, enhanced hourglass control to reduce analysis time and shear locking.\n\n8)The maximum plastic strain of the model is compared with the failure strain of  the material to determine failure of the material during Forming process\n\n', u'title': u'Quasi-static non-linear analysis of forming process in a metal sheet (contact analysis) using ABAQUS/standard'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.11 ~ 2015.11', u'description': u'Estimation of PACEJKA Tire Coefficients (Load dependent parameters, Lateral force parameters) from a given Tire Test Data using  MATLAB', u'title': u'Estimation of PACEJKA Tire Coefficients from a Fatigue analysis using ncode design life using stress life and strain life approach.\n', u'title': u'Analysis and Topology optimization of Compressor Connecting Rod using ANSYS workbench 12.1.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2015.10', u'description': u'Improving Thermal conductivity of materials is becoming increasingly important in domains ranging from tire industry and electronic packaging to Aerospace industry since  heat dissipation is a crucial factor.\n\nIncreased heat dissipation is required in tire composites to enhance their service life and performance\n\nHigh performance, high speed and long service life are some of the requirements of tire industry.\n\nESBR (Emulsion-polymerized styrene-butadiene rubber) which is a common material used in tire tread composites, brakes and conveyer belts can be modified for higher thermal conductivity.\n\nESBR is cheaper than other butadiene rubbers and hence widely used over styrene butadiene rubber but  the disadvantage is that it has low conductivity.\n', u'title': u'Thermal Analysis using Abaqus and Python to find the effect of micro fillers on the overall thermal conductivity of a polymeric composite- ESBR.'}]

Research the vehicle parameters and use at least nonlinear parameters for simulation.\nModelling done on : Quarter car model, Half Car model & Full Car model.', u'title': u'Modelling and simulation of a full vehicle suspension system for bounce, pitch and roll conditions under linear & non-linear parameters'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.6 ~ 2015.6', u'description': u'Project done at Usha Martin Pvt Ltd:\nTesting of wire drawing dies, Maintenance of die block, Design & Installation of lump cleaning mechanism, Troubleshooting, Documentation for industry for future reference, Overall decrease in cost due to tensile breakages.\nConcepts:\nMachine Design, Maintenance Engineering, AUTOCAD', u'title': u'Reduction in tension breakages in 23AC wet wire drawing machine & overall optimization of cost due to tensile breakages\'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2017.8 ~ 2017.8', u'description': u'Study of material handling in Ranger Design Pvt Ltd, Rochester and applied Lean approach to decrease lead time and improve its process through various lean tools like DMAIC, SIPOC, Fish bone diagram & process Flow charts', u'title': u'Lean Six Sigma_Yellow Belt'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.5 ~ 2016.5', u'description': u'Academic Research Project at IIT(ISM) Dhanbad:\nGlass fiber reinforced polymer composites (GFRP) are used for critical industrial components performing under different environmental conditions. Tribological properties of GFRP composites developed by Vacuum bagging process (glass fiber reinforced with bis phenol epoxy resin) were experimentally investigated under three different sliding environments, (a) Dry sliding, (b) Oil-lubricated sliding and (c) Inert gas (argon). The counter face used in these experiments was En 31 steel hardened to 60 HRC, two sliding velocities and three normal loads. Results obtained experimentally shows that sliding in inert gas (argon) provides the maximum value of coefficient of friction followed by dry sliding and oil-lubricated sliding. FESEM analysis of the worn surfaces reveals that the high wear in inert gas (argon) results from an easy separation of fibers from the polymer matrix under high friction. During oil-lubricated sliding, the softer epoxy resin body matrix between layers of glass fibers plays an important role in lowering the coefficient of friction. It is proposed that the lubricant gets adsorbed on steel surface and the slight initial wear of the polymer also serves in effect as a \u201clubricant storage reservoir\u201d then the protruding glass fibers pick up lubricant molecules to effectively avoid fiber to steel contact and ensure effective thin film lubrication. In the dry sliding conditions and without oil between the fibers, they undergo bending at the ends, and under the higher force of friction more wear increases rapidly.', u'title': u'Tribological behavior of Glass Fiber Reinforced Polymer(GFRP) composites sliding under dry,oil lubricated and inert gas environmental conditions'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.5 ~ 2011.5', u'description': u'Bachelor's Academic project:\nDesign of Plain Journal self lubricated hydrodynamic bearing.\nStudy of pressure distribution\nfabrication of test rig.\nConcepts used:\nDesign of Machine Elements, Hydrodynamic bearing, AUTOCAD, ANSYS, Manufacturing process.', u'title': u'Design and development of test rig for measurement of pressure in plain journal bearing under variable load.'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2010.4 ~ 2011.1', u'description': u'Worked on designing and manufacturing an all terrain vehicle to withstand the extreme terrains. Our team participated for the first time in 2011 BAJA main event in Pithampur (near Indore), India. \n\nKey Contributions :- \n> Designed the Steering arm and optimize it for Off-road performance .\n> Designed and fabricated Chassis, and suspension components  \n> Performed Material Procurement for powertrain components. \n>Performed dynamic analysis using MSc Adams.\n> Performed drive train simulations/transmission modeling  using MATLAB for the custom built rotary gear train. It was done to optimize the gear ratios for maximizing the performance of the ATV.  ', u'title': u'Design of All-Terrain Vehicle for SAE-India BAJA 2011 - Team Blitzkrieg'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.4 ~ 2014.5', u'description': u'>The Objective was to numerically solve the flat plate turbulent boundary layer equations in MATLAB. \n> Implemented the one equation Reichardt model for turbulent viscosity calculation in the inner region and Clauser  model for turbulent viscosity calculation in the outer region \n>Implemented Crank Nicholson scheme for discretization of terms.\n> Validated  the numerically computed turbulent velocity profile at different axial locations on the flat plate with the empirical velocity profile as per the Logarithmic Law of the wall\n>  Analyzed the effect of changing the model parameters on the computed results.\n> Compared the numerically computed axial variations of Boundary layer thickness and Skin-friction Coefficient with the empirical correlations . ', u'title': u'Numerical Solution of 2D Turbulent Boundary Layer Equations using 1-equation Turbulence models in MATLAB'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.11 ~ 2013.12', u'description': u'> Derived the Modified Viscous Stability equation(Orr-Sommerfield Equation) for Flat Plate Boundary Layer Asymptotic Suction\n> Numerically solved the fourth order Orr-Sommerfield Equation equation  using fourth order Runge Kutta method.\n>Applied Grahm-Schmidt Orthonormalization at each step to ensure Linear Independence of the Viscous and Inviscid solution. \n> Plotted the  resulting neutral curve and validate the critical Reynolds number with theory', u'title': u'Numerical Solution of Orr-Sommerfield Equation for 2-D Asymptotic Suction Problem in MATLAB'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.2 ~ 2011.2', u'description': u'>Designed a quarter-symmetry model of a 2-D plate with a uniformly distributed load along one of its edges.\n> Generated a 100x100 element structured mesh using PLANE42 element (the structural element).\n>  Computed the displacements, strains and stresses after solving the problem under the given structural boundary conditions (plane stress) in ANSYS MAPDL.\n>Exported the stresses,strains and displacements & saved them to a new file.\n>Re-generated the  mesh but this time using PLANE 13 element (2-D coupled thermal-structural  element)\n>Imported the structural loads saved in the file generated from the structural analysis and then applied the thermal boundary conditions.\n>Recomputed the stresses,strains and displacements. Also computed the Von-mises stress and verified that it is below the yield point of steel. \n> Validated  the results from theoretical calculations.', u'title': u'Coupled Thermo-Mechanical Stress Analysis of a 2-D Steel Plate in ANSYS MAPDL'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.9 ~ 2013.10', u'description': u'> Numerically solved the Second order Rayleigh Equation for Inviscid instability using Fourth Order Runge-Kutta Scheme.   \n> Applied a Newton Raphson Scheme to compute the next guess value of oscillation Frequency.\n> Plotted the graphs of spatial growth rate versus frequency for symmetric and anti-symmetric modes. ', u'title': u'Numerical Solution of Temporal stability modes of a Bickley Jet  using MATLAB'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.11 ~ 2012.12', u'description': u'>Designed  a QTZ 63-160A Crane model  in SOLIDWORKS.\n>Conducted Static Stress Analysis of the Jib and Mast Section of a QTZ 63-160A  Crane in ABAQUS to account for the  Gravity Loading and Wind Loading.\n>Validated that the stresses produced under the maximum load doesn't break the Von-Mises Failure Criteria.\n>Conducted Mesh Sensitivity Analysis for accuracy and consistency.', u'title': u'FInite Element Stress Analysis of a Tower Crane  in ABAQUS'}]

summary: Currently working as an advanced thermal systems development engineer at Mahle's Lockport Technical Center. \n\nExtensive experience with Computational Thermal-Fluid analysis & CFD code development and hands-on experience with Finite Element Stress analysis, statistical analysis in Minitab .\n\nWorked on time-critical projects with industry leaders like  Chrysler, GM, Ford ,GE-Transportation, ANSYS Inc. , Indian Oil Corporation Limited , Unilever and Indian Ordnance Factories .\n\nKey Strengths & Skills : ANSYS FLUENT (Turbulence Modeling, Turbomachinery flow analysis, Surface Tracking , Electronics Cooling & Gas Turbine Film Cooling ) ,ANSYS ICEPAK (electronics cooling) , STAR CCM+( Design Optimization using HEEDS and Design Manager), GAMBIT, ANSYS ICEM CFD (Structured and Unstructured Meshing), NX 9.0 , SOLIDWORKS ( Synchronous and Parametric Modeling) ,ABAQUS/ANSYS Mechanical (Thermo-Mechanical Stress Analysis) , Object Oriented Programming in C++/C# (CFD -code development),  Arduino ( Stepper Motor Control) , OpenMP(Parallel Programming), MINITAB (Statistical Analysis) and  MATLAB (Engineering problem solving & CFD code development). \n\nCareer Interests :CFD Analysis, Thermal-Fluid design, Battery Cooling , Electronics Cooling,  Heat transfer, Fluid Mechanics, Turbulent Flow analysis, FSI (Fluid Structure Interaction), FEA(Finite Element Analysis),  and Turbomachinery design .

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2012.8 ~ 2012.8', u'description': u'Multiple-instance learning (MIL) is a setting where labels are provided only for a collection of instances called bags. There are two types of instances: negative instances, which are found in either negative bags or positive bags, and positive instances, which are found only in positive bags. While a positive bag should contain at least one inherently positive instance, a negative bag must not contain any positive instances. In MIL, labels are not available at the instance level. It is interesting to note however that the label space is the same for both at the bag level and at the instance level. One may attempt to learn instance-level labels during the training stage, thus reducing the problem to an instance level supervised classification. Alternatively, one may also localize and prototype the positive instances in the feature space and rely on the proximity to these prototypes for subsequent classification.\n\nMIL is an ideal set-up for many computer vision tasks. In particular, MIL can be an especially suitable model for medical image-based pathology classification and lesion detection localization, where an image is labeled pathological just because of one or a few lesions localized to small portions of the image. Medical images collected in a clinical setting may readily have an image-level label (either normal or various levels of pathology) while lacking the exact location of the lesion(s). The figure above illustrates such an example: color fundus images of eyes affected with different pathologies of diabetic retinopathy (DR). It is easy to notice that, although majority of the image looks normal, a small retinal landmark is enough to alter the label of the image from normal to pathological. In a MIL formulation for this problem, each image can be considered a bag and patches of images can be considered instances.\n\nYouTube: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oaclw6_JYyo\n', u'title': u'Multiple Instance Learning'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.12 ~ 2015.12', u'description': u'yann: version 0.0.1a1\n\nAn even easier, simpler and versatile CNN tool alternative to Lasagne and Keras.\nPromotes easy learnability and practice of CNNs using theano.\nModular and plug and play modules and layers.\nImplementations of most commonly used techniques and popular papers in CNN research.\n\nOriginally written for personal research, this toolbox will be most useful for those who are interested in starting deep CNNs to make a fast transition into theano and developing CNNs. It was called samosa back then. Now yann has evolved into this toolbox for CNNs. Yann is designed as a supplement to an upcoming book on Convolutional Neural Networks and also the toolbox of choice for a graduatelevel deep learning course under developement at CIDSE ASU.\nBecause of this reason, Yann is specifically designed to be intuitive and easy to use for beginners. That does not compromise Yann of any of its features. It is still a good choice for a toolbox for running pre-trained models and build complicated, non-vannilla CNN architectures that are not easy to build with the other toolboxes.This will also be useful for industry when teting out prototypes.\nThere is a documentation page that has some details on how to run the code and how to use it. For a quick start into the toolbox, you can use this guide.\n\nThanks for using the code, hope you had fun.', u'title': u'Yet Another Neural Network Toolbox for Convolutional Neural Networks'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.5 ~ now', u'description': u'The aim of the project is to manage the increasing traffic demand and the available transportation supply through a cyber-physical infrastructure. Video-based self-positioning of the car and vehicle detection are its essential components. While most of the state-of-art approaches either use complex instruments or assume a rigid positioning of the camera, this work determines the number of lanes and the car position on the road from the video taken by a normal camera with little positioning constraints.', u'title': u'Prediction of lane model and automated self-positioning.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.8 ~ now', u'description': u'Using fundus camera images, automatic diagnosis of diabetic retinopathy is performed. Features from the images are collected, based on which a model is trained. The trained model is then applied to new images, classifying the images based on the diagnosis labels. A multiple-class, multiple-instance learning approach is currently being researched upon to implement the same.\n\nAdvisor:- Dr. Baoxin Li', u'title': u'Automated Diagnosis of Diabetic Retinopathy \u2013 A Learning approach'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.3 ~ 2012.4', u'description': u'A novel way for Video De-Interlacing is being proposed both spatially and temporally using adaptive control grid interpolation. A technique of fusing the above mentioned technique individually and together with motion compensation is also studied. Methods of 2D and 3D CGI are also worked upon.\n\nAdvisor:- Dr. David Frakes', u'title': u'Content adaptive video de-interlacing using Adaptive Control Grid Interpolation'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.8 ~ 2014.8', u'description': u'Implemented and profiled Regionlets for vehicle detection in C++ using OpenCV. ', u'title': u'Situational -aware vehicles.'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2009.8 ~ 2010.5', u'description': u'In a communication channel, a novel method for detection of faults and estimation of distance to faults is proposed on studying the standing wave pattern in both Frequency and Time Domain. Comparison is made between time domain and frequency domain implementation for different test cases.\n\nAdvisor:- Prof. Ravi Naganathan', u'title': u'A comparative study of Detection of Faults and Estimation of Distance to Faults on wired communication channels, using TDR and FDR techniques'}]

summary: David Gulbransen is a Chicago area attorney with practice areas in information technology law, intellectual property law, and business law. summary: My team says that I build clubhouses. I keep trying to find new ways to share information and strengthen the ecosystem of professionals around me.\n\nI have a long history of dedication to knowledge sharing and community service:\n* I've been a volunteer/officer for the Association for Computing Machinery (at one chapter or another) since 1998.\n* I've volunteered for Society of Women Engineers at various events over the years. \n* I started the Arbortext PTC/User group and continue to donate resources to help it thrive\n* I provide technical and infrastructure support for Arbortext Code archive at adepters.org\n* I was the first podcaster to address Arbortext community's need for knowledge sharing\n* I've been presenting strategies, technology tips, and introductions between users at industry and technical conferences since 2002\n* I founded TC Camp, the first unconference for the content creation community.\n* I started TC Dojo, the first user-driven webinar series for the content creation community.\n\nMy dedication to growing communities and helping other people grow their expertise is so strong that it's carried over into the way Single-Sourcing Solutions does business. Each one of our team members is active in one or more on-line user communities and it is expected that each one devote a portion of their on-the-job time to helping people find answers to problems.\n\nI'm a gardener: I'm happiest when those around me are flourishing.\n\nAs if you can't tell by reading through the rest of my profile, I'm a single-sourcing expert who has independently designed, documented and implemented changes required to take Technical Publications Departments from traditional publishing to XML publishing. \n\nWant the buzzwords? I've filled nearly every role in the XML publishing chain, but my Specialties? Single-Sourcing, document analysis, content management, content reuse strategies, system architecture, multi-channel publishing, XML, XSLT, XSL-FO, FOSI, HTML, Perl, Java, to name a few.

summary: I have over 25 years of experience with product documentation at IBM, spanning the evolution of GML, SGML, and XML-based markup languages and applications. I have enjoyed stints as IBM's primary representative for the W3C XSL and CSS working groups. I led the IBM workgroup that developed and eventually contributed the DITA XML specification as an OASIS standard. I am still Co-Chair for that committee, helping to guide the future of DITA and its communities of use.\n\nI operate the Learning by Wrote business as an opportunity to provide independent consulting services and to promote DITA uptake for new communities and applications. I am active on blogs and on many forums and user communities, and I present regularly at conferences worldwide on challenges and opportunities for new DITA adopters.\n\nI enjoy working with vendors and supporting communities of writers to discover ways to improve their work experience and productivity through the use of open standards, open source, and COTS tools. I strive to lead in defining content standards and enabling innovative collaboration solutions both for technical and professional writers and for subject matter experts.\n\nSpecialties: XML content and XSL processing architectures, Web architecture, collaborative writing solutions, project and work group team leading, user community organization and support, information architecture principles, structured editor configuration.

summary: Ron is a Parallel Entrepreneur, having started and sold a number of successful companies. The companies Ron has started and run have collectively employed hundreds of people, raised over $60M in Venture funding and exits in the millions.\n\nRon is senior analyst at the Artificial Intelligence-focused analyst and advisory firm Cognilytica.\n\nRon is founder and chief organizer of TechBreakfast - the largest monthly morning tech meetup in the nation with over 15,000 members and 3000+ attendees at the monthly events across the US including Baltimore, DC, NY, Boston, Austin, Silicon Valley, Philadelphia, Raleigh and more. \n\nHe is founder and CEO at Bizelo, a SaaS company focused on small business apps. He is also a SXSW Interactive Judge. Prior to Bizelo, Ron founded and ran ZapThink, an industry analyst firm focused on Service-Oriented Architecture (SOA), Cloud Computing, Web Services, XML, & Enterprise Architecture, which was acquired by Dovel Technologies in August 2011.\n\nFounder and CTO of ChannelWave, an enterprise software company which raised $60M+ in VC funding and subsequently acquired by Click Commerce, a publicly traded company. Ron founded and was CEO of VirtuMall and VirtuFlex from 1994-1998, and hired the CEO before it merged with ChannelWave.\n\nRon is a well-known expert in IT, Software-as-a-Service (SaaS), XML, Web Services, and Service-Oriented Architecture (SOA). He is well regarded as a startup marketing & sales adviser, and is currently mentor & investor in the TechStars seed stage investment program, where he has been involved since 2009. In addition, he is a judge of SXSW Interactive Awards and served on standards bodies such as RosettaNet, UDDI, and ebXML.\n\nRon is the lead author of XML And Web Services Unleashed (SAMS 2002) and co-author of Service-Orient or Be Doomed (Wiley 2006) with Jason Bloomberg. Ron received a B.S. degree in Computer Science and Engineering from Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) and MBA from Johns Hopkins University.

summary: My background is in desktop publishing, translation and editing. I have specialized in XML and related technologies since 2000. I design, write and document DTDs and schemas for publishers and other users of document-based XML. I provide XML and workflow consultancy and have introduced digital-first workflows. I create best-practice content models and focus on validation and quality assurance as the basis of sound markup-based production. I am skilled in manipulating and validating XML using XSLT, XQuery, Schematron, Java and (parser-based) Python.\n\nI contribute to international standardisation as an individual expert member of IST/41, the Technical Committee of BSI (the UK member of ISO and IEC) responsible for XML and related standards.\n\nI am also Project Editor for the Schematron international standard (ISO/IEC 19757-3).\n\nSpecialties: XML, SGML, XSLT, XPath, XQuery, XProc, Schematron, RELAX NG, DTD, XML Schema, Java, Python, W3C standards, training, requirements gathering, implementation, XML quality assurance and validation, content architecture, information architecture.

summary: Connecting your data\n\n✔ Semantic ― RDF, RDFS, OWL, SPARQL, Triplestores\n✔ NoSQL and Data ― Documents, Graphs, MarkLogic, eXist\n✔ XML ― XQuery, XPath, XSLT, XML Schema\n✔ Web Services and SOA ― WSDL, SOAP, WS-*, BPMN, BPEL\n\nSince Florent discovered IT back in the 90's, he has always been fascinated by how data are stored and represented. He naturally came to XML, and contributed many open-source and community-driven projects in the field of XML.\n\nFlorent discovered Web services, and later SOA, in the 2000's. He had the intuition that Web services and SOA are good interoperability tools, but make it difficult to query and investigate the entire enterprise data set as a whole. During the 2010's, he was then pleased to be part of the NoSQL movement, enabling central data hubs in the enterprise, and providing ground for data technologies and data science.\n\nIn his pursuit of data flexibility, Florent has been exposed to the Semantic Technologies since the late 90's. But it is only with the advent of NoSQL technologies and transactional triplestores that Florent started to consider using Semantics and the flexibility of its data model in commercial projects.\n\nFlorent is an invited expert in the XSLT & XQuery working groups at W3C since 2009, where he works on the new versions of XSLT, XQuery and XPath. Florent is the chair of the EXPath community group at W3C, and the maintainer of XSpec. Florent and H2O are members of the XML Guild, a consortium of some of the best independent XML consultants in the world.\n\nFlorent collaborated to several books. The Swiss Space Implementation Plan (SSIP) for 2014 to 2023 within the Education, Research and Innovation (ERI) framework is the Swiss response to this trend and crystallizes the national space policy. This ten-year plan shall be revised roughly every three years and shall support the decision-making process on the allocation of the financial resources defined in the current ERI Dispatch 2013 \u2013 2016 and beyond.\n\nThe SSIP will contribute to strengthen an innovative and competitive Swiss space sector and will en- courage the use of space-based services and applications by public and private actors. The national focal areas of technology, science & exploration, space transportation and applications are confirmed. In addition, the emerging themes \u201csmall satellites\u201d and \u201cminiaturization\u201d are addressed. Finally, four measures, which will be implemented within the current ERI funding instruments, namely the Swiss participation to the activities and programmes of the European Space Agency and the National Com- plementary Activities, are presented. summary: My work at Wesleyan University supports teaching and learning from the Davison Art Center collection of works on paper. Much of what I do there aligns with my interest in using digital technologies to serve the educational missions of cultural heritage institutions in new ways, and in helping to move that field forward.\n\nThis professional focus builds on my experience in nonprofit leadership (especially with the Museum Computer Network, MCN); knowledge of digital standards, best practices, and emerging technologies in museums; years working at a university; and service reviewing federal grant applications for digital work in cultural institutions. My background as an improvising musician, often in intercultural groups, gives me a solid experiential understanding of how to collaborate creatively and how important listening is to doing that, and of how to temper perfectionism by means of iteration.\n\nI've presented in, chaired, and/or organized conference sessions on such topics as strategies for moving museums toward open content policies, simplifying digital content contribution, open access image delivery, nonprofit leadership sustainability, using FADGI/Metamorfoze guidelines in cultural heritage imaging, design factors for collections photography studios, digital images for education, getting projects done, metadata standards such as LIDO, museum technology trends, JPEG 2000, and XML, as well as repatriation from ethnomusicological sound archives, ethics, and musical identity. Most of this has been at MCN or Museums & the Web; some has been at IMLS WebWise or meetings of the American Alliance of Museums (AAM), Coalition for Networked Information (CNI), Society for Ethnomusicology, and other organizations.\n\nAs LinkedIn recommends, I mostly link to people with whom I've interacted in a professional context. If you invite me to connect and we haven't done so recently (or at length in the past), please remind me of where and how we did. Thanks!

summary: I work with product teams who want to profit with Amazon Web Services.  \n\nWould you benefit from a solution that allowed you to more profitably scale to meet demand, and do so more quickly?\n\nIf you are like most of my clients, you are doing your best to improve your capacity and performance. You are spending time and money reacting to increasing customer demand by adding servers, bandwidth, and storage. You might even have an on-premises datacenter and private cloud.\n\nBut I am guessing you do not really have a great strategy for massive growth. Maybe you hope your budget will double tomorrow, or your staff will become twice as efficient overnight. Or you are adding more infrastructure than you need, just to stay ahead of demand.\n\nYou need a cloud strategy that works\n\nHere is what you need ASAP:\n\n* Ability to quickly and securely host your applications\n* Ability to choose the operating systems, programming languages, web application platforms, databases, and other services you need\n* Pay only for the compute power, storage, and other resources you use, with no long-term contracts or up-front commitments (zero CapEx)\n* A scalable, reliable, and secure global computing infrastructure with minimal downtime\n* Ability to scale your application up or down based on demand\n* Physical, operational, and software security\n* Reduce the time it takes to make IT resources available to your developers\n* Delivery of a faster, better user experience globally\n\nI have perfected the process of transforming on-premises applications and infrastructures in the cloud - specifically, with Amazon Web Services (AWS). These transformations regularly produce returns on investment (ROI) of greater than 10x.\n\nContact me to grow your business and increase profits in a way that scales indefinitely and works on autopilot.\n\nMark Richman\n\uD83D\uDCDE561-571-5008\n✉️ mark@markrichman.com\n\uD83C\uDF10 markrichman.com

summary: I am a software engineer with an R&D background and over 10 years of experience (8 years in startup companies). My favorite languages are Scala, Python and Java.\n\nI currently work at Simulmedia in the data team working on ETLs and datawarehouse using Python, Scala/Akka, Java, the AWS stack and Redshift. Prior to that I worked at Onswipe where I used Scala, Storm and AWS (Dynamo, SQS, S3, EC2). Before that I worked at Appnexus an adtech company.\n\nI am interested in Big Data in general (Spark, Hadoop, ...), data grids (Oracle Coherence, HazelCast), NoSQL (MongoDB, Dynamo), machine learning (Mahout, Spark MLLib) and real-time processing (Storm).\n\nI have a strong background in Distributed Systems (MsC in Distributed Systems) and a strong research background (PhD in Computer Sciences).\n\nIn all my positions, I take an active role in the design of the architecture, the technology choices, the database design, development and documentation.\n\nYou can find me at tech meetups (Java, MongoDB, Big Data Warehousing, Google Developer) in New York City.\n\nI also like to work on personal projects on the side with my brother to learn new technologies. You can see some of my work related to crawlers, big data and Android works at:\n- http://chimpler.com\n- http://tuxigloo.org\n- http://github.com/darthbear\n- http://github.com/chimpler\n\nI maintain a new tech blog with my brother which revolves around big data and machine learning. You can see it at: http://chimpler.wordpress.com.\n\nFeel free to connect or contact me at Francois.DangNgoc@gmail.com

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2010.9 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'ActionScript3, Flash, JavaScript, XML\n\nMaintenance for bug fixes and updates for this legacy courseware rendering engine.', u'title': u'UCP Courseware Engine'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.4 ~ 2015.4', u'description': u'Light-weight order management system to help bridge the gaps in the systems for handling business-to-business orders.  \n\nMain interface is a web front-end communicating with .NET Web API.  \n\nI worked on the front-end using Angular JS and Bootstrap 3.  \n\nProject went through prototyping phase with approval on UI from the business only after 2 review sessions.\n\nThere were a few unknowns to investigate.  \n\n- Mix of working with AngularJS and Web API.  \n- Setting up Web API to allow cross-origin resource sharing from the UI.\n- Authentication, using Windows authentication.  Unfamiliar with how authentication in AngularJS UI would need to work with Windows authentication, so investigated with a proof of concept.\nAuthorization strategy investigation based on access to Web API.  Hit up Web API to determine authorization to requested resource.  For example, if user can/cannot access a resource, then show/hide sections on page as a result.  It does cause extra call to the API, but it allows authorization to be defined in one place and for the UI to be agnostic to specific user roles and instead focus on whether a user can access a particular feature.\n\nUpper management scrapped the project after one month. However, I learned much about authentication/authorization strategies, ways to structure the application, and working on front-end prototypes for feedback from the business stakeholder.', u'title': u'Order Management System'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.11 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'ASP.NET MVC 3.0, C#, JavaScript, jQuery\n\nWorked on a web application that hosted a suite of tools to help with the process of handling GLE courseware content.', u'title': u'CourseForge'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.2 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'Primarily responsible for setting up a continuous integration process for building and\ndeployment of GLE Courseware Engine.\n\nUses Jenkins, custom Beyond Compare scripts, and other tools.\n\nDecreased a mostly manual deployment preparation process from 1 to 2 hours down to a 15\nminute fully automated process for a lengthy build.', u'title': u'Continuous Integration Process'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.2 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'ActionScript3, Flash, JavaScript, XML, .NET (for launching courses)\n\nThis is the successor to the UCP Courseware Engine. I was part of a 2-person team that was responsible for refactoring the UCP Courseware Engine to turn it into the new GLE Courseware Engine as the main platform for all of the courses going forward.  In addition to refactoring, the overall structure of the courseware engine data and process that the engine goes through to load and run a course was changed and lots of new features were added. One major change to the structure was for having a centralized launching page for courses instead of distributed set of course launching files for every course.  One major feature is the ability to customize almost all content for a course that is loaded by the engine.  As of now it supports over 60 languages including right-to-left languages.', u'title': u'GLE Courseware Engine (Flash)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.9 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'ASP.NET, C#, JavaScript\n\nMostly worked on maintenance, bug fixes, and updates for this legacy web application tool that automatically packages up the legacy UCP courseware into packages for our clients that can be run offline or on CD and for SCORM 1.2 and SCORM 2004 formats.  Internal development team tool.', u'title': u'UCP Course Packaging web application tool'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.6 ~ 2015.5', u'description': u'C#, .NET 4.5, ASP .NET MVC 4, Entity Framework 5, SQL, JavaScript, jQuery, jQuery Mobile, AngularJS, CSS, Twitter Bootstrap\n\nLeading the effort for redesigning and implementing the presentation layer of an area of the desktop version of the application for an improved user experience using Bootstrap and AngularJS mixed with our existing MVC architecture.\n\nLed effort to allow mobile version to process gift cards and handle returns, which allowed for increased productivity and saw approximately a 70% increase in gift card sales in 2013. All store salespeople utilize the mobile devices, which allowed the stores to scale at seasonal peaks.\n\nWorked on open API for the commercialization of the POS system to allow for client integration for sales, purchase orders, and 3rd party digital marketing.  Interface consisted of WCF service leveraging existing proprietary authentication/authorization model. Refactored the interface and internals of the service to make it more reusable for other potential business needs.\n\nWorked together with the team to improve processes.  Suggested ideas to help improve concurrent development and preventing unfinished features from being released into production. Investigated potential performance improvement with Entity Framework to use stored procedures.', u'title': u'Cloud-based Point of Sale System'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.9 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'ASP.NET 4.0, C#, JavaScript, jQuery\n\nCreation and maintenance of this web application tool to work with the latest courseware format, GLE.  It isn\u2019t just a simple copy/paste of the tool for the legacy UCP engine.  Some concepts were borrowed where applicable, but it is completely separate from that legacy tool. There are a lot more features since the new GLE courseware engine has better support for configuring courses at runtime and a general restructuring of the courseware, so the additional complexity required a new tool built from the ground up. It automatically makes packages for our clients that can be run offline or on CD and for SCORM 1.2 and SCORM 2004 formats. It communicates with the GLE Service Layer to dynamically get the \', u'title': u'GLE Automated Course Packager'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.8 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'.NET 4.0, C#, Windows Communication Foundation (WCF), JavaScript, jQuery, XSL, XML\n\nWith the GLE Course Engine Flash and HTML5 versions running off of the same content, myself, the senior software engineer on the team, and my manager determined that the best way for them to have a shared loading process was to implement a web service to handle the shared logic for processing the content, which would then send that data back to the engine that requested it.  This was necessary because the logic for loading content into the engine was only built into the Flash version.  So, to prevent duplication and have a reusable set of logic that could be used for more than just the current engines (tools, future engines, other potential formats etc..) and since my 3 teammates were focused on other assignments, I was given the sole responsibility for designing and implementing the entire web service from the ground up including both the server side and a JavaScript client to consume the service.  The service is full-featured complete with error handling and logging logic to capture any errors that might occur, and it passes the log back to the client, so it generally fails gracefully and having the log makes errors easier to track down.  Also, the original logic for loading content from the Flash version of the GLE engine was recreated in the web service for backwards compatibility but also improved to be much more robust and with a better structure to allow for an easily configurable and extendable processing logic based on the data output format types that need to be supported.\n\nThe service is hosted with a simple ASP.NET web application.', u'title': u'GLE Service Layer'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.9 ~ 2013.5', u'description': u'HTML5, JavaScript, jQuery, LESS/CSS, kineticJS\n\nAn HTML5 version of the GLE Courseware Engine.  I was part of a 2-person team responsible for building this engine off of a very base prototype made by a third-party vendor that the company hired.  It uses the GLE Service Layer to reuse content that already existed for the Flash version of the engine with the exception of the style data, which due to the differences between the engines, had to be handled separately for the HTML5 version.  So, that is handled with its own process by using LESS, which is handled by the GLE Service Layer and compiled down into the appropriate CSS to apply to the page at runtime.', u'title': u'GLE Courseware Engine (HTML5)'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2013.10 ~ 2013.10', u'description': u'I am the Executive Director of the Structure-Function Linkage Database (SFLD). This database is a hierarchical classification of enzymes that relates specific sequence-structure features to specific chemical capabilities. It serves as the analysis and archive site for superfamilies targeted by the Enzyme Function Initiative, and is developed by the Babbitt Laboratory in collaboration with the UCSF Resource for Biocomputing, Visualization, and Informatics. ', u'title': u'Structure Function Linkage Database'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2006.12 ~ now', u'description': u'A novel tool for searching similar enzymes based on chemical knowledge.', u'title': u'EC-BLAST'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2002.10 ~ now', u'description': u'Executive Director and Creator of MACiE. MACiE, which stands for Mechanism, Annotation and Classification in Enzymes, that aims to catalogue the function of amino acid residues and the catalytic mechanism of enzymes. It is a collaborative project between the Babbitt lab at UCSF, Thornton Group at the European Bioinformatics Institute and the Mitchell Group at the University of St Andrews (initially within the Unilever Centre for Molecular Informatics part of the University of Cambridge). We have also extended to collaboration to include the Bertini Group at the Magnetic Resonance Center (CERM) in Florence (Italy). This aspect of the collaboration incorporates the expertise of CERM with metalloproteins and we have developed Metal MACiE, a database of catalytic metal ions, with a view to understanding the functions of the roles and activity of catalytic metals in enzymes.', u'title': u'MACiE'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.7 ~ 2014.7', u'description': u'As the number of publicly available sequences continues to grow at astonishing rates, new tools are required to predict their functional properties and to improve our understanding of biological processes and evolution. This proposal focuses on enzymes, which catalyze the vast majority of chemical reactions essential for life. While many sophisticated tools and resources exist to probe relationships between enzyme sequences and their structures (bioinformatics), the resources to describe the chemistry of enzymes (cheminformatics) are fewer and significantly less mature. In this project, we build on the Babbitt and Holliday labs expertise and the we've resources developed and by others to classify, compare and analyse many aspects of enzyme catalysis and link the results to the sequences and structures that enable those reactions. The results will be provided to scientists from many fields for interactive exploration, enabling them, for the first time, to ask in depth questions about how enzyme sequence and structure are linked to reaction mechanism, the partial and overall reactions enzymes catalyze, and their substrates and products. Applications of this work will impact areas that range from improved understanding of enzyme evolution and structure-function relationships, to the design of novel enzymes or new pathways for biodegradation of toxic compounds, to improving annotation of molecular function for metagenomic data.', u'title': u'MEERCat (NSF DBI-1356193)'}]

summary: I recently finished working for UCSF where I was responsible for the running of the Structure-Function Linkage Database (SFLD). This role included the management of a small team of developers and researchers to provide a the continuing high quality of service and to develop new features. This also included managing the project to meet deadlines for our deliverables. I am also responsible for the MACiE database and the Catalytic Site Atlas (CSA), including the linking of these three database. \n Whilst searching for a new job, I am working as a consultant for the MACiE and CSA databases, as well as the SFLD. This role involves updating entries as well as consulting on interface and usability design for the new release planned for late 2017.\n\nI continue to be interested in the area of enzyme function and mechanism. My recent work has included trying to understand how enzyme chemistry (overall chemical transformations) ties in with mechanism, and whether the EC number of an overall reaction can be predicted from the overall reactions or mechanisms involved. Also, investigating how the local environment of the catalytic amino acid residues plays a role in their catalysis. I am also turning my attention to the chemistry within evolutionarily related families of enzymes with a particular emphasis on the Radical SAM Superfamily, the Isoprenoid Synthase Superfamily and the Acyl-enzyme activating enzyme superfamily.\n\nSpecialties: Enzyme reaction mechanisms, function of catalytic residues, MACiE, SFLD, CSA

It allows me to have a good overview of several programming languages so I can compare them and choose the best one for a given task.\n\nI love to keep up to date and learn about new computer science concepts, new technologies, new software languages, new frameworks and like to have other expertise fields. Swimming is my favorite personal sport.\n\nSpecialties:\n• Software engineering, Internet protocols, software prototyping.\n• Currently developing with Java, Python, JavaScript.\n• Also did some C, C++, C#, Objective-C, ActionScript/Flash/Flex, PHP, HTML(5)/EcmaScript/CSS\n• Tests are good: methodology, unit tests, tools (JUnit, Hamcrest, Espresso, ...)\n• Design patterns are good: GoF, dependency injection, ...\n• Electronic/embedded prototyping with Arduino, Raspberry Pi, Beaglebone\n• Mobile development: Android (Java/AS3/JavaScript)\n• Operating system agnostic (Windows, Linux / Unix, MacOS X)

summary: 17+ Years’ experience in the Information Technology field. Responsibilities have included the design, development, testing and deployment of numerous web applications. Additional experience includes customer support, web analyst, server administration and project management.\n\nDEPARTMENT OF THE NAVY\nNAVY PERSONNEL COMMAND\n2 MAR 05\nFrom: Commander, Navy Personnel Command\nSubject: LETTER OF APPRECIATION\n On 19 January 2005, the new design of the Bureau of Naval Personnel (BUPERS) website was launched. The new BUPERS website is the culmination of 17 months of effort and unparalleled teamwork among our three departments. The new website provides Sailors and their families with tools and information necessary to make informed career decisions. I want to extend my sincere appreciation to Mr. Walter D. Baxter for his efforts to improve this website.\n\nAs the Web Content Management System Administrator for the project, Mr. Baxter was instrumental in executing the vision for the new website. His hard work and efforts have resulted in a website available to the Fleet with an esthetically pleasing design and much-improved navigation that allow Sailors and their families to quickly and easily find information. The new website allows content contributors to make changes to the site with a minimum amount of training and very little technical knowledge, reducing the time required for these collateral duties and improving the timeliness and accuracy of content posted for the Sailor. Mr. Baxter has worked relentlessly with other contractors and departmental representatives to ensure the functionality of the site and its availability to the Fleet. Response from the Fleet in regard to the new look and feel of the site has been overwhelmingly positive.\n\nPlease pass on a “well done” to Mr. Baxter and thank him for his continued professionalism and dedication to the Navy and our Sailors.\n\nJ. W. Townes, III\nRear Admiral, U.S. Navy\n\n_______________________________________

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2007.1 ~ now', u'description': u'DITA for Publishers is an open-source project that provides Publishers with the basic components they need to apply the DITA standard to typical Publishing documents and business processes. DITA for Publishers builds on the inherent extension facilities of DITA.\n\nThe goal of DITA for Publishers is to lower as far as possible the cost of adopting DITA for Publishing, making it as easy as possible to use XML for Publishing.\n\nDITA for Publishers provides additional markup tailored to the needs of Publishers as well as new transforms for the DITA Open Toolkit for producing ebooks (EPUB and Kindle), HTML5, and enhanced HTML.\n\nIt also provides frameworks for generating DITA from Microsoft Word documents and InDesign from DITA documents.', u'title': u'DITA For Publishers Project'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2012.3 ~ 2012.9', u'description': u'Participated in the implementation of a FatWire Enterprise CMS for Insperity.\n\nDesigned parts of the asset model and implemented templates. \n\nWrote custom scripts to extract information from the old WordPress site and populated it into FatWire using XMLPost. \n\nImplemented a custom vanity URL solution as FatWire doesn't support this out-of-the-box. ', u'title': u'Insperity.com'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.10 ~ 2013.4', u'description': u'Helped Zinio, the world's largest newsstand to implement a system that would intelligently extract articles from PDFs. \n\nA PDF doesn't contain any semantic information about its content, it is basically print commands that tells a reader which character should be printed in what position on a page. Zinio's mobile device readers need the articles properly formatted as XML, complete with headers, pull quotes, authors, etc. The mobile readers uses this information to also provide a text-only view, rendered with native fonts for best reading experience. Previously the PDF to XML conversion was performed through manual labor. \n\nThe system that we developed is using machine learning, where a user trains the system what fonts, their relationship and their meaning, but also how fonts form words, how words form paragraphs and how paragraphs form articles. The user uses a web interface to train the system for 30 minutes to an hour and then the system can automatically use this information to extract articles into XML for issues of the same publication. It isn't 100% accurate all the time, but it provides the tools to improve the manual labor by an order of magnitude.', u'title': u'Zinio PDF to XML'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.7 ~ 2014.11', u'description': u'Participated in a two scrum team sized project that developed the new iPad application for Target. As an iOS developer, I developed many features in the new application, #TargetStyle, components on the home screen, etc. ', u'title': u'Target iPad Application'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.2 ~ 2014.7', u'description': u'Participated in the development of three Adobe AEM implementations for GE Power. \n\nWrote a custom authentication handler for enabling single sign on with Adobe AEM through SiteMinder. The authentication handler obtains information through HTTP headers and makes sure a user account exists in AEM. If the account doesn't exist, the authentication handler would create it. \n\nI also developed OSGi components to connect to different web services and update the information stored in JCR. The components were unit tested with JMockit and the components were also mocked for local development as the web services were not accessible outside the VPN.\n\nAlso developed a number of page components that utilized the information stored in JCR by the OSGi components.', u'title': u'Adobe AEM implementations for GE Power'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.9 ~ 2014.1', u'description': u'Complete reimplementation of Zinio's iOS application. Used new services introduced in iOS 7 such as background downloading and Text Kit. The application is a magazine reader for single issues and subscriptions purchased through Zinio. The magazines are downloaded as encrypted PDF files that are unlocked and presented through PSPDFKit to the user. Techniques to download relevant pages progressively so the user doesn't have to wait for the whole PDF to download were used.', u'title': u'Zinio iOS'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.9 ~ 2012.1', u'description': u'Solely responsible for the architecture with backend and frontend implementation of a video sharing application for Android 2.2 and above. \nThe Video Manager helps users to organize and share their own videos and videos on the web with their friends. The application has a custom navigation that uses animations to enhance the experience for the user. The user can follow the activity of their friends which they can invite through either Facebook, Twitter or their address book.\n\nThe Android application uses fragments, providers, SQL Lite and integrates with the camera, the gallery, the notification system, the address book and other applications. It uses a REST API to communicate with the server and synchronizes with its local DB for responsiveness. \n\nThe backend was implemented with Spring, Hibernate, MySQL and Tomcat and deployed on a cluster of Amazon EC2 instances. I used Jackson to stream JSON to the client. Since we wanted to support as many devices as possible, I had to use FFMPEG to re-encode the uploaded videos into a format that could be progressively streamed.\n\nIf the user shared a video with a user that didn't have an Android device (on Facebook, Twitter, etc), the user was redirected to a microsite. The microsite had a desktop version for desktop computers and tablets, but also a mobile version that would be automatically served to mobile devices. If the device was able to handle HTML5, it was playing the video natively otherwise it fell back to Flash.', u'title': u'Video Manager'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.6 ~ 2014.7', u'description': u'Developed an iPad application used by GE Software\u2019s sales team to gather information and recommend solutions to potential clients. I developed the application using storyboards and auto layout. All the data provided was parsed from an Excel spreadsheet and seeded to a core data model. I utilized MagicalRecord, RestKit and AF Networking for a lot of the plumbing work so my time could be focused on the business logic. All gathered information was stored locally so it could be transmitted at a later time if networking was not available during the gathering.', u'title': u'iPad application for GE Software'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.3 ~ 2011.12', u'description': u'I was leading the architecture for the web layer in this big project to develop an online live auction site. The project called Outbid originally setup goals to become as big as Ebay, so we were using Oracle Exadata to make sure we could scale even when using a relational database. The project engaged Accenture for project management and QA, IBM to develop the live auction server, R/GA for visual design and ThoughtMatrix for backend and front-end development. It started up as a separate website, but it eventually ended up as a Facebook application (http://www.facebook.com/myoutbid).\r\n\r\nThe application is using asynchronous calls to update different parts of the page, so I developed a framework that could be reused both on first page load and subsequent asynchronous calls. I also implemented business logic in the service layer, provided services to the front-end and web service team, and integrated other sub systems through Mule ESB. \r\n\r\nThe web layer is using Freemarker templates to render the views, Spring as controller and Hibernate for the model. The project currently has 67 entities mapped through Hibernate using JPA annotations. I used the Jackson streaming API to generate JSON for the asynchronous calls, Maven as build tool and JUnit for unit testing (100% class coverage). All deployments were performed through Hudson (Jenkins) and Archiva.\r\n', u'title': u'Outbid'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.12 ~ 2014.12', u'description': u'GE Software needed some improvements to the application that I built earlier last year. First I improved the project by setting up a build pipeline with automated publishing to TestFlight. It was also a great opportunity to learn Swift as all new functionality was implemented with the new programming language.', u'title': u'iPad application for GE Software - Phase 2'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.4 ~ 2013.9', u'description': u'Helped Zinio to re-architect their web services infrastructure. Used Spring Framework to implement user stories for the JSON consuming/producing REST services.\n\nConfigured Nginx and Memcached to cache the result of URLs for scalability. \n\nThe security model was implemented with OAuth 2 authentication and authorization scheme.\n\n', u'title': u'Zinio Web Service Architecture'}]

summary: Helping software engineering teams become high functioning and collaborative gives me a huge sense of accomplishment. It feels good to see teams build great products, individuals who are proud of their work. So I spend every day ensuring that the teams have an environment conducive for great programming, failing, learning and building great software, which results in happy people and a healthy business.\n\nI started out in the space industry and quickly jumped to the internet industry where I have been programming for the past 20 years. My favorite technology stack is Node JS, but I'm good at building things on the JVM and .Net too (Java, C#, Javascript, HTML, CSS, etc). I love coding and continue to do it while managing development teams responsible for the Product Information Page and the Product Information API on homedepot.com. It keeps me connected with the team's pain points so that we can continuously improve. I also enjoy collaborating about my own failures and lessons learnt in hopes that others will learn from them too. Building software is a social endeavor. Creating a learning environment is a key strategy to do it well.\n\nCurrently, I'm at The Home Depot, helping to create an XP culture where pair programming and test driven development are the norm. I write about my experiences periodically on my blog if you're interested and sometimes I'll tweet a pic or comment that gives a little insight into our world. It's a great time to be at The Home Depot right now. Feel free to follow me to see for yourself.\n\n@ijoeyguerra

summary: A leader in the architecture and technical delivery of complex global enterprise systems, particularly as they interact with devices in the mobile world.\n\nCurrently a Principal Engineer on Amazon's Alexa Voice Service (AVS) team.\n\nPrior to this I was Distinguished Engineer at Neudesic, responsible for delivery of large or complex projects. I also founded Neudesic's Mobility Practice, leading a nationwide team creating mobile solutions for our clients across a range of mobile devices.\n\nPrior to Neudesic, I was Lead Architect for Dell.com, where I designed and led development of the www.dell.com web application and the globalization/UI framework underneath it for 7 years. This system was initially developed around a custom script engine written in C++, then moved to C#/ASP.NET at the end of 2000 - one of the first major web sites to move to .NET. The underlying framework was then used to port all of the Dell.com online applications to .NET (cart/checkout, My Account, Premier, Support etc.)\n\nSpecialties: Mobile solutions development (cross-platform) • Complex enterprise application design • Developing highly modular smart clients • Object oriented design • Software globalization • Writing very high performance dynamic websites • Writing secure code

summary: Tomasso Groenendijk is an Application Architect at Motion10, a leading Microsoft service integrator in the Netherlands. Tomasso has over 15 years of experience in software development and software design. He specializes in application integration, designing and building web services and APIs, SQL Server databases and also NoSQL databases like MongoDB and CosmosDB.  He has a strong interest in Azure cloud platform and is a Subject Matter Expert (SME) in API Management. He is also an active contributor to the community through his work on MSDN TechNet forums, TechNet Wiki, his blog on ithero.nl and as a speaker. For these efforts, Microsoft has awarded him with the Microsoft Azure MVP award for the past 4 years.\n\n\nSpecialties: \nAzure, BizTalk, C#, SQL Server, MongoDB, XML, XSD, XSLT, XPath, HTML, HL7, WCF, REST,  Sentinet

summary: I am a technology entrepreneur with almost 20 years experience in engineering and technical management at Silicon Valley companies like Netscape (bought by AOL for $4.2B in 1998), Liveops (grew to $125M+ in revenue in 2010), Trulia (IPO in 2012, bought by Zillow for $3.5B in 2014), and BrightFunnel (raised $12M from angel/seed/VC funds and hit multi-million annual revenue run rate in 2017).\n\nI have worked at consumer and enterprise companies of all stages in my career: I was employee #1500+ at Netscape (consumer internet browser), employee #65 at Liveops (enterprise virtual callcenter web/telephony platform), employee #8 at Trulia (consumer real estate website), and co-founder at Zamanzar, IntroRocket (enterprise sales web service), and BrightFunnel (enterprise marketing web service).\n\nThe technology stacks I've coded on so far are C/C++ (Netscape), Java (Liveops), Symfony/PHP (Zamanzar), Ruby on Rails (IntroRocket), and AngularJS/BootStrap/Groovy/Grails (BrightFunnel).\n\nMost recently at Brightfunnel, I set up Cloudera's Hadoop clusters running Apache Impala and Spark to scale up the backend computations of our batch data pipeline.  I also architected our real time data pipeline that accepts a stream of web browser tracking events into an AWS API gateway and uses Lambda functions to store the events into Dyanamo DB.\n\nThe technology domains that excite me are Big Data, Machine Learning, and Mobile Platforms.  I want to learn, create, and deliver as much value as I can while operating at the confluence of as many of these domains as possible.\n\nI gravitate toward senior engineering management roles where I can have the flexibility to lead/manage a team as well as code/create.  I am particularly interested in building innovative technology solutions for the health and education verticals.\n\nMy ideal roles are:\n\na) Technical Co-founder / CTO\nb) CTO and/or VP Engineering at a post-Series A company

summary: I'm a full-stack developer with a background in LAMP and frontend coding, now specialising in TypeScript/JavaScript and Angular. I have worked for startups and corporates such as Flypay and YouView TV. I have commercial experience using Angular, TypeScript and RxJS employing best practices throughout.\n\nI love to work in technical roles that also require an element of input on user experience, I consider myself a both-sides-of-the-brain developer with an eye for design aesthetic and usability (without compromising on my coding). I believe code should be elegant, scalable and tested but not too clever. Done is better than perfect but I prefer to avoid technical debt.\n\nOOP and functional programming, TypeScript, JavaScript ES6/ES2015, Angular, RxJS, SASS,  Material, Bootstrap, Jasmine/Mocha/Sinon, CucumberJS, Protractor, Webpack, gulp.\n\nI have four years of full-time top ten agency experience and have been a London-based freelancer for almost fifteen years. I'm a positive and motivated team player with high standards of communication, coding and a flair for creative detail. I believe its important to leave a trail of good code and documentation behind you for the next guy or gal. \n\nVery much at home in an Agile environment. I've helped to refine Agile processes in some of the places I've worked.\n\nCurrently very interested in RXJS, pure functional coding and machine learning.\n\nFor a comprehensive list of the tech I am experienced with, please visit: http://johngrimsey.co.uk\n\nI'm also a musician and in a band called The Honey Ants.

summary: I DON'T ACCEPT RANDOM INVITATIONS FROM PEOPLE I'VE NEVER MET OFFLINE OR ONLINE. #NORECRUITERS.\n\nCurrently, my focus is the development of high-available, accesible and usable websites and social networks based on an opensource stack based on Drupal, but always willing to learn new technologies. Recently I've worked with Symfony and Salesforce too. Experienced with Varnish configuration languages, and memcached.\n\nAlso, I'm interested in helping Drupal to be the first choice if you need a multilingual CMS. I participate in the D8MI initiative with patches for Drupal 8 core contributing to that goal. Also contributed to the Migrate in Core initiative, trying to leverage D8 adoption when is released.  \n\nMy skills are deeper in web development, with experience in a handful of technologies like Drupal&Symfony (PHP), GWT (Java), Django (Python), or ASP.NET MVC (.NET) and with full understanding of the foundations: HTTP protocol, HTML5, CSS3, JavaScript (DOM, AJAX, OOP...), and XML technologies, like XSLT or XQuery.\n\nI have a strong experience with OpenSource Software. I have worked building GIS systems based on an OpenSource stack (OpenLayers, MapServer, WMS protocol). While learning about it, I contributed some patches to the OpenLayers javascript mapping library from OSGEO.\n\nI have a big background in Microsoft .NET technologies, having developed solutions for WMobile 6.5, ASP.NET (from 1.1 to 3.5) and Windows Forms. I'm not currently interested on MS based technologies at the moment anyway.\n\nI have written a lot of Java code too, for the desktop in my contributions to ArgoUML and for the web (mostly GWT framework). \n\nI'm proficient in design and architectural software patterns. I have a deep knowledge of UML 1.4 and 2.0, being a committer of the ArgoUML opensource CASE tool.\n\nI've done team management in the past based on agile methodologies. I'm a SCRUM practitioner.\nI am a proactive person.\n\nITIL v3 Foundation Certification (December 2010) (ITIL v2 Found. in May 2009)

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2015.3 ~ 2015.6', u'description': u'Working as one of the Technical Agile Coaches on a Agile Transformation Mission for a banking client to help the workforce improve their skills in Agile Software Development environment.
