summary: For the past 17 years I've been heavily immersed in the healthcare, automotive, and general IT verticals, providing innovative technology solutions and leading technology teams. I'm incredibly passionate about what I do and attempt to inject my enthusiasm and love for technology in all those around me.\n\nI started my career in 2000 and spent 4 years building enterprise-level, database-driven Web applications. I worked for two different companies during this timeframe which included work on several high profile projects in the e-Learning space with one spanning the efforts of the Chinese Ministry of Education and the United States Department of Education.\n\nIn 2004 I began working as a senior developer for a small company building dynamic Web sites in the automotive industry. I spent five years at Dealerskins helping grow the company from 300 Web sites to 2,200 Web sites in 2008.\n\nI left Dealerskins in 2009 to help form an automotive startup focused on big data solutions. I served Dataium as Chief Technology Officer from December 2009 through December 2014. My role at Dataium involved managing the technology staff and leading the technology vision to build the entire technology stack from a blank sheet of paper. Some of our accomplishments include engineering an Apache Hadoop-based platform which processed hundreds of gigabytes each day into a multi-terabyte data warehouse. We also created a Web Services system using Linux, Node.js, and MySQL (later MongoDB) which processed over 3.3 billion HTTP transactions in March, 2015.\n\nDataium was sold to IHS in March 2015.\n\nIn May 2015 I started a new journey with the technology healthcare firm, Concert Genetics. My role as Vice President of Engineering involves hands-on programming and leading the amazing engineering team. We are reinventing how people think about and interact with the genetics testing marketplace.

summary: I am a software engineer with 4 years of experience in Java and various web related technologies. Sentences that best describe me as a software engineer are the following:   Self-discipline combined with awareness of teamwork and the benefits of sharing information and knowledge; Hard working person and fast learner with willingness to broaden experience to other technologies;  Adapting in different situations to always be the best in the area of work;\nI like to work in stimulating and challenging position to build upon my skills, knowledge as well as the experience. My interest in engineering is in my desire to create something new and significant: \n     •  To envision a product, process or algorithm, and use the tools I have and my skills to make it a reality. \n     •  To complete and succeed in the market place is the true test. \n     •  Involvement in various aspects of the software development and having the ability to specialize in specific life-cycle phases to meet the needs of the client. \n     •  Working with team members to thoroughly understand software requirements, deliverable's and \ntime-lines. \n     •  Unit and system test new services, releases and software upgrades. \n     •  Complex applications that target international market.

summary: I work in every environment Linux, OSX, Windows to get things done.\nI build software in the following stacks:\n\nGolang (interested in Rust, Webassembly, elixir)\n.NET -> C#, ASP.NET MVC, MS SQL\nJava -> SpringFramework, JBoss, MySQL, PostgreSQL\nLAMP -> laravel, slim, flask, Django, MySQL, MongoDB, Redis\nNode.js -> Angular v1/2/4, Express, Meteor, MongoDB, PostgreSQL, MySQL, Redis, AWS\n\nAzure - AWS - Google Cloud - Linode - Slicehost - Heroku\n\n\nHighly talented Software Engineer with Architecture skills, but prefer to be hands on. Background in many different technologies and came a long way from a 3rd world country to become an expert in the field of building large scale Client/Server Enterprise Software for Fortune 500 companies.\n\nCapable of learning new things and adjusting to business needs. Microsoft Certified and Sun Certified. Holds MCTS: Web App, MCTS: Win App, MCTS: Distributed App and is a MCPD: Enterprise Applications Developer and plans to be Microsoft Certified Architect. SCJP with plans to be Sun Certified Enterprise Architect (SCEA). Windows and Web Development expert. Open Source follower with miscellaneous skills such as linux and kde. Building platforms for startups using popular LAMP stacks. Creating APIs before creating a web front end.

summary: I've always been attracted by computers and science in general.\nMy father, unconsciously, brought me to the computers world: he bought me a Philips big keyboard with a BASIC interpreter and I started programming with that. I spent my childhood between this keyboard and sailing. \nOn January 1994 I changed it with a Windows 3.1 Compaq Presario CDS 520, where I moved my first steps in OSes.\nAt the university I met structured programming languages such Java, C, OCaml and the theoretical paradigms that stand behind Computer Science.\nTalking about my skills, I'm used to pay attention to the order, with a strong orientation for results. I'm able to work in teams, through a fair confrontation with colleagues, and individually placing myself seriously towards the tasks. I think that my growing process isn't finished, I'm strongly interested in  learning, using and mastering technologies.

Drag and drop form creation.\n2. Easy logic controls. Route form submissions on any form element.\n3. Advanced approval system allowing for customized approval/processing assignment.\n4. Visualize responses with analysis and reporting services.\n5. Database storage of uploaded documents.\n6. Responsive form design allowing for forms to display on any device.\n\n--UPDATE This project will now utilize MongoDB as the database backend.', u'title': u'Dynamic Form Creation with MongoDB Backend'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.1 ~ 2016.1', u'description': u'A work in progress.\n\nI was asked to create a highly customizable cross-platform cloud configured monitoring solutions for a Technical Consultant that can be used to monitor and track various systems. (Windows, Mac, Linux, Rasberry Pi etc.)\n\nThe server side system utilizes .NET Core running on Linux system. It incorporates WebAPI, MVC, SignalR, async Rules Engine, and a ReactJS front-end for administration. A repository pattern is currently being used within the API. Data is managed by MongoDB. \n\nOn the client (Windows), a worker service incorporates async delegates to execute scripts (WMI for now, looking at PowerShell) to retrieve server side specified queries.\n\nThe next iteration will be adding support for Linux using a daemon. For cross-platform support, I am considering Python.', u'title': u'Cross Platform System Monitoring Solutions'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.7 ~ 2016.7', u'description': u'An ancient Linux distro migrated to VMWare would no longer print properly. summary: Antoine works within Netflix's Open Connect which develops and maintains its own private CDN, pushing about 1/3rd of all Internet traffic at peak times. Focused on leveraging our infra to build out network acceleration of dynamic traffic, which is one of the top 10 request volume worldwide.\n\nPrevious roles include Solutions Architecture and Software Development at Elastic (Elasticsearch) and MongoDB, two fast-growing pioneers in the open-source big data space. Through those he helped many high-profile companies design and implement large scale Datastore, Search and Analytics systems.\n\nOther experiences includes a long stint in the Content Delivery space, designing and developing one of the largest and fastest Caching and App Acceleration Network. This system was built from the ground up and implemented many bleeding edge solutions at the time: consistent hashing, non-blocking IO, append-only storage, Haystack store, etc. This single system spans across 10,000 servers distributed worldwide in 120 PoPs and is still in production today.\n\nMy recent positions have been a mix of software architecture, programming and team leader. I have always been hands-on, and spent a lot of time actually developing software. Excited to learn new things, help develop kick-ass software, and foster the best in my team.\n

The purpose of the Sales and Quoting Engine is to allow the sales person to add products to quote, get the prices for the selected products and to proceed with the order journey. The engine has a set of core functionalities which include product modelling, data driven and dynamic UI.\n\n\u2022\tThe front-end is based on AngularJS framework\n\u2022\tThe back-end is based on Java technologies (J2EE, Hibernate etc.)\n\u2022\tApplication is developed in a TDD and BDD fashion and follows delivery using Agile/Scrum   \n        methodologies.\n\u2022\tInteractions with the various BT systems are based on: REST, SOAP Web services and data   \n        content is via JSON and XML. \n\n\tAs Software Engineer I was responsible for:  \n\u2022\tRefactoring old SQE system and implementing new key features (front-end/back-end)\n\u2022\tLarge amount of defects fixing\n\u2022\tAttending SCRUM meeting on regular basis\n\u2022\tFollow BDD and TDD practices\n\u2022\tReviewing submissions to source code repositories\n\u2022\tDebugging issues and problem solving\n\u2022\tWorking with team members located in different countries though phones, IM and emails\n\u2022\tPerformance tuning, improvement, balancing, usability\n\u2022\tPresenting ideas for system and UI improvements \n\nKey Technologies used: \n\u2022\tAngularJS, Java, J2EE, Hibernate, Jersey, JavaScript, JQuery, CSS, XHTML, Bootstrap, Testacular, Karma, Jasmine, Mockito, jUnit, Selenium, Grunt, Oracle Database, Web services (SOAP and REST), Apache Tomcat, XML, Subversion, Intellij, TeamCity, Gradle, Oracle SQL   Developer, HP Quality Center, Agile/Scrum development', u'title': u'Telecoms Sales and Quoting Engine'}]
summary: I am Full Stack Software Engineer who thrives to improve every day, learn new technologies and better ways of doing things. Throughout my career I have encompassed all phases of development life-cycle including design, development, mentoring and documentation tasks for small, medium and large-scale IT projects with team sizes ranging from large (40+) to small (sole developer). I started off as a Web Designer/Web Developer and then I moved to Java where I was developing a number of large and complex e-commerce projects but now I mainly use ECMAScript 2015 (ES6)/ECMAScript 2016 (ES7), AngularJS, NodeJS, Serverless, Couchbase, DynamoDB, Docker, AWS and building fault tolerant large scale distributed systems using Microservices Architecture. More information about me and my work can be found on my personal website www.martinmicunda.com or www.github.com/martinmicunda.\n\nSpecialties/Skill Sets:\n•\tCloud - AWS, Google Cloud\n•\tServer side - NodeJS, ExpressJS, NSQ, Grails, J2EE (Java), Hibernate, Groovy, Python\n•\tClient side - ES6/ES7, AngularJS 2, TypeScript, Ionic, HTML5, CSS3, JavaScript, Bootstrap, jQuery\n•\tDevops - Docker, Consul, Vagrant, Ansible, AWS\n•\tTesting - Selenium, JUnit, TestNG, Jasmine, Mockito, Testacular, Karma\n•\tDatabase - DynamoDB, Couchbase, MongoDB, Cassandra, Redis, Oracle, MySQL\n•\tWeb services - SOAP, REST\n•\tVersion Control - GIT, Subvesion\n•\tWeb servers - Nginx, Apache Tomcat\n•\tMethodologies - Agile/Scrum, BDD, TDD\n•\tContinuous Integration - TeamCity, Travis CI, Jenkins\n•\tBuild tools - Gulp, Grunt, Gradle, Ant\n•\tModelling - UML\n•\tGraphic design - Adobe Photoshop \n•\tIDE - IntelliJ, WebStorm, Eclipse

summary: Martha Folmsbee is a Principal Scientist in the Scientific and Laboratory Services department at Pall Corporation, based in Port Washington, NY.  Martha specializes in bacterial and bacteriophage retention testing of sterilizing grade filters.  Her work there includes a special focus on mycoplasma filtration (mycoplasma clearance) and sterile filtration of low surface tension fluids, particularly in relation to specific customer applications.  Martha received a Masters in Environmental Science from the University of Oklahoma in 1997 and later her PhD in Microbiology in 2004.  For her PhD dissertation, she studied the physiology and nutritional requirements of anaerobic growth and biosurfactant production of Bacillus mojavensis and several other bacilli.  In 2005, she was awarded an ASM/NCID (American Society for Microbiology/National Centers for Infectious Disease) Post Doctoral Fellowship to work at the CDC (Center for Vector Borne Disease) in Fort Collins, CO.  There, she studied the physiology and nutritional requirements of Borrelia burgdorferi with a focus toward the development of defined media for the culture of this organism.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2001.1 ~ 2009.1', u'description': u'Tulsa operations had no formal new hire orientation nor on-boarding process. I designed and facilitated bi-weekly sessions for all new hires. We covered all aspects of company policies and culture. I involved HR representatives and department managers as guest presenters. I also designed presented a week-long product and systems training each month.', u'title': u'New Employee On-boarding'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2010.10 ~ 2014.11', u'description': u'The HR department needed someone to assume responsibility for facilitating dozens of Open Enrollment education sessions for U.S. employees in more than 200 locations each year. HR prepared the presentation, I reviewed the presentation each year and made suggestions, then I delivered the presentations via classroom sessions locally, and via instructor-led virtual classes on WebEx. I answered most employee questions about the benefits and open enrollment, and referred unique cases to HR representatives. The HR department realized significant time savings as well as travel expense savings.', u'title': u'Employee Benefits Open Enrollment'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2001.4 ~ 2001.7', u'description': u'The Tulsa Division needed a learning management system and online courses to better meet training needs and delivery. I researched and tested several LMSs and a variety of courseware. I recommended purchase of the Advanced Learning Platform from Intelladon. I also secured and installed two courseware libraries to meet compliance needs, as well as non-required courses to augment employee development. The project was completed 30 days ahead of schedule and $200,000 under budget.', u'title': u'LMS Deployment'}, {u'timePeriod': u'1995.7 ~ now', u'description': u'Every request for a training intervention is treated as a project for both internal and external customers. After meeting with the customer's business partners to analyze the request, timeline, budget, and desired outcome, I meet with SMEs to capture critical learning elements. Using the ADDIE model, I design the instruction incorporating the desired learning objectives and measurements. I prepare the facilitator's outline and detailed guide so the learning intervention can be delivered by other trainers, or myself.', u'title': u'Learning Interventions'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.7 ~ 2014.7', u'description': u'As project leader, I coordinated the activities of our virtual team which prepared new training scenarios; revised workbooks; updated the internal ERP (SIMS) training region; printing, collating, and assembly participant training packets; and recorded \', u'title': u'SIMS Train Refresh'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.3 ~ 2012.3', u'description': u'MRC had an LMS that was no longer supported by the vendor. I managed the project to retire that LMS; secure and deploy a new LMS from a new vendor; manage the change management process; market the transition to employees; administer the new LMS; add third-party courseware content; design and deploy new internal courses; and launch it to all employees. The project was completed on-time and with an annual cost savings to the company.', u'title': u'LMS Retirement and Deployment of a new LMS'}, {u'timePeriod': u'1991.7 ~ 1992.6', u'description': u'I managed the 80-member team of staff and volunteers that put on the organization's Annual Meeting. We secured convention center, meeting facilities, hotels, caterers, A/V vendors, presenters, entertainers, and area sites for entertainment. I secured a headline presenter, Zig Ziglar. summary: I began my working career as a chemist fresh out of college with the WV Air Pollution Control Commission while continuing to perform and teach as a musician.  This brought valuable attributes to my work experience.  I then moved on to Union Carbide and further expanded into musician representation as a union leader, finding my organizational and management skills were in need there.  This led to many roles including stage manager/entertainment director for the Charleston Sternwheel Regatta.  Dow Chemical Corporation saw fit to make me a laboratory information technology site expert which later led to my career as a distance learning coordinator, beginning at the Clay Center for the Arts and Sciences where I was also tapped for a house manager and artist liaison position due to my previous experience.  Union Carbide and then Dow Chemical also trained me in facilitation, team building, Six Sigma and Apollo Root Cause Analysis, among many other subjects.  Finally, I found my niche in distance learning and systems management at the Virginia Department of Health in Richmond where I currently live.\n\nSpecialties: Critical Thinking, Data Analysis, Six Sigma Green Belt, Facilitation, Organization, Personnel Management, Systems Management, Contract Administration, Distance Learning Technologies, Web 2.0 Applications, Audio/Video Technologies, Percussion, Education and Training, MS Applications, Apollo Root Cause Analysis, Problem Solving, Work Process Analysis, Technical Writing, Web Design and Maintenance, Learning Management Systems, Laboratory Information Management Systems, SAP, NIMS/ICS, Blended Learning, Mobile Learning, Adult Learning, ADDIE, Agile Learning Design, Five Moments of Learning Need, Project Management

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2013.5 ~ 2013.12', u'description': u'To augment student learning in CMPT 363 User Interface Design (a classroom-based course which I periodically teach at SFU), I am designing and building a Web-based Course Companion modeled as a performance support tool, not the traditional \u201ccontent dump\u201d of lectures and slides.\n\nIn addition to optimizing page layout to accommodate an ever-growing number of mobile devices, additional user interface elements are presented with the goal of enhancing ease-of-use on larger touch-enabled devices such as tablets.\n\nYou can explore one of my most recent CMPT 363 course companions at http://bit.ly/cmpt363 and also install an experimental Google Chrome App version at http://bit.ly/cmpt363chrome', u'title': u'Multi-device University Course Companion (built using WordPress)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.1 ~ 2014.4', u'description': u'With the positive results of publicly re-envisioning the course materials for my CMPT-363 User Interface Design course offered at Simon Fraser University, I am once again undertaking an open course development experiment.\n\nPlanned for April 2014, my new UBC Continuing Studies course entitled Designing Multi-device Learning Experiences is now being developed in the open, with all course materials to be publicly accessible before, during, and after the course.\n\nMulti-device course companion: http://bit.ly/1kCQO0q\nLearning objectives: http://bit.ly/1jgYd52\nThemes: http://bit.ly/1cW7UCd\nVisual topic map: http://bit.ly/1eyYDjE\n', u'title': u'Open Continuing Studies Course Development'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.2 ~ 2014.6', u'description': u'To provide additional learning opportunities for participants enrolled in my Designing Multi-device Learning Experiences at UBC Continuing Studies, I am designing and building a Web-based Course Companion using Moodle 2.6.x and the Bootstrap Framework.\n\nFor Google Chrome users, the course companion is also available at a Google Chrome App at http://bit.ly/1fPTBvw', u'title': u'Multi-device Continuing Studies Course Companion (built using Moodle)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.6 ~ 2014.12', u'description': u'Seeing the potential of the real-time communication tool Kato.im as a multi-device platform for supporting persistent and private coaching spaces in blended learning environments, I provided the Kato team on-going learner experience feedback and design guidance for this context of use.\n\nI experimented with Kato as a means to provide real-time personal consulting and feedback with various learning contexts, including large university classes, continuing studies courses, and corporate education scenarios.', u'title': u'Multi-device Persistent and Private Coaching Space (using Kato.im)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.1 ~ 2016.1', u'description': u'Based on the positive experience of my students (and myself) when I used the Grav CMS for my Fall 2015 CMPT 363 class, I decided to create an open source project (Grav Course Hub) to help other Web-savvy instructors get started in flipping their LMS with an open and collaborative platform.\n\nGitHub Repository\nhttps://github.com/hibbitts-design/grav-skeleton-course-hub\n\nGetting Started Guide\nhttp://hibbittsdesign.org/blog/posts/2016-02-12-grav-course-hub-getting-started-guide\n\nOn-line Demo\ndemo.hibbittsdesign.org/grav-course-hub/', u'title': u'Open Source Grav CMS Course Hub Skeleton Package'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.1 ~ 2015.3', u'description': u'Frustrated with such issues as lack of support for modular content and rapid content updating (never mind feature bloat, security, and portability) I started to assess modern flat-file CMS's such as Statamic, Kirby, and Grav to build a better online learning space for students in my face-to-face workshops. Key requirements included being open source, multi-device presentation, easier updating for course facilitators, and the ability to add various learning ecology elements such as one-on-one coaching, a curated social learning feed, and a Q&A forum (similar to StackExchange).\n\nAfter choosing Grav (http://getgrav.org/) as my platform of choice, I created a publicly accessible working prototype (hibbittsdesign.com/courses/iy103-w15-prototype/) to further explore design options and ideas. I also created a more generic open source version of that same prototype and made it available for others on GitHub (https://github.com/paulhibbitts/grav-skeleton-workshop-companion-prototype).', u'title': u'Multi-device Workshop Companion (built using the flat-file CMS Grav)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.4 ~ 2015.12', u'description': u'Within the Grav CMS I saw the possibility to create an alternative LMS front-end to improve the student experience while at the same time decreasing my workload in maintaining the on-line component of my Fall 2015 CMPT 363 course. With this approach, the strengths of an LMS (management of courses, assignment submissions, grades, etc.) can be leveraged while also providing a more modern, open and flexible experience for all other online elements of a course.\n\nA fully functioning example of this approach, designed to complement the Canvas LMS for use in my CMPT 363 course at Simon Fraser University, is at http://cmpt-363-153.hibbittsdesign.com.', u'title': u'Alternative Multi-device Front-end for a LMS (built using Grav CMS, to complement the Canvas LMS)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.7 ~ 2016.12', u'description': u'Course hub for the Fall 2016 offering of SFU CMPT 363 (User Interface Design), built with my Grav Course Hub skeleton package (https://getgrav.org/downloads/skeletons).', u'title': u'SFU CMPT-363 Course Hub'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.6 ~ 2013.12', u'description': u'Inspired by the Open Textbook Movement, I am publicly re-envisioning the course materials for CMPT-363, a 3rd year User Interface Design course offered at Simon Fraser University during the Fall 2013 semester. By developing this course openly, I hope to get critical feedback throughout the process from industry colleagues, instructors, and students.\n\nI'm excited by this style of transparent and interactive course development that, I've noticed, has already demanded more from me as a designer.', u'title': u'Open University Course Development'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.5 ~ 2014.12', u'description': u'As Canvas getting more widely used by faculty and students at Simon Fraser University, I wanted to explore its capabilities from both from a pedagogical and learner experience viewpoint. I was also looking for a method to further increase 1-on-1 engagement with students in my large-size classes.\n\nWith a design mindset of leveraging existing capabilities and more graceful content degradation (the Canvas mobile apps do not support all Web page elements), I am utilizing various techniques that do not require a responsive framework to deliver an enhanced multi-device learning experience. The real-time team messaging service Kato has also been integrated into the course companion, with the conceptual goal of providing a persistent and private coaching/feedback space to each of my students.\n\nYou can explore my on-going work with the Canvas LMS at the publicly accessible CMPT 363 Fall 2014 website at https://canvas.sfu.ca/courses/17482', u'title': u'Multi-device University Course Companion (built using Canvas LMS)'}]
skills: [u'User Experience', u'User-centered Design', u'Usability Testing', u'Interaction Design']
summary: Paul is an educator, interaction designer and open source developer. For over 20 years he has delivered design solutions, customized training and practical strategies for organizations such as Hewlett Packard, SAP BusinessObjects, The Canadian Real Estate Association and The University of British Columbia. Combining his professional user experience design skill set with his extensive instructional background, Paul thrives on the challenges of design for learning and experience in today's multi-device connected world.\n\nHe recently published his first open source project to help fellow educators 'flip' their institutional LMS with the Web platform Grav to shift control back to the hands of course facilitators and participants.

The system integrates seamlessly HR applications. ', u'title': u'Online Learning Case Study - Medline Training Academy (MTA)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'Normally, KMi\u2019s eLMS product is centered around courses and the related completion data (scoring, certificates, etc.). Epsilon System\u2019s VITA/TCE Certification Program required a substantial change in the flow of the application: 1) Courses that launch immediately into assessments which are housed inside the same browser window for a seamless experience; 2) Population of an industry-standard IRS certification, or \u201cVolunteer Agreement\u201d, which shows scores on the applicable assessments; 3) Randomly generated assessments from a pool of questions; 4) The ability to \u2018track\u2019 which questions are presented to each user as to not present the same question list on subsequent attempts; and 5) Handle efficiently the use of the site by 25,000 simultaneous users. ', u'title': u'Online Learning Case Study -  VITA/TCE Certification Program'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'Creating an online training program that demonstrated the tools, behaviors, policies and procedures around security requirements provided an exciting, engaging and memorable vehicle for educating the corporate population and remains scalable and accessible across business units, departments and global offices. KMI developed a rich e-Learning module, following a narrative scenario style, that provided that underlying security foundation in a compelling way and that is accessible on\u2013demand, to every employee world-wide. ', u'title': u'Online Learning Case Study - Security Awareness Training'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'KMI Learning applies an eLearning mindset to these short marketing videos to \u201cteach\u201d prospective clients about the processes and technologies that this global marketing company is proposing. We have developed a number of metaphors including the chalkboard, the whiteboard, paper cutouts, the iPad as well as live action video and full bleed photography. They are short and to the point and the language is friendly and accessible. ', u'title': u'Online Learning Case Study - Marketing Presentations'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'With collaboration from BG, KMi helped to develop a fully integrated process for both creating and managing user accounts as well as providing a seamless login experience. Secure WebServices are used that BG calls on-demand to push user updates to the LMS so that when a user is created or modified in the local HR system, the changes are immediately applied to the LMS. eLMS also had a custom grouping structure created that was \u201cmapped\u201d to the existing HR User Organization structure so that all group-assignments could be automated as well. ', u'title': u'Online Learning Case Study -  Easy HR Data Integration'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'KMI Learning developed a rich e-Learning module that utilized custom video. Scenarios were crafted that reflected real-life potential business disruptions. These scenarios provided opportunities for the learner to identify and learn appropriate processes and procedures during these situations. ', u'title': u'Online Learning Case Study - Business Continuity Training'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'KMI Learning took the existing online course, evaluated it for instructional design, graphic and navigational effectiveness and level of interactivity. We then made specific recommendations as to how we would approach each of these elements. The course was then adapted, refined and altered to create an exceptional example of interactive instructional design using engaging testing and scenario techniques. Additionally, we used HTML5 to enable the course to be delivered across platforms, whether PCs, Android or iOS. ', u'title': u'Online Learning Case Study - Human Resources Training'}]

summary: I've spent the past 8 years in both education management and corporate training deployment. Currently, I am the global LMS operations program manager for a Fortune 5 client in Alpharetta Georgia (US). I lead the team that is responsible for all aspects of LMS configuration, governance, and integration with other HRIS systems. We work with our internal customers to assist them in deploying both local and global learning initiatives that impact nearly 60,000 active users across the enterprise. \n\nPreviously, I was a higher education curriculum specialist in charge of migrating traditional classroom based programs into a blended online synchronous program that could be delivered across seven campuses. This was a large undertaking that required my ability to manage multiple stakeholders including I.T., vendor partners, academic advisory boards, faculty, and executive leadership. The project took a little over two years to complete and I lead the project from concept prototype to production. \n\nCompetencies: project management, program development, learning and development, learning technology solutions, business learning requirements gathering and translation into technical scope, change management, instructional and curriculum design.\n

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2013.4 ~ 2013.4', u'description': u'At the end of the day, IT is all about delivering and supporting applications. Thinking out of the box, a business application is nothing but collecting data, reporting it. With a little bit of workflow and integration with other systems makes it powerful. \n\nAppian just makes all of this easy. It offers rapid application development and deployment. It offers out-of-box Mobile and Collaboration capabilities. Appian is our new cutting edge BPM platform at Merck. \n\nI was involved in architecting the infrastructure and standing up the platform in Merck network.\n* It uses Jboss app server, Oracle DB and Kx in-memory Database(interesting).\n* With help from Appian professional services, the installation and configuration is totally scripted avoiding room for errors.\nInvolved in development of smart services to integrate with Sharepoint using Kerberos.\n\nEnjoyed solving challenges like integrating with LDAP(s), automating the installation, deploying f5 load balancers.', u'title': u'Appian BPM Platform'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.8 ~ 2013.8', u'description': u'WebAPIs as the new way to do business in this mobile world. Apigee is a leader is this space and is the Web API gateway for Merck. \n\n* Very excited to be involved in standing up this platform in AWS cloud.\n* Got introduced to a lot of new tools and cloud infrastructure - Drupal, mySQL, Postgres, QPid, Cassandra, ZooKeeper, AWS console to name a few..\n', u'title': u'Apigee Web API Gateway'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.10 ~ now', u'description': u'The goal was to ensure consistent configuration across all AWS VPCs and put an end to the network challenges reported by folks using these VPCs for the first time. The team established standards for VPC - DHCP options sets, Routing tables, subnets and tag standards for these objects. These standards were then scripted and executed in all VPCs. Creation of NAT instances were also automated using autoscaling groups that attach themselves with the routing tables.', u'title': u'AWS VPC Restructuring'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2009.10 ~ now', u'description': u'Merck won the 2012 Brandon Hall Gold award for the Best in Learning Technology Implementations.\n\nI am proud to be part of the winning technology team making this project a success for Merck.', u'title': u'LMS Implementation at Merck'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.3 ~ 2014.3', u'description': u'Implemented mediawiki, catering for a demand to implement a collborative content creation platform. It was a great experience implementing this in AWS with multi-az autoscaling, RDS and automated deployment. Excellent response time navigating thru pages is (thanks to memcache) and easy to use from anywhere with any device, including iPhone. ', u'title': u'Wiki Platform'}]

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2012.9 ~ 2012.9', u'description': u'The framework of most learning management systems is closed, whereas collaborative environments such as Google Drive are built from the opposite perspective. I am leveraging the cooperative nature of OERs within the scope of LMSs to exploit the sharing features. Using the LMS as a gatekeeper, I am embedding content within the scope of the LMS so that students can experience the rich, collaborative learning offered by non-native tools. One critical component of this project is balancing the authentication of each OER so that the student experience is not contingent on having any particular account (other than their LMS), as well as embedding the OER into the LMS so that the entire experience is encapsulated.', u'title': u'Open Educational Resources Integration to LMS Framework'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.8 ~ 2012.8', u'description': u'Our team is tasked with investigating the feasibility of converting instructor materials into eBooks (ePub, Kindle, and iBooks) and distributing them. My role is to design a streamlined workflow model that can be scaled and is also extensible.', u'title': u'eBook Creation, Conversion, and Implementation'}]

summary: Dave is a forward-thinking, tech-savvy innovator. With more than ten years of classroom experience and technology integration, Dave is a visionary in the realm of educational technology. In his eight years as a high school educator and technology coach, Dave was an early adopter of interactive whiteboards, learning management systems and tablet PCs. His successful record of seamlessly integrating meaningful technology into the classroom encouraged him to start a consulting company.\n\nWith three years at Monroe Community College, Dave provides direction and instruction for the online learning department. Institutionally, he helps shape the path of the online education community by providing custom training that targets best-practices. In addition to furnishing logistical instruction and support, Dave also injects pedagogy into his trainings. His active involvement on multiple committees steer the college as it investigates emerging topics such as eBooks, MOOCs, and richer online learning tools.\n\nIn the classroom, Dave provides an empowering and collaborative atmosphere for his students. He teaches a developmental math class that yields exceedingly high success rates. He leverages the technology in the classroom (multiple SMARTBoards, a tablet PC, three learning stations and ANGEL) to seamlessly support classroom discussion and discovery. \n\nStepping outside the box of traditional education, Dave often looks to businesses and other non-educational resources as inspiration of how to further the classroom technology (in order to make students apprehension of content and resources more effortless). He also has a passion for open resources, and is currently involved in two major projects that will provide greater access for students, and more powerful tools for educators.\n\nDave stays informed on current educational technology trends by attending (and presenting at) regional, state, and national conferences.

summary: I am a senior Java developer with over 10 years experience developing Java Enterprise Edition and Spring Framework applications in a variety of sectors including finance, gambling and e-learning. My most recent experience includes the  design of a microservice architectured online lottery platform.\n\nI am a published author, conference speaker, technical editor, Java trainer, kids coding club mentor, and an Oracle Certified Professional in Java SE and Java EE.\n\nI am the co-author of Professional Java EE Design Patterns and a regular speaker at conferences. I have presented at JavaOne San Francisco, Devoxx UK, jDay Sweden, Java Day Lviv, Kiev and Belarus, VoxxedDay Istanbul, JEEConf Kiev and too many more to mention.\n\nI share my passion for Java through courses I have recorded for some of the best-known training providers such as LinkedIn and have published many articles for readlearncode.com, DZone and JavaCodeGeeks.\n\nI was on the panel launch of the microprofile.io at JavaOne 2016, representing the London Java Community (LJC) and a member of the Oracle Technology Network Speaker Bureau and the Jersey Digital Users Committee, and vice-chairman and mentor of an after-school coders club, jerseycoders.com.\n\nI write and present Java EE courses for LinkedIn Learning (Lynda.com) and I am also writing courses for three other established online video training providers.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2013.7 ~ 2013.7', u'description': u'Oracle's popular NetBeans IDE has several features that greatly simplify Java EE development, but with many features and great flexibility, Java developers can become overwhelmed by the options available in NetBeans. This video course provides hands-on instructions that show you how to take control of the environment and make use of these features to make your Enterprise Java application development more efficient and productive than ever before so that you can concentrate on the important parts of your application.\n\nJava EE Development with NetBeans 7 shows you how to develop applications using the most important and latest Java EE technologies and APIs such as JavaServer Faces (JSF) 2.0, Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB) 3.1, and the Java Persistence API (JPA 2.0). The course is a practical guide explaining the various features of the NetBeans IDE related to Enterprise application development.\n\nJava EE Development with NetBeans 7 covers all the major Java EE technologies, APIs, and the rapid development capabilities of the NetBeans IDE such as wizards and keyboard shortcuts.\nWhile focusing on NetBeans features, you will learn how to develop aesthetically pleasing web-based user interfaces using Java Server Faces. You\u2019ll also learn how to take advantage of automated transaction handling and scalability via Enterprise JavaBeans, and how to simplify database access through the Java Persistence API.\n\nBy the end of this course, you will be able to develop Enterprise applications quickly and easily by taking advantage of several time-saving features of Oracle's NetBeans IDE.', u'title': u'Java EE Development with NetBeans 7 Training Video'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.9 ~ 2016.9', u'description': u'For those familiar with basic Java EE functionality, this hands-on lab presents intermediate and advanced Java EE concepts:\n\u2022 JSF features \u2013 beyond the basics, including HTML5 markup, Ajax, templating, flows, and resource library contracts\n\u2022 CDI features \u2013 beyond the basics, including qualifiers, stereotypes, interceptor binding types, and CDI events \u2022 EJB features \u2013 beyond the basics, including interceptors, lifecycle annotations, transaction management, asynchronous method invocation, and timer service\n\u2022 RESTful web service development using JAX-RS ', u'title': u'Java EE: Beyond the Basics'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2015.10', u'description': u'The NetBeans IDE has a great set of free out-of-the-box tools for quickly and efficiently developing all kinds of applications. In this series of lightning talks, you\u2019ll see a range of demos, from working with Gradle to efficiently tuning your application for performance. Come find out about everything NetBeans can do for you.', u'title': u'Lightning Talks: Even More Productivity with Free Open Source Tools'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.4 ~ now', u'description': u'Java Platform, Enterprise Edition Lab 101: An Introduction - HOL1827\n\nFor anyone familiar with the Java language but without direct Java Platform, Enterprise Edition (Java EE) experience, the capabilities and APIs in Java EE can seem daunting. Documentation is helpful, and well-written books can make it easier to come up to speed, but isn\u2019t the best way to learn something to actually do it? This session\u2019s speakers hope to smooth the path for anyone curious about Java EE by offering a gentle, yet useful, introduction to four key concepts:\n\n\u2022 JavaServer Faces (JSF)\n\u2022 Contexts and Dependency Injection (CDI)\n\u2022 Java Persistence API (JPA)\n\u2022 Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB)\n\nUsing NetBeans and the bundled GlassFish application server, the speakers present each new concept with live code and then help attendees complete hands-on exercises.', u'title': u'Java Platform, Enterprise Edition Lab 101: An Introduction'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.10 ~ 2015.10', u'description': u'For anyone who is familiar with the Java language but doesn\u2019t have direct Java EE experience, the capabilities and APIs in Java EE can seem daunting. The documentation is helpful, and well-written books can make it easier to come up to speed, but isn\u2019t the best way to learn something to actually do it? This session\u2019s speakers hope to smooth the path for anyone curious about Java EE by offering a gentle yet useful introduction to four key concepts: \n\u2022 JavaServer Faces (JSF)\n\u2022 Contexts and Dependency Injection (CDI) and JSF validation\n\u2022 Java Persistence API (JPA)\n\u2022 Enterprise JavaBeans (EJB)\nUsing NetBeans and the bundled GlassFish application server, they present each new concept with live code and then help attendees complete hands-on exercises.', u'title': u'Java EE Hands-On Lab'}, {u'timePeriod': u'', u'description': u'Many modern web applications are written with pure HTML5 markup and JavaScript and CSS libraries such as Bootstrap and jQuery. JSF applications are typically written with JSF component libraries, abstracting away HTML markup and JavaScript. Many developers think this is an either/or situation: either work with JSF (giving up control of your HTML, CSS, and JavaScript) or work in HTML5 (giving up JSF functionality such as easily implemented dynamic navigation and seamless data binding between input fields and server-side data). This doesn\u2019t have to be the case! This session demonstrates how we can have the best of both worlds, a pure HTML front end with a JSF and CDI back end.', u'title': u'Integrating JavaServer Faces and HTML5 [CON1784]'}]

summary: Reza Rahman is a long time consultant now working at CapTech. He has been an official Java technologist at Oracle. He is the author of the popular book EJB 3 in Action. Reza has long been a frequent speaker at Java User Groups and conferences worldwide including JavaOne and Devoxx. He has been the lead for the Java EE track at JavaOne as well as a JavaOne Rock Star Speaker award recipient. Reza is an avid contributor to industry journals like JavaLobby/DZone and TheServerSide. He has been a member of the Java EE, EJB and JMS expert groups over the years. Reza implemented the EJB container for the Resin open source Java EE application server. He helps lead the Philadelphia Java User Group.\n\nReza has over a decade of experience with technology leadership, enterprise architecture, application development and consulting. He has been working with Java EE technology since its inception, developing on almost every major application platform ranging from Tomcat to JBoss, GlassFish, WebSphere and WebLogic. Reza has developed enterprise systems for well-known companies like eBay, Motorola, Comcast, Nokia, Prudential, Guardian Life, USAA, Independence Blue Cross, Anthem, CapitalOne and AAA using Java EE and Spring.

summary: Call me naive, but I cannot get over the fact that people right across the world trigger electric currents every day that runs through thousands of code lines I have written and applications I have designed and sold over 11 years. I still marvel at this reality which creates fear within as I hope that they are satisfied. This fear is a great motivator for me, it is my mandate and my drive.\n\nYou see, at my very core I’m a musician and while music is food for the soul, every musician knows that it cannot make an impact without fans. When what one creates triggers a happy face, the magic truly begins.\n\nWhile SaaS is certainly a good thing, I advocate SiaS – Software IS a Service. It’s a service that enables great business ideas – on the cloud or on the ground.\nIn my view, success and effectiveness of software and solution architecture should be measured by the accuracy in which it executes the business logic, by its cost (to develop, to implement, to operate and maintain and to scale up/down) and by the user satisfaction (derived from the comfort and ease of use, performance, reliability, privacy and security). It’s not about technology and tools which are mere means that enable the journey and are not the final destination.\n\nI seek to inspire and to be inspired. This is when we are motivated to accomplish greatness. \n\nSpecialties:\nTechnical leadership, Big Data, Large scale CRM, Enterprise Applications Integration (EAI), Service Oriented Architecture (SOA), Business Process Management (BPM), Content/Document Management (BCM/DM), Distributed Systems, High Availability (HA), Performance Tuning, Production Monitoring, Presale and Delivery of large scale projects.\n\nPrimary Skills:\nBig Data, Java/J2EE, EAI/SOA, Application Integrator/Solution Architect/Technology Evangelist, SDLC System Architecture, Pre-sales

summary: Gerald Loeffler leads and works with technical teams and organisations creating software-intensive systems, particularly in the enterprise integration space. In doing so he draws on his copious project and industry experience, doing whatever it takes to consistently deliver successful projects and products. Depending on organisational context and needs, Gerald enjoys filling the role of software development manager, project manager, Scrum master, team lead, mentor, trainer, architect or data scientist. The technology domain he is intimately familiar with is object-oriented and functional software development on the JVM, often in Scala, for application development as well as system integration, using SOA, microservices, ESB-style and message-based integration and related enterprise software technologies and software engineering practices.\n\nGerald holds a PhD in Bioinformatics, an accredited MBA and an MSc in Psychology. He has attained these certifications: ScrumMaster, PRINCE2 Foundation, MuleSoft Trainer, Apache Spark Developer, Java EE Enterprise Architect, EJB Developer, Java Programmer, Mule ESB Developer, MuleSoft Connector Developer, API Designer with RAML.

An author of a best-selling book, an avid runner, a globe trotter, a Java Champion, and a JUG leader, he is easily accessible at @arungupta.

summary: I believe that the best working place must be one where communication flows - from clients and company direction, to development layers - and where people feel free and involved enough to talk, share and experiment. As Lookatitude CEO I like to think I’m the one who firstly opens the door for such environment, and who ultimately drives change within the company.\n\nMy main functions include presiding all day-to-day operations, being close to clients and teams, helping everyone making the most appropriate decisions.\n\nIn 2012 I had the chance to bring Rocket Internet to Portugal and built its Tech Center in Porto. It was certainly a footprint in Portugal IT history that none can erase: in just a couple of months, me and a small founding team were able to provide the necessary recruitment, training, equipment, infrastructures and assets for more than 140 people. \nThe experience in Rocket Internet Tech Center as Managing Director and CTO sure gave me the opportunity to deal with all kind of international businesses at a large scale, different cultures and timezones. It also matured me to work between many bright, committed professionals who proved that things done fast could be also good.\n\nMy technical background and experience enables me to lead, motivate and support the development teams at any phase - from the initial tech decisions and design iteration, to the assurance of product and service quality. I recruit dedicated professionals and take them to follow the best practices of the industry, thus building surely efficient and reliable teams.\n\nIn parallel, I provide IT consulting - that is, if you need a hand in architecture design, development, team creation or project management, I can help.\n\nSpecialties: entrepreneurship, start-ups, business development, strategy, international business, web and mobile development, agile and lean methodologies, team management, system architecture design, e-commerce, productivity apps

summary: I've worked in web design and application programming since 1996 in a variety of roles from Graphic Designer to Director of E-Learning.  \n\nI am a ‘creativist’: driven by curiosity and a desire to learn how and why everything works.  My curious nature has led to a very wide range of skills including: application programming, Arduino microcontroller programming, web design, graphic design, e-learning development and Internet marketing.  I am an avid user of IoT devices and a fanatic of APIs as data sources.  \n\nMy desire to expand upon my skills led to my return to school for a Bachelor's degree in mobile media programming.  I’m enjoying putting these skills to use and working for an employer who values lifelong learning, creativity, curiosity, exploration of new technologies, and the desire to create impactful, interactive products.\n\nSpecialties: Web design, web-based applications, UI/UX, graphic design, multimedia, e-learning development, video editing, animation, ActionScript, Javascript, jQuery, CSS, HTML5, Responsive Web Design, branding and identity, logo design, print media, and 3D modeling and animation.

summary: I'm an Italian game developer, who led the development of some of the major Angry Birds games. Currently running a small game studio in Italy since 2012, with 11 titles published and more coming out next year. My main goal is to make living out of indie games development. \n\nI'm proficient with the following programming languages:\nC, C++, C#, Java, Python, Lua, Obj-C, PHP, ASP, Lua, Javascript, Boo.\n\nI worked on the following platforms:\nPC, OSX, Linux, iOS, Android, WebOS, Symbian (S60 and S^3).\n\nI'm extremely proficient with the Unity3D engine which I used for several professional and personal projects, mostly for mobile platforms.\n\nI've been working with the following IDE and tools:\nVisual Studio (2005, 2010), XCode, Eclipse, Unity, NetBeans, QT Creator, Adobe Flash CS->CS5.\n\nI also have a pretty good background in shader programming and knowledge about the rendering pipeline.\n\nFinally I'm proficient as well with the following 3D/SFX/Graphic tools:\nCinema4D, Realflow, Blender, Endorphine, PF Tracker, Voodoo Camera Tracker, After Effects, Photoshop.\n\nI speak the following languages:\nItalian (mother tongue), English (Excellent), French (Good), Finnish (Good).\n\nSpecialties: programming, problem solving, 3D modeling, maths, scripting, multitasking, debugging, leading and mentoring.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2014.11 ~ 2014.11', u'description': u'Available free on the App Store: http://bit.ly/AppStoreLayerPlayer\n\nLayer Player explores the capabilities of Apple's Core Animation API, specifically CALayer, CAScrollLayer, CATextLayer, CAGradientLayer, CAReplicatorLayer, CATiledLayer, CAShapeLayer, CAEAGLLayer, CATransformLayer, and CAEmitterLayer. Each class includes several controls to manipulate the properties of the class and observe the effects.', u'title': u'Layer Player'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.8 ~ 2012.8', u'description': u'Screenshots:\nhttp://bit.ly/anglerally\nhttp://bit.ly/anglerallystoryboard\n\nAngler Ally is a universal iOS app for iPhone and iPad that utilizes Core Data, geolocation, JSON data feeds, and additional frameworks to provide a useful interface for fishermen/women to track their success, share photos and details of their prized catches and fishing trips, and pinpoint ideal fishing spots and optimal weather and lunar conditions. Angler Ally is localized in English and Chinese (Simplified).', u'title': u'Angler Ally'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2016.3 ~ 2016.3', u'description': u'Explores reactive programming with RxSwift, RxCocoa, and third-party libraries.', u'title': u'RxSwift Player'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.7 ~ 2014.12', u'description': u'Your Practice. Your Cloud.\u2122\n\nPracticeVine brings the power of cloud computing to traditional client/server-based healthcare practice management and clinical solutions. PracticeVine securely connects to a healthcare practice's on-premise practice management and EMR database to extend the capabilities of that system to the cloud.', u'title': u'PracticeVine'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.12 ~ 2011.12', u'description': u'Patient Web Kiosk for MacPractice was a PHP/MySQL web app that provided a fully-integrated customizable patient web kiosk for the MacPractice suite of practice management and EMR/EDR software, enabling patients of MacPractice clients to complete registration forms, medical/dental histories, etc., before or upon arrival to the office. This eliminated a bottleneck that occurs in healthcare, in which patients are required to arrive well before the scheduled appointment time to complete necessary preliminary paperwork, thus congesting the reception area and posing an inconvenience to patients with busy schedules. Data was stored directly in the MacPractice EMR/EDR module. The design was optimized for use on both desktop and tablet computing devices.\n\nThis project served as an important step in our exploration of integrating with a client-server healthcare practice management and electronic medical records system to extend its functionality to the cloud.', u'title': u'Patient Web Kiosk for MacPractice'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.7 ~ 2012.7', u'description': u'Morel Tracker is an iOS app for the iPhone that utilizes Core Data, geolocation, and additional frameworks to provide a useful interface for morel mushroom hunters to track their success, share photos and details of their prize morels, and pinpoint ideal locations to find morels.', u'title': u'Morel Tracker'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2008.1 ~ 2008.1', u'description': u'MPQ is a PHP/MySQL web app proposal generator for internal use by MacPractice sales representatives. MPQ provides an intuitive interface to select line-item features for the MacPractice suite of practice management and EMR software, and then prepares a proposal including license agreement for the representative to provide to the prospective customer. MPQ replaces a time-consuming and error-prone Excel- and Word-driven approach, and also provides admin and light CRM functionality.', u'title': u'MPQ (MacPractice Quotes proposal generator)'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.7 ~ 2014.12', u'description': u'Screenshots:\nhttp://bit.ly/practicevinepatientform\nhttp://bit.ly/practicevinepatientforms\nhttp://bit.ly/practicevinestaffpatientforms\n\nPatient Forms for MacPractice is built upon our PracticeVine platform, and enables MacPractice clients to utilize their EMR/EDR ability within MacPractice to create forms that patients can complete via any web-connected computer or device. Completed form data is saved directly in the client's MacPractice database. For example, this allows patients to complete forms (e.g., health history, HIPAA acknowledgment, consent for treatment, etc.) from home prior to their appointment. And it allows a MacPractice practice to establish a paperless workflow, e.g., utilizing iPads or other tablet devices to allow patients to also fill out forms while at the practice. \n\nPatient Forms for MacPractice will save MacPractice clients and their patients considerable time and effort in the process of having patients fill out forms. It will also save paper and ink costs associated with printing out paper forms. And it will help ensure accuracy, since required fields, lists of selectable values, date and phone formats, etc. that are used in MacPractice EMR/EDR templates will also be used in Patient Forms for MacPractice.', u'title': u'Patient Forms for MacPractice'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2015.2 ~ now', u'description': u'Chat with anyone, anywhere, anytime. No need to friend, follow, or connect. Find and join chats all over the world or create your own. Includes real-time translation across 90 languages.\n\nDon't let language get in the way of a great conversation. LOC can translate chat messages on the fly between 90 languages. Enable translation in Settings.\n\nChats are pinned to the map where they are created, making it easy to find and join chats anywhere the world. Or start your own chat with just a couple taps. Chats will automatically disappear after about a day of inactivity, but active chats will keep going.\n\nCatch up with friends or make new friends around the world with people who share an interest in the topic of a chat or the location where it was created.\n\nAugmented reality mode in LOC lets you find chats and moods happening right around you right now. Tap the button in the top left of your Nearby list to enter AR mode.\n\nWatch chats to keep up with multiple conversations and quickly rejoin them from your Watching list. Tap the action button in the top right of a chat to toggle watch/unwatch, and swipe left on chat in your Watching list to unwatch.\n\nShare how you\u2019re feeling or mark important locations, and optionally include a comment. Choose from a curated list of dozens of emojis. Mood annotations only last an hour, so if you see one, you know it's fresh.\n\nWhen news breaks, join chats at the location of the event to get real-time updates and pictures from people who are there.\n\nOptionally share your location in a chat so people can find you\u2014especially useful in an emergency.\n\nBusinesses can create chats to attract customers and promote specials.\n\nInvite people to join you in a chat via your social networks, email, text messaging, and more. Tap the action button in a chat and then tap Share.\n\nLOC respects your privacy and keeps your personal info safe. Only your profile picture and display name are shown to other users.', u'title': u'LOC - Location-based chat.'}]

summary: I have over 10 years of experience in the Software Development field as well as teaching and training arenas. Throughout my career, I have been working for a variety of companies, training centers and colleges. I am currently designing, coding and teaching mobile applications for Android and iOS. I have also been working with mobile-friendly Web Applications using a variety of platforms, from .NET to Java to PHP, in Oracle, SQLServer and MySQL DBMSs.  I worked as a Sr. Developer for the United Nations  (UNESCO) for over 4 years. Working for an organization whose ultimate goal is the betterness of the world is priceless. I also worked as the Chief of Architecture at Alliance Information Technology, in Toronto Canada, as well as, an IT Corporate Trainer in Canada, United States and Europe (mainly United Kingdom). I have taught in colleges in Canada and South America. Academically, I hold a BSc in Computer Science and post-grad studies in Software Engineering, Internet Development using Java and Databases. I hold a Bachelor degree in Education focusing in Adult Education from Brock University - Canada, a Master's degree Education (MDE) and MBA from University of Maryland, MD, USA. \n\nSpecialties: As a Software Architect / Senior Developer: \n\n- Statistical Application development and maintenance for International Organization;\n- Risk Management Systems Development (design and implementation)\n\n- Software development using .NET (C#), C++, PHP, Sharepoint and SCRUM\n\n- Mobile applications development for iOS and Android. Design and implementation of mobile-friendly websites.\n\n- Software architecture for Data Visualizations and Web Apps\n\nAs IT Trainer / Professor: \n\n- What students / clients say: \n http://www.ratemyprofessors.com/ShowRatings.jsp?tid=453534\n\n\n.NET, JAVA, Ajax, PHP, Perl, Web Development, mobile application development (introduction to advanced iOS and Android programming), introduction to game programming, SQLServer, Oracle

summary: I am a motivated dependable senior business application developer. I have years of experience in\nmultiple languages and platforms. I have subject matter expertise in manufacturing, healthcare, and\nwholesale distribution. I enjoy what I do and always put in the time required to make the project successful. \n\nHighlights\n\n• C#, Visual Basic\n• Xamarin iOS/Android\n• Asp .NET, WebForms, MVC\n• Windows CE/Mobile, Compact Framework .NET\n• HTML, CSS, JavaScript, jQuery, Ajax\n• Azure Worker & Web Roles\n• WCF & WebApi\n• Excel & Access VBA\n• WordPress, Joomla, Kentico CMS\n• T-Sql, PL-Sql\n• AS400 RPG, CL, DDS\n• Mapics XA, VAI System 2000, SAP\n\nWhy?\n\nI am a passionate coder. My teamwork, mentoring, and problem solving skills are the biggest assets I bring to teams and projects.\n\nMy teamwork plays a huge roll in everything I do. I share my ideas and listen to my teammates. I often become an informal leader on projects helping other developers complete tasks, find the information they need, and help them become successful. \n \nMentoring just seems to always happen when I am around. I am very open to discussing stories and tasks, helping when asked and volunteering to make sure deadlines are met.\n \nMy background is diverse. I have worked on hundreds of projects and with thousands of IT professionals in all capacities. This background and understanding allows me to solve the hard problems. I offered options on how to determine what the problems could be and worked to turn the feature around. I used information and knowledge gained from several past projects to refactor the feature. summary: I am currently the Lead Robotics Engineer at Fetch Robotics where I lead a team of talented and passionate engineers on developing cutting edge robotic solutions. Before that I completed my PhD in Computer Science from Worcester Polytechnic Institute where I worked under the advisement of Professor Sonia Chernova as a member of the Robot Autonomy and Interactive Learning (RAIL) research lab. I was also the community manager and core team developer for the Robot Web Tools project. I received my B.S. in Computer Science with honors from Dickinson College and M.S. in Computer Science from WPI. My R&D interests include robotic learning from demonstration with non-expert users, cloud and web robotics, human-robot interaction, and multi-robot applications. When I am not in the lab, I can usually be found hiking the great outdoors.

summary: Are you working on an interesting project in mobile or embedded devices, or sensor networks? Do you create IoT, telecom, or consumer electronics products? I want to hear from you! I'm interested in technology, implementation, product management, and project management.\n\nI am Series Editor of the Addison Wesley Android Deep Dive series. The first book in the series, by Roger Ye, is Embedded Programming with Android, published August 2015. The second book is Android Concurrency by G. Blake Meike, and the third is Android Database Best Practices, by Adam Stern. I am lead author of the top-selling O'Reilly title Programming Android, which is being updated for a 3rd edition. I am also the lead author of Enterprise Android, published by Wiley WROX in 2013. Enterprise Android is the first book to focus on cloud API-based Android applications.\n\nI run the specialist consultancy Surfaceable.com. We work on mobile software development projects that generalists shy away from: Novel networked applications, projects involving hardware integration, and ambitious application projects. \n\nI was the CTO of Open Mobile Worldwide. I designed OMWW's Android compatibility system.\n\nPreviously I was Chief Architect at D2 Technologies, a voice-over-IP (VoIP) technology provider. There he lead engineering and product definition work for products that blend communication and social media in purpose-built embedded systems and on the Android platform.\n\nAt D2 Technologies, I was the architect of two multimedia, multi-protocol, IMS-capable user interface systems: One that runs in its own user interface framework in a standard Java runtime (e.g. JamVM and GNU Classpath, or Java SE), and one that replaces core elements of the Android communications UI with components that unify IP communication and circuit switched telephony.\n\nRead what I think about mobile software at http://www.oreillynet.com/pub/au/3685?all=yes#Blog and my blog, telirati.com\n\nSpecialties: Mobile user experience, applications, and system programming, device creation, Android, mobile data networks, Search, location-based services (LBS), IMS, Dual mode, VoIP, presence, PoC, IM, SIP, XMPP, Android, J2ME, MIDP, BREW, Symbian, .NET Compact Framework, Open source Java VMs, embedded AWT implementations, UIOne, embedded browsers, CPE telephony, unified messaging, telephony UI and applications, speech processing, NetBeans, Eclipse

summary: I have 4+ years' experience of developing web apps using the MEAN stack and mobile apps using PhoneGap, Angular and Ionic technologies.\n\nI have recently contributed in two world class Angular/Node projects. Within Yottaasys and WIPRO, I have developed myself as a specialist on J2SE & J2EE Web Application development including Java Frameworks (Spring and Hibernate), Bigdata analytics with Fusioncharts, Kibana4, Tableau. And also helped the development of this within the Yottaasys BIM practices.\n\n          > And I was lucky to work with amazing clients such as Shell, Gaminride and RedOn. Colleagues know me as a highly creative developer who can always be trusted to come up with a new approach. I never try to impose my ideas on others. Instead, I spend a lot of time understanding the business logics and the modular programming before suggesting ideas. I can (and often do) work well alone, but I'm at my best collaborating with others.\n\n          > I'm truly passionate about my work and always eager to connect with other developers. While I enjoy all aspects of my job, I think my favourite stage of a project is working with the senior developers or team leads to understand his or her service logic requirements. As we go through that collaborative process, the ideas start to flow and that’s always the fun part.\n\n          > I'm always interested in hearing from former colleagues, team leads, or just interesting creative folk, so feel free to contact me if you’d like to connect.

summary: Joyce Hutter, a puppet designer, storyteller and the artistic director of Strings and Things Puppet Theatre. Using medley’s of styles and mediums, she creates elegant shadow & hand puppets, life-size mechanical puppets and rod and body puppets performing them on stage to entertain both children and adult audiences.  Her mission is to bring puppet theatre performances to life with insightful messages, a social conscience and a sense of humor that enlighten, educate and challenge viewers. \n\nFilm/Television Credits:\n\n•\tHand of God (Season 1, Episode 6) – Lead puppeteer Amazon Studios (For the Rain to Gather)\n•\tNanuq the Film – Stop Motion Puppet Designs \n\t\nTheatre Experience:\n\n•\tThe Sound of One Hand – Shadow Puppet Designer/director/puppeteer (Strings & Things Puppet Theatre) \n•\tThe Seal Maiden – Shadow Puppet Designer/director/puppeteer (Strings & Things Puppet Theatre) Jim Henson Foundation recipient\n•\tSongbirds – Shadow Puppet Designer/Director/writer/puppeteer (Strings & Things Puppet Theatre) Jim Henson Foundation recipient\n•\tThe Crocodile, the Boy and the Kind Deed – Toy Theater Designer /director/puppeteer (Strings & Things Puppet Theatre) \n•\tCarnevil – Shadow & Puppet Designer (Sacred Fools Theater Company) \n•\tWho Speaks for Wolf – Director/writer/puppeteer (Strings & Things Puppet Theatre) Jim Henson Foundation recipient\n•\tThe Comical Tragedy or Tradical Comedy of Mr. Punch – Puppet designer & development team (Rogue Artists Ensemble) Jim Henson Foundation recipient\n•\tThe Story of Frog Belly Rat Bone – Puppet Designer & story development team/puppeteer  (Rogue Artists Ensemble) \n•\tFroggie Went A Courtin’ – Director/Shadow Puppet Designer/puppeteer (Strings & Things Puppet Theatre)\n•\tStrauss Meets Frankenstein!! – Lead designer & puppeteer (Long Beach Opera & Rogue Artists Ensemble)\n•\tSound of Color: Raveonette’s Black/White – Shadow Puppet Designs (Blind Inc., Chris Do)\n\nhttp://stringsnthingspuppettheatre.wordpress.com/ \n\n\n

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2013.3 ~ 2013.10', u'description': u'Hybrid and native Android application development and prototyping using Java, JavaScript, HTML, and CSS.\n', u'title': u'Android Mobile device prototyping'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2006 ~ 2006', u'description': u'WestBeer.com was a web site project for a Glasgow, Scotland based micro-brew, West Brewing. I designed and developed this website using standards oriented practices in a series of HTML pages and minimal CSS to allow for fast loading times.\n\nThe site integrated photographs of the brewing facility and restaurant taken by the owner and brewmaster, Gordon Stewart. Other aspects of the project also included integrating Flash for image slideshow as well as Google Analytics for tracking.', u'title': u'WestBeer.com'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2001.4 ~ 2002.5', u'description': u'Interactive sales design to sell potential; customers on the strength and exceptional reliability of the Brocade switches.\nThis was build an programed in Flash after the animations were rendered and exported from 3D Studio Max. Voice actors and music were placed in post before distribution copies where made.', u'title': u'Brocrade SanSwitch promotional video'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011.3 ~ 2013.3', u'description': u'Adaptu is an online and mobile service that puts you in charge of your financial future.\nDevelopment spanned several platforms and included custom Salesforce.com Apex pages to deliver a secure logged in user experience and secure access to the members personal finance information, as well as a highly customized and secure Wordpress site to deliver financial content from industry experts and the personal finance community.', u'title': u'Adaptu.com'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2001 ~ 2001', u'description': u'This was a companion to the launch of the HP REDA (Real Estate Document Assistant). It was an interactive, Flash-based help app that incorporated product animation for tutorials simulating actual usage of the product that the custom would receive. The interactive pieces work in tandem with technical documentation and links directly to the HP REDA software to make it easy for the customers to find the help they needed and get back into the application quickly.', u'title': u'HP Real Estate Document Assistant Interactive Help'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.4 ~ 2012.4', u'description': u'Verne and I created a Flash quiz to be hosted on Facebook to help engage Adaptu's Facebook page fans with Adaptu.com. Developed in Flash, using AS3, the quiz was integrated with custom landing pages designed specifically for each of the personalities that were associated with the players answers, and then tied back to Adaptu.com with hooks into the registration process of the Salesforce backend.\n\nThe Facebook app was hosted through Salesforce, and then directed towards static HTML5 based landing pages.', u'title': u'Adaptu Financial Quiz'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011 ~ 2011', u'description': u'The website for the Zippo Encore music program began as a .NET, database driven application that supported the US market only, and offered bands and musicians a front door to the Zippo Encore program while also giving visibility to the bands fan-base.\n\nIn 2011 the project expanded to incorporate several countries, and it became clear that existing site wouldn't handle the localization requirements needed. Over the course of 2.5 months, the site was rebuilt using the robust Wordpress platform, incorporating many jQuery interactive enhancements as well as social integration to give both Zippo and their partners easy access to the administrative tools needed to run their programs in each of the supported countries.\n\nThe core structure and Wordpress theme was built on an HTML5 backbone, and utilized popular Wordpress plugins to allow the site to be easily accessible on mobile devices.\n\nOn this project I was the designer and developer, and worked closely with the marketing team and several national and international partners to get the sites localized and launched on time.', u'title': u'Zippo Encore Multinational Music Site'}]
summary: I've been bending the web to my will for more than a dozen years. Whether it's been building enterprise e-commerce sites, customizing Wordpress, writing custom JavaScript or making use of jQuery to fine tune interaction, building and designing for the web is my passion.\n\nIn my grab-bag of tools you'll find Sass, jQuery, Foundation, PHP, Ember and others being coerced into playing nice.\n\nI don't ignore our mobile friends either. I build responsive sites that are designed for a cohesive, singular experience regardless of the size of the screen you use.\n\nAll the while keeping the Social aspect close at hand, working with Marketing teams to incorporate the web presence into social markets to further enhance reach and expand the conversation.

summary: ART\nI'm a Pittsburgh-based artist working in performance art, site-specific installation and public art projects.  My works deal with environmental and social issues.  My projects often involve community interaction and participation.  \n\nFrom September 2006 though May of 2008 I developed a project called The Tom Museum.  The work involved creating a museum in a row house on the North Side of Pittsburgh.  I lived in the house, adding new work weekly.  Visitors and members of the community participated in thematic exhibitions, events and spontaneous collaborations.  The project was an exhibition of the Mattress Factory Museum of Art.\n\nSCHOOL RESIDENCY PROJECTS\n\nSince 2007 I have been visiting elementary schools and after-school programs for artist residency projects.  Projects generally involve a school assembly, the creation of a thematic installation with a core group of students, and a presentation of work for families or the public.  One residency resulted in the creation of work for the new Children's Hospital in Pittsburgh.  \n\nPUPPETRY\n\nI've been performing puppet shows and organizing puppetry events in Pittsburgh since 1999.  I'm currently involved with the development of a new puppetry guild (Puppetry Guild of Pittsburgh), established January 2016.  \n\nSpecialties: painting, drawing, sculpture, museum and gallery exhibitions, site-specific installation, residency programs, curatorial work,  interactive art,  community art events, arts education (children and adults) artist co-op management, puppetry, commission work.

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2012.4 ~ now', u'description': u'Puppet Enterprise is IT automation software that gives system administrators the power to easily automate repetitive tasks, quickly deploy critical applications, and proactively manage infrastructure, on-premises or in the cloud. Puppet Enterprise automates tasks at any stage of the IT infrastructure lifecycle, including: discovery, provisioning, OS & app configuration management, orchestration, and reporting.', u'title': u'Puppet Enterprise'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.6 ~ 2013.6', u'description': u'Allows cellphones to create an ad-hoc adaptive mesh network with routing over wi-fi and bluetooth.', u'title': u'Adaptive Mesh Network'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.6 ~ 2013.6', u'description': u'This is a program that keeps track of running processes, their stats, and their open network connections (though it could be used to track any kind of file descriptor). I created this with the goal of visualizing the interactions of multiple components in a distributed system.\n\nI wrote this draft in a week during my free time. It is implemented in Ruby, uses immutable data structures, depends on ProcFS being present, and uses a polling architecture. The data structures are mildly patterned after Merkle trees in order to have a hash for individual system states and to allow detecting repeat states.\n\nIf I were going to create a production ready version of this, I would use C or C++, ditch the polling, bypass ProcFS and go straight to the kernel for monitoring changes. This would allow creating different modules for different types of operating systems instead of tying it to systems with ProcFS.', u'title': u'Distributed Profiling & Performance Monitoring Tool'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.5 ~ 2012.5', u'description': u'Presented Puppet Labs, Inc. practices around encouraging biking to work. I was a last minute substitute presenter, but no one seemed to notice that I had less than a few hours to prepare or that I had only been at Puppet Labs, Inc. for less than a month.', u'title': u'Portland Employer Bike Summit'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2013.12 ~ 2013.12', u'description': u'Presented a brief talk on the past, present, and future of the internet.
