It also allows binning a series into a set of ranges and applying a statistical function to those ranges.\n\nThis was developed to help prototype visualizations and statistics around reports.', u'title': u'StatisticsJS'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.10 ~ 2012.11', u'description': u'Superpowers lets people use their Android device to experience what it is like to have synaesthesia -- a condition where multiple senses get wired together in the brain and behave almost as one sense. projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2008 ~ 2010', u'description': u'\u2022 An aging socialite grows fur and claws to recapture the attention of her philandering game hunter husband.  \', u'title': u'Bride of Wildenstein - The Musical'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2004.10 ~ 2004.10', u'description': u'\u2022 This multi-media artist talk is customizable to your needs in the class room, conference, or event, as an hour long lecture or as a spring board to a class discussion on life after art school or careers in puppetry\n\u2022 In it, I present images and videos on my work from shows like \', u'title': u'Marsian: An Artist Talk'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012 ~ now', u'description': u'\u2022 \', u'title': u'Object of Her Affection'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2007 ~ now', u'description': u'\u2022 Underground puppet slams are popping up everywhere.  They feature contemporary short-form puppet and object theater for adult audiences, often late at night in small venues, nightclubs and art spaces.  Puppet Slams exist at the nexus of vaudeville, burlesque, and performance art through the intersection of experimental theater, art, music and dance as a viable alternative to the culturally homogenous digital mass media.\n\u2022 This multi-media presentation, on the Puppet Slam movement and the history of the Puppet Slam Network can be tailored to your needs as an to an informal 20 minute teach in, to hour-long lecture, or as the centerpiece of a roundtable discussion\n\u2022 Presented at the The National Puppetry Conference at the Eugene O'Neill Theatre Center (2010, 2011, 2012), The Puppetry and Post Dramatic Conference at UConn (2011), Club Sapien in Calgary (2011), Winnipeg Puppet Collective (2010), The Orlando Puppet Festival (2010), and the National Puppet Festival in Atlanta (2009) and Minneapolis(2007).', u'title': u'The New American Vaudeville and the Puppet Slam Network'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2011 ~ now', u'description': u'\u2022 How does fantasy fuel the way we interact and perform with objects in our daily lives? Why do some people become sexually attracted to objects or fall in love with them? Where do sex toys, fetish, fantasy, and animism intersect? In this multi-media artist presentation, Marsian examines the underpinnings of the suspension of disbelief and looks at how objects are fetishized in everyday life. Marsian has selected clips and images from the margins of what is traditionally thought of as puppetry and object theater for the consumption of theatrical audiences.\u2028\n\u2022 This multi-media presentation is suitable for adult audiences in the general public, and for graduate and undergraduate students. Object/Fetish is perfect for puppetry, art, cultural and media studies and sex and gender departments. It is customizable for visiting teaching, panel discussions, and lectures ranging from 20 minutes to a three hour class, or series of classes with assignments and homework\u2028.\n\u2022 Has been presented  at the Transmodern Festival through MICA in Baltimore (2011), Calgary's Club Sapien (2011), at the Puppetry and Post Dramatic Performance Conference at UConn (2011), and for the Puppetry Department at the CalArts School of Theater (2010)', u'title': u'Object / Fetish: Staging the Suspension of Disbelief in Everyday Life'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2004 ~ 2011', u'description': u'\u2022 Enter the off-kilter world of Linda Carvel, fictitious daughter of a famed New York ice cream mogul. Add a heavy dollop of puppet tragicomedy, a sprinkle of kitsch-surrealism & the result is more than the recommended daily allowance of weird\n\u2022 An hour-long ensemble tragicomedy with actor-puppeteers\n\u2022\xa0Full-length performances have been presented at Venue 13 (Edinburgh) as part of the Edinburgh Fringe Festival and at CalArts Ensemble Theatre (Valencia\n\u2022 Excerpts have been presented at REDCAT (Los Angeles), International Festival of Animated Objects (Calgary), St. Ann\u2019s Warehouse (NYC), Theatre for a New City (NYC), Judson Church (NYC), Transmodern Festival (Baltimore), Mad Cow Theatre (Orlando), Space Ark (Pasadena), Coolidge Corner Theatre (Boston), Comedy Connection (Boston), Atlantic Center for the Arts (New Smyrna Beach), Perishable Theatre (Providence), Carriage House (Providence), and The Park Theatre (Winnipeg)\n\u2022 Ephemera from the show has been exhibited at Grand Central Art Center (Santa Anna), Acorn Gallery (Los Angeles), Guilford Art Center (Guilford, CT), Avalon Island (Orlando), and AS220 (Providence)\n\n\', u'title': u'Growing Up Linda'}]

summary: Marsian is an actor, writer, director, and visual artist who uses puppetry and performing objects in original shows that have toured the United States, Canada, and Europe.   Marsian earned an MFA from CalArts, where he developed “Growing Up Linda” and “Bride of Wildenstein - The Musical”. As a visiting lecturer, Marsian has presented multimedia artist talks at MICA, UConn, Club Sapien, and Bryant University.\n\nAs an arts administrator, Marsian spearheaded the Puppet Slam Network to connect puppet artists, adult audiences, and venues through short-form puppetry by managing grants and creating a strong social media presence.  Marsian serves on the board of UNIMA-USA. \n\nCurrently, Marsian is developing, “Object of Her Affection”, an unconventional love story about a woman who falls in love with inanimate objects and her search for love that is just beyond her reach.\n\nKey Artistic: \n•\tPuppet performance styles include marionette, television-style, table-top, hand, rod, walk-around, costume, pop-ups, mechanisms, live-feed, and experimental styles \n•\tPuppet building , specializing in experimental methods, toy-theatre style, table-top, and pop-ups\n•\tActing: improvisation, comedic characters , and vocal mimicry \n•\tDirecting , dramaturgy, playwriting and creative writing \n•\tExtensive yoga  and movement training, including stilt walking and acro yoga\n•\tFine arts: drawing, sculpture, storyboarding \n•\tDesign and multimedia: Adobe Photoshop, Keynote, iMovie, FinalCut\n•\tProducing touring shows\n\nKey Administrative:\n•\tProject and event organization, planning, and research - both independently and as team support \n•\tGrant writing and administration \n•\tEngaging audiences through social media (Facebook, Blogger, Twitter, Google+, LinkedIn, and Instagram), and list management systems (MyEmma, Constant Contact, Vertical Response, and Mail Chimp) \n•\tMicrosoft Office Suite: Word and Excel \n•\tDatabase aps: Basecamp, Backpack, and Filemaker \n•\tBudgeting and book keeping, including QuickBooks

summary: Born in Los Angeles, Blake Worrell has a professional background that overshadows most in his field today. From high budget film productions to major worldwide performances, his skills in entertainment continue to increase as he reaches new heights with his extraordinary hard work and genuine passion in entertainment.  \n\nBased in Los Angeles, London, Paris and Berlin, with his multilingual skill set, Blake Worrell is building bridges across borders.\n\nAt the age of 13, Blake was welcomed to ILM/Lucas Ranch. At age 14 he sat in and studied Roy London classes with Les Brown Jr. in Los Angeles, observing major actors such as, Brad Pitt.  By the age of 20, Blake was the youngest professional sound engineer in Los Angeles, working full time at Roger Corman Studios (Concorde). \n\nIn 2000 Blake was hired overseas to work in the sound department at Babelsberg/Potsdam for an animated American TV series. He officially moved to Berlin in 2002, and began working as a professional music composer, performer and even puppeteer, making his mark in over 2,000 concerts large and small worldwide. summary: I love bringing emotions out in characters no matter what the medium. So much can be said just in the face of a character alone. Puppetry has taught me that even if your character has no blinks or moveable facial pieces you can still express so much just in the way the head and body are positioned. I love the challenge of getting a person to believe a character is thinking.    \n    I enjoy any project where I can add a sense of humor. I love to make people laugh, whether I’m quoting 90’s movies or breaking into song and dance. I work well in a collaborative environment and enjoy bouncing ideas back and forth throughout the creative process. Working with a fun team creates an enjoyable workplace and ultimately results in a more successful product.\n    I can't wait to meet you and start collaborating on something exciting!

projects: [{u'timePeriod': u'2012.7 ~ 2013.4', u'description': u'My Heart is a Traveler begins as a live theatrical performance and ends as an interactive art installation. The technologies we are exploring include video mapping (onto both moving bodies and mapping moving bodies onto video in real time), the integration of field recorded audio and live vocal mimicry, light/shadow/object puppetry, and human-robot interaction with autonomous flying quadrotors. Layering these technologies with the natural elements of water, dirt, wood, and flour, we transition ancestral themes to modern-day metaphors. Using personal documentaries of our parents\u2019 immigration experience, we invite the audience to join in the adventure and share their stories. Journeying past the shadow-land of technological and biological mergence, join the Robot Immigrants in a land both familiar and foreign, a place where we are all Native Tourists building a society and searching for a home.\n\nApril 27 & 28 at 7 Dunham', u'title': u'My Heart is a Traveler'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2014.2 ~ 2014.6', u'description': u'Now we have a serious crisis that threaten our existence. In our continuous search for convenience and comfort in today's information society, we began to lose our sense of raw reality, our kinetic sense, and our physical sensations. As one characteristic phenomenon, we have a difficult social condition where we can't judge the difference exactly between the real image and the virtual image.\n\nThen, for children and adult, \', u'title': u'Space Dance in the Tube'}, {u'timePeriod': u'2012.2 ~ now', u'description': u'New web series about maniacal and campy vamps set on taking over Planet Earth - one brainstem at a time. Hijinks and mayhem will ensue!\n\nPlease check out and support our production shooting this Spring. do it and we will spare you of our wrath!\n\nhttp://www.seedandspark.com/studio/zompire-vixens-pluto', u'title': u'Zompire Vixens from Pluto!'}]
summary: Nomadic artmaker largely based in NYC, Japan, and various locations by the sea. \n\nFrolicking at the intersections of art/science, visual/performing arts, and nature/technology, my work celebrates the universal interconnectedness of the everyday. Trained in a multitude of somatic, academic, and creative disciplines results in an interdisciplinary cross-pollination expanding boundaries of perception, developing imaginations and uniting them in a shared mind-body field. \n\nI believe in Unity in Diversity; Collaboration is at the crux of all my work. What I create reflects this world within and around me—one that is full of inherent magic and people are free to love and be. The art takes many forms and is always site-specific, both a response and reflection of the environment for which it is made. Like nature, it is always adaptable. I am open to any opportunities that involve healing arts and creative practice. I hope to connect with kindred spirits working toward peace in a unifying world.

summary: I am a technologist obsessed with finding ways for technology and people to work together. In my career, I have been laser focused on helping individuals, teams, and companies focused on working better through optimization, performance tuning, refactoring people processes and more. My career has been focused on learning about how teams work effectively through a combination of people management and technology optimization. I have helped grow teams in small and large companies alike.\n\nThis is more than just technology. It's an ethos. A culture. I like working with teams to help them perform at their best, automating away tedious work, and allowing others to focus on adding business value through features. Engineers work best when they are at the top of their game. I want to help you get there, whatever that means.

summary: NOTE: I receive a _lot_ of connection requests. If you send me one, don't just send the default message. Tell me how we know each other and/or what you are adding me for. I generally only add people I have met or have done business with, unless you have a compelling reason to convince me otherwise.\n\nI’m an IT leader with a passion for everything I do. I started my career in IT in the early 2000’s as a Delphi programmer and over the next decade held many positions as software engineer, DBA, sysadmin, IT leader and everything in between. This gave me a strong technical foundation to build my career on.\n\nIn 2008 I decided to make a long lived dream come true: I started on my own. Initially I was doing freelance MySQL consulting and engineering while traveling the world. Eventually I started hiring more people in OlinData. \n\nI grew OlinData to a micro-multinational lifestyle business with a 100% remote team spanning multiple countries in Europe and Asia. We built global partnerships with some of the world’s leading open source product companies and leveraged those partnerships to do business in 20+ countries including India, Singapore, South Korea and the US.\n\nTogether with my business partner we started businesses in Singapore (2012) and India (2015) gaining a unique amount of experience and understanding about cross-cultural international business. We signed strategic deals with some of the largest companies in the world (see http://www.olindata.com/clients) to provide training and consulting on open source infrastructure management and DevOps. I’m proud to say that until today OlinData is completely self-funded and debt-free.

summary: \t\tI use songwriting, puppetry, story telling, photography, videography and other artful activities to help raise awareness and a feeling of guardianship for all the elements of our planet and beyond. \n\tI began my work in this area as a teacher of teens in danger to themselves and others.  I found that raising interest in the natural world and to teach how all elements of our world are in delicate balance with one another, appeared to raise caring in my students, not only of nature, but of themselves.  \n\tSomewhere in the process of reaching and teaching students with behavior issues I found puppets or they found me.  The one thing that surprises most people is my strong belief that teens are the best audience for puppets.  Teens still like play and they understand the artistry behind puppetry far better than young children do. Anyway when I brought puppets into the classroom  they did what they have historically done, they helped  teach through humor and story. I began to have my students write group  puppets shows, often on ecological themes. I would write at the same time, providing a model for their writing.  We would them make puppets, stage them, video take the show and make titles on flash animation. Meanwhile I kept  I seemed to be gathering  more and more puppets (to date over 600 from all over the world-and some home made. People began to ask me to present my ecological shows and to my surprise I became a puppeteer. \n\tI am also proud of my children's nature relaxation videos, Take 10 with Nature, my community garden book, and over 100 children's ecology songs-can be found on cd baby. I hope you agree that kids ecology is one of the most important issues of our time.\n\t\n

summary: Over 40 years as a scenic designer, technical director, producer, performer, and theatre instructor with numerous performing arts organizations.  \n\nCurrently I hold the position of Technical Director for the TALON Theatre and teach Stagecraft at Santa Margarita Catholic High School in Orange County, CA.  I will mentor student designers and act as faculty supervisor of technical crews for Godspell, West Side Story and the annual Christmas program.\n\n Prior to SMCHS, I was Industry Professional Adjunct Professor at Pepperdine University, working directly with students, staff and faculty to create sets for University Productions.  In 2015-2016 I was Technical Director at San Diego Repertory Theatre, and before that, Master Carpenter.  \n\nFreelance projects include: Puppet Designer, San Diego Repertory Theatre (southern California premiere of Sarah Ruhl's The Oldest Boy); Scenic Designer (Hairspray, Fiddler on the Roof) Young Actors'​ Theatre, Technical Director for Playwright's Project 2014 and 2015 festival, and Scenic Designer and TD for Different Stages San Diego (Lone Star/Laundry and Bourbon, The Hallelujah Girls, The Dixie Swim Club, Burn This). \n\nSpecialties: Extensive background in technical direction, scenic design and construction, actor, puppetry design,  production and performance, technical theatre instruction and touring logistics.

summary: \t\tI use songwriting, puppetry, story telling, photography, videography and other artful activities to help raise awareness and a feeling of guardianship for all the elements of our planet and beyond. \n\tI began my work in this area as a teacher of teens in danger to themselves and others.  I found that raising interest in the natural world and to teach how all elements of our world are in delicate balance with one another, appeared to raise caring in my students, not only of nature, but of themselves.  \n\tSomewhere in the process of reaching and teaching students with behavior issues I found puppets or they found me.  The one thing that surprises most people is my strong belief that teens are the best audience for puppets.  Teens still like play and they understand the artistry behind puppetry far better than young children do. Anyway when I brought puppets into the classroom  they did what they have historically done, they helped  teach through humor and story. I began to have my students write group  puppets shows, often on ecological themes. I would write at the same time, providing a model for their writing.  We would them make puppets, stage them, video take the show and make titles on flash animation. Meanwhile I kept  I seemed to be gathering  more and more puppets (to date over 600 from all over the world-and some home made. People began to ask me to present my ecological shows and to my surprise I became a puppeteer. \n\tI am also proud of my children's nature relaxation videos, Take 10 with Nature, my community garden book, and over 100 children's ecology songs-can be found on cd baby. I hope you agree that kids ecology is one of the most important issues of our time.\n\t\n
